<FIRST>r a PM-SpillYellowstoneTeam     04-04 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill Yellowstone Team,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yellowstone Fires' Troubleshooters Deployed At Oil Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Tanker Spill, Bjt ^By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEWARD, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The disaster expert whose crew saved two
Montana towns from last summer's Yellowstone firestorms now is
plotting to defend another national park against the largest oil
spill in U.S. history.
   ``Our mission is to find out where the marine wildlife and sea
birds are today, then set priorities so the oil that kills them can
try to be contained,'' said Dave Liebersbach, a veteran Bureau of
Land Management troubleshooter whose title is incident commander.
   Liebersbach's team has found similarities here to Yellowstone.
   ``In Yellowstone we put firefighters on the ground. Here we're
providing logistics for Ph.D. biologists who we're handling as a
very intelligent resource, very delicately. If they need a boat we
get one, if they need a ham sandwich we make one. What they need we
try to provide,'' Liebersbach said.
   The tanker Exxon Valdez hit a reef near Valdez on Good Friday
night and bled 10.1 million gallons of crude oil into Prince
William Sound. Huge fingers of the slick are now extending westward
through Montague Strait toward the 660,501-acre Kenai Fjord
National Park.
   The oil was less than 10 miles offshore from Seward on Sunday
night, but calm seas and gentle breezes made its future course
unpredictable.
   ``It's possible it could miss everything here,'' said
Liebersbach, ``but to ignore it would be totally negligent. Knowing
what we do, we have to prepare to mitigate it.''
   Created by the Alaska National Interest Lands Conservation Act
of 1980, the new national park is a necklace of bird rookeries,
tidal pools, and whale playgrounds draped along 610 miles of the
Kenai Peninsula's eastern coastline.
   Located 100 air miles southeast of Anchorage, most of the park
can be reached only by floatplane or boat. It attracted fewer than
60,000 hardy tourists last year, and is more hospitable to its
critters than its visitors.
   Among the animals who cavort in the midnight sun amid the rugged
grandeur of the park's coves and inlets are many endangered
Humpback and California gray whales, a few endangered Fin whales,
and otters, sea lions, and seals.
   Liebersbach is in charge of a 40-member-and-growing team of
pilots, support personnel, and environmental experts drawn from
Alaska agencies, the U.S. Forest Service, National Park Service,
Bureau of Land Management, and U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service.
   Although Liebersbach's home is Fairbanks, he was at a meeting of
the government's 18 Class 1 disaster incident commanders in Reno,
Nev., when his permanent eight-man core unit was activated at the
request of the park service.
   ``The last time we were together was Yellowstone, on the Storm
Creek fire,'' said Liebersbach. ``We didn't expect to see each
other again until summer.''
   Last August and September, he was boss to several thousand
civilian and military firefighters who faced down 200-foot walls of
flame threatening to incinerate Silver Gate and Cooke City, Mont.
The two towns were saved but Yellowstone's fires charred nearly one
million acres.
   Marvin Robertson, the team's planning chief, said the spill
``woke us all up and got us ready for the year. It looks like it
could be a long one.''
   The team set up shop in a small house near park headquarters in
Seward. Up went the topographical maps. In came the photocopy
machine, typewriters, and coffeemaker. Seven phone lines now ring
constantly from dawn until midnight.
   ``An oil slick is like a fire line, it just keeps moving,'' said
Robertson.
</TEXT>
