<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 0048EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-AmazonRainForest     04-04 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Amazon Rain Forest,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ecology Group Warns Sarney He Responsible for Amazon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of leading Latin American writers,
artists and scholars has told President Jose Sarney of Brazil he
will bear ``historical responsibility'' for continued destruction
of the Amazon rain forest.
   ``We believe that the historical responsibility for destroying
the Amazon jungle is very great, and future generations of Latin
Americans will not forgive it if everything possible is not done to
avoid it,'' the Group of 100 warned un a letter, which was released
Monday.
   Sarney has rejected international criticism of the deforestation
of the Amazon basin as foreign interference in Brazilian affairs.
   The Group of 100 declared that ``to invoke national sovereignty
to justify crimes against nature _ like those being committed
against one of the richest and most complex ecosystems on Earth _
appears puerile and dishonest to us.''
   The group condemned ``criminal burning that razes millions of
acres of tropical forests, the clearing of the jungle for
colonization and transnational agriculture'' and ``the
extermination of ethnic groups whose members are hunted down by the
`modernizers' of agriculture to take over their lands.''
   The letter, signed by 28 leading Latin American writers and
artists, was delivered to the Brazilian Embassy by group president
and poet Homer Aridjis.
   Among its signatories are Carlos Fuentes of Mexico, Gabriel
Garcia Marquez of Colombia, Juan Carlos Onetti of Uruguay, Isabel
Allende, widow of the slain Chilean President Salvador Allende,
Mario Vargas Llosa of Peru and Ernesto Sabato of Argentina.
</TEXT>
