<FIRST>r i PM-Cuba-Museum     04-04 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cuba-Museum,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuban Security Museum Displays Relics Of War With CIA</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVANA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Museum of State Security displays the scorched
tail of a small plane, plastic explosives, a tattered 2506 Brigade
armband, assault rifles, a radio transmitter and a battered water
can with a label in English.
   The artifacts are part of what Cuba presents as its 30-year
struggle with the Central Intelligence Agency and dissident Cubans
accused of trying to kill or overthrow President Fidel Castro.
   The museum, which opened this weekend, occupies a refurbished
mansion in a once-wealthy neighborhood whose villas now house
embassies or government offices.
   In a small plaza visible from the street, a power boat with a
black hull, sea blue decks and Florida markings looks at first
glance like a private plaything in a country where such luxuries
are rare.
   Closer examination reveals that the boat, driven by powerful
Mercury engines, has heavy machine guns mounted fore and aft.
   Octavio Cruz, the clean-cut, graying guide at the museum, said
the vessel made coastal raids until it was captured by agents of
the State Security Department, Castro's special police force.
   Maps inside the museum are dotted with sites of ``imperialist
aggression,'' a battle plan for the U.S.-sponsored Bay of Pigs
debacle in 1961. There are a rogue's gallery of people accused of
trying to kill Castro and relics of what is portrayed as a secret
war on the regime he established 30 years ago.
   At the center of an upstairs room, in its own sealed plexiglas
case, is a three-volume set of the yellow-bound proceedings of a
Senate Intelligence Committee investigation of 1975.
   The committee investigation disclosed bungled CIA attempts on
Castro's life _ once with an exploding cigar, for instance, and
another time with poison powder that supposedly was scattered on
the leader's clothing but did no harm.
   Asked why the evidence was not displayed, Cruz first said,
``There have been so many attempts they couldn't all be put in the
museum.'' Later, he said he wasn't sure the evidence still existed.
   He led the visitors into the Hall of Martyrs, lined with
portraits of 88 agents of State Security described as having died
fighting the CIA, Cuban exiles, counterrevolutionaries or other
enemies. A brass plaque beneath each portrait gave the details.
   Cruz said the museum's purpose ``is to bring to the people a
cultural identity and to transmit a story for all visitors
fundamentally about a fight and the atrocities carried out against
us, and the aggressions of the last century.''
   Asked why a meseum opened now to depict events of the 1960s,
Cruz said: ``The opportunity is now'' and, in the past, ``the
revolution had other priorities.''
   In first room of the museum are a giant photo of the U.S. Marine
landing at Santiago de Cuba in 1898, during the Spanish-American
War, and a huge copy of a letter written in 1895 by Jose Marti,
patron saint of Cuban independence. Marti said the United States
would ``continue to use Cuba as a base to extend its power into the
Caribbean.''
   The only other exhibit in that room is an enlargement of a
letter Castro wrote in 1958, from a camp in the hills, telling his
longtime friend and secretary Celia Sanchez: ``They're firing
rockets at us in the mountains. Mario was killed, and the Americans
will pay dearly for this.''
   He also wrote, just a year before gaining power: ``It's becoming
clear to me that this war will go on much longer. It will have to
go on against the Americans.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
