<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     04-04 0883</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,880</SECOND>
<HEAD>Land Values in Midwest Were Stable Despite Ravages of Drought</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Agriculture Department economist says
federal emergency aid ``probably helped stabilize land values in
the Midwest'' last year after drought ravaged crops across the
region.
   Gregory Hanson of the department's Economic Research Service
said that surveys by the Farm Credit Banks of St. Paul, Minn.,
indicate that land prices did not decline in Michigan, North Dakota
or Wisconsin in June through November last year.
   Other surveys indicate that farmland prices rose in the Corn
Belt in 1988, he said. Real estate is the main source of loan
collateral for farmers.
   ``While drought assistance has helped stabilize the agricultural
economy, the USDA estimates that 10,000 to 15,000 commercial farms
faced loan repayment problems due to crop losses,'' Hanson said.
``These stressed farmers represent 1.5 percent to 2.5 percent of
all commercial farms.''
   The Disaster Assistance Act of 1988 was signed into law last
Aug. 11 as the scorching summer drought was still at its peak. The
law provided up to $3.9 billion in federal aid and other measures
to help farmers recover.
   Hanson, writing in the April issue of Agricultural Outlook
magazine, said that federal disaster assistance may turn out to be
less than foreseen last fall ``because crop losses were smaller
than expected.''
   ``Also, qualification for drought assistance was based on the
whole-farm average yield for each crop, rather than on a
field-by-field basis,'' he said. ``The averaging-up of yields,
where good fields offset poorer fields, excluded some farmers from
qualifying in areas with scattered rainfall.''
   Even so, Hanson added, the combination of drought assistance and
federal subsidized crop insurance ``has permitted thousands of
farmers in hard-hit states to survive last year's bad weather with
less financial suffering than had been anticipated.''
   Hanson said a full assessment of federal drought aid and
insurance benefits cannot be completed until all payments and
indemnities have been disbursed. But preliminary figures show those
had ``substantial stabilizing effects'' in the hardest-hit drought
areas.
   But on Capitol Hill there have been grumblings that USDA has
mishandled 1988 relief and has ignored drought conditions now
prevailing in parts of the Great Plains, notably in Kansas and
parts of Texas.
   Department officials testified that more than 558,000 producers
had received disaster payments and emergency feed assistance
amounting to more than $2.7 billion nationally.
   In his report, Hanson said that as of early February, more than
$2 billion in drought payments and almost $1 billion in federal
crop insurance benefits had been paid to farmers in the top eight
states.
   Farmers in Montana and the Dakotas _ where more than 80 percent
of the commercial farms were in drought-stricken counties _ have
received nearly a third of the drought payments made so far.
   Benefits paid to the eight states as of early February, in
millions of dollars, included drought aid in the first column,
federal crop insurance in the second, and the total in the third:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Ill.   207   97   304
Iowa   168   128   296
Minn.  242   60   302
Mont.  149   95   244
N.D.   332   187   519
S.D.   148   49   197
Texas   90   28   118
Wis.   120    7   127
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American ketchup makers and other tomato
processors will have a Japanese competitor bidding for farmers'
crops, says an Agriculture Department report.
   The Kogome Co. Ltd., Japan's largest tomato processing company,
announced it will open a $20 million plant next year in Los Banos,
Calif., to manufacture tomato products and fruit juice beverages.
   ``Most, if not all, of the manufactured products likely will be
exported to Japan to take advantage of future market openings for
tomato and fruit drink products achieved under a recent U.S.-Japan
agreement,'' the department's Foreign Agricultural Service said.
   The agreement gives U.S. exporters of 11 product categories,
including processed tomato products and fruit juices, greater sale
opportunities in Japan.
   Bryand H. Wadsworth, U.S. agricultural counselor in Tokyo, said
the plant will produce institutional-size containers tomato ketchup
from tomato paste bought from local manufacturers.
   In addition, he said, the plant will produce retail-size
``fruit-juice added'' drinks such as orange and apple in both
carbonated and non-carbonated form.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says the U.S. dry
bean situation has ``completely reversed'' itself from a year ago
because of higher prices prompted by the 1988 drought.
   By January, the average farm price of dry edible beans was
$29.60 per hundredweight, up from $13.40 a year earlier.
   Price increases were the greatest for beans hit hardest by the
drought. For example, grower prices for navy beans in the week of
Jan. 24 averaged $32 per hundredweight, compared with around $10 in
January 1988, the department's Economic Research Service said.
   Total U.S. output of dry beans dropped 26 percent to 19.2
million hundredweight last year, the agency reported.
   ``The sharpest decreases in production were for red kidney,
pintos and navies, the beans grown in states with less
irrigation,'' the report said.
   Another price factor is an improved outlook for bean exports
because of poor harvests in several major importing countries,
including Mexico and Japan.
   ``Domestic demand for beans could also improve this year because
of recent media attention and industry promotional efforts,'' the
report said. Beans are a nutritious food item and are noted for
their fiber content.
</TEXT>
