<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 0209EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ComputerVirus     04-04 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Computer Virus,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cornell Says Ethics, Not Security, The Key to Preventing Computer
Worms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM KATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethics, not increased security, are the best
defense against computer ``worms'' like the one unleashed last fall
by a Cornell University graduate student, a school official said.
   A special university commission reported Monday that Robert T.
Morris Jr. acted alone and with ``reckless disregard'' on Nov. 2
when he launched a debilitating program into the Internet network,
causing thousands of computers around the country to clog and
overload.
   The commission concluded that Morris did not intend for the worm
to destroy data or files, but that he did want it to spread widely.
   It said the program was not technically a ``virus'' _ a program
that inserts itself into a host program to propagate _ but was a
``worm,'' an independent program that replicates itself once placed
in a computer system.
   Release of the worm was not a ``heroic event that pointed up the
weaknesses of operating systems,'' contrary to Morris' claim, the
commission wrote. The panel also denied that Morris was a genius
for creating the worm. It said although the worm was technically
sophisticated, it could have been created by many students.
   In fact, Morris' ``juvenile act'' did little to provide insights
into the already well-known security flaws of the Internet system,
a national research network used by universities, industry and
government, said M. Stuart Lynn, Cornell's vice president of
technologies.
   Lynn and Cornell Provost Robert Barker said the incident's
greatest impact was the breach of trust it had caused among
researchers who use the network. However, both cautioned that
employing drastic security steps was not a solution to prevent
similar incidents.
   ``Violations of such a trust cannot be condoned,'' said Lynn.
``A community of scholars shouldn't have to build sky-high walls in
order to protect a reasonable expectation of privacy _ particularly
when such walls would impede the free flow of information and
ideas.''
   Lynn added that it's unlikely any security steps could guarantee
an impenetrable system ``in a community of individuals possessed of
all the knowledge and skills required to scale the highest
barriers.''
   Instead, the Cornell officials stressed the need for improved
awareness of computer ethics, said Lynn.
   ``I don't think one can ever feel confident by putting bigger
and tighter locks on the door,'' said Lynn. ``That's why it's
important to stress ethical considerations.''
   Morris, who is on a leave of absence from school, declined to be
interviewed by the commission, which was left to speculate as to
the reasons he created the ``worm.''
   The panel made no recommendation about disciplinary action
against the first-year graduate student in Cornell's doctoral
computer program. Barker said Morris' case would be reviewed by a
panel of graduate students and faculty that could permanently bar
him from the university.
   Morris, 23, of Arnold, Md., remains under investigation by a
federal grand jury in Syracuse and the Justice Department in
Washington, D.C.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890404-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 0210EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Opera     04-04 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Opera,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Billy Budd Revived at Met</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The expanding shipboard set that dominates
Benjamin Britten's ``Billy Budd'' at the Metropolitan Opera is so
spectacular that the work would almost be worth reviving just for
the chance to see it in action.
   Luckily, there was also quite a bit of a musical nature to hold
the interest Monday night when the company presented the John
Dexter production for the first time in several seasons.
   Herman Melville's classic tale revolves around three sharply
drawn characters who inspired some of Britten's most memorable
music: Billy Budd, the good and handsome sailor; John Claggart, the
evil master-at-arms who is bent on his destruction; and Edward
Vere, the philosophical captain who reluctantly sends Billy to his
death to preserve law and order.
   Two of the three roles were in excellent hands. Baritone Thomas
Allen made a first-rate Billy, conveying first his youth and
enthusiasm and later his pathos when, chained and awaiting
execution, he sings a haunting ballad. As Vere, tenor James King
made a moving figure, especially in the prologue and epilogue where
he appears as an old man musing about the distant past.
   Another composer might have made Billy a tenor, the vocal part
traditionally associated with a young hero. But in Melville's
ambiguous narrative, Captain Vere may be the real hero, and
Britten's decision to make him the tenor seems to acknowledge this.
   The malevolent Claggart is portrayed more conventionally as a
deep bass. Jan-Hendrik Rootering looked sinister enough, but his
good-sized voice lacked the bite and menace that James Morris
brought to the part when the production was new.
   The men's chorus, which has a major role in the all-male cast,
performed lustily, and the orchestra played well under conductor
Thomas Fulton.
   But it was above all the set, designed by William Dudley, that
commanded admiration. With the aid of the Met's elaborate system of
stage elevators, the ship expands and shrinks like an accordion as
the action shifts from the main-deck, to the captain's cabin, to
the quarter-deck, to the lower gun-deck.
   The effect is fittingly to make the ship itself the dominant
image in the opera, a microcosm where the battle between good and
evil is played out to its tragic conclusion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890404-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 0211EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-JuvenileExtradition     04-04 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Juvenile Extradition,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Penalty Opponents Pressing D.C. Mayor To Block Extradition
Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of capital punishment are pressing
District of Columbia Mayor Marion Barry to block the extradition of
a juvenile sought by Alabama until he's assured the youth won't
face the death penalty.
   But Barry so far has refused to interject himself publicly into
the extradition case involving a 17-year-old black youth charged in
the May 1988 firebombing of a Gadsden, Ala., apartment. A
14-month-old black child died in the fire.
   Rick Blake, the mayor's deputy press secretary, said Barry would
not respond to pleas, made at a Monday news conference by a group
of death penalty opponents and church leaders, that he refuse to
honor Alabama's extradition request unless state authorities
guarantee the youth, identified by the initials O.M., will not be
charged with a capital crime.
   While Barry has remained silent, lawyers for the district
government have supported Alabama's bid to extradite the youth, who
has been held in Washington since his arrest in December on a
fugitive warrant from Alabama.
   Superior Court Judge Stephen F. Eilperin last week granted
Alabama's extradition request, but he stayed his order until today
to allow the youth's attorneys to appeal. An appeal was filed
Friday with the District of Columbia Court of Appeals, which
extended the stay until April 10.
   Alvin J. Bronstein, director of the National Prison Project of
the American Civil Liberties Union, said Barry can supersede the
court ruling and block the extradition until Alabama promises not
to seek the death penalty.
   Bronstein charged that Barry, by allowing his government to
support the extradition, has ``forgotten the values that motivated
him 25 years ago'' when he worked for racial justice in the South
as a member of the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee (SNCC).
   Bronstein, who was an attorney for SNCC members during the civil
rights movement, said he was issuing ``a personal plea to the mayor
... don't send this youngster back without the kinds of guarantees
that will ensure us that he won't be killed in jail, that he will
be treated in a decent fashion and that he won't face the death
penalty.''
   If Alabama refuses to make such guarantees, then Bronstein said
the district should release the youth, because there are no other
outstanding charges against him.
   O.M.'s attorneys contend he cannot get a fair trial from the
white authorities of Etowah County, Ala., because of their
long-standing vendetta against his family. Both the boy's father
and uncle died while in police custody.
   Another of the boy's uncles has been charged with murder and
arson in connection with the 1988 firebombing. O.M. is charged
under juvenile law as an accessory to the firebombing, and thus is
not facing an immediate threat of the death penalty.
   But Alabama authorities have refused to rule out the possiblity
that he might be tried as an adult and subjected to the death
penalty.
</TEXT>
