<HEAD>Eds: SUBS first item to DELETE INCORRECT reference to first official
nut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hazelnut rolled past the giant chinquapin
on the way to becoming the official state nut.
   The Senate Government Operations and Elections Committee on
Monday passed the hazelnut on to the full Senate for consideration.
   The only person to testify in favor of the giant chinquapin, a
cousin of the chestnut, was John Pope, a Salem seed company owner
and nature lover who admitted that legislators might consider his
favored nut ``squirrel food.''
   He was no match against 10 members of the Slick Chick Camp Fire
Group from Clackamas Elementary School and lobbyists for the $20
million hazelnut industry.
   ``Indians and pioneers ate hazelnuts,'' said troop member Sarah
Stitt.
   Only one committee member voted against the hazelnut, also known
as filberts.
   ``I'm not convinced this was an issue we need to address,'' said
Sen. Dick Springer.
