<FIRST>r w PM-CongressionalMilestone     04-04 0698</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congressional Milestone,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Congress Had First Quorum 200 Years Ago</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress this week celebrates a curious but
important milestone: The 200th anniversary of the days on which the
first House and first Senate achieved a quorum and were finally
ready to begin the work of the new nation.
   The House marks the occasion today, April 4, three days after
the actual April 1 anniversary. The Senate celebrates on Thursday,
April 6, the actual date of its first working quorum.
   Commemorative postage stamps will be issued honoring the
bicentennials of both houses.
   The Congress established under the Constitution first convened
in New York City on March 4, 1789.
   But the absence of the required majority plus one prevented the
two chambers from getting down to business.
   On that first day only 13 of the 59 House members and only eight
of the 22 senators were in attendance.
   Election complications, bad weather, muddy roads and just plain
sloth get the blame as causes for the delay.
   The journal of the House noted with monotonous regularity that
``a quorum of the members not being present, the House adjourned.''
   Congress under the discarded Articles of Confederation had been
noted for absenteeism and near paralysis, and many feared history
was about to repeat itself.
   ``We lose credit, spirit, everything,'' Rep. Fisher Ames of
Massachusetts wrote to a friend in Boston. ``The public will forget
the government before it is born.''
   The senators who had managed to reach New York wrote to their
absent colleagues: ``We apprehend that no arguments are necessary
to evince to you the indispensable necessity of putting the
government into immediate operation and, therefore ernestly request
that you will be so obliging as to attend as soon as possible.''
   George Washington had been elected the nation's first president,
but could not enter office until the Senate achieved a quorum and
met to count the ballots of the Electoral College.
   From Mount Vernon he grumbled that senators and House members
were in a state of ``stupor or listlessness.''
   But eventually the required numbers assembled.
   The House, counting its first quorum on April 1 _ April Fool's
Day some have noted _ elected Frederick Augustus Muhlenberg of
Pennsylvania as its first speaker.
   And Fisher Ames, much mollified now that work could begin, said
he was pleased with his new colleagues.
   While there were few ``shining geniuses,'' he said, there were
many who had ``experience, the virtues of the heart, and habits of
business.''
   On April 6 the Senate counted its first quorum.
   The first order of business: Counting the votes of the electors
and dispatching messengers to inform Washington and John Adams that
they had indeed been chosen president and vice president.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The postage stamp honoring the Senate will display the gilt
shield and eagle suspended over the presiding officer's chair in
the Capitol's Old Senate Chamber, in use from 1810 to 1859.
   The stamp honoring the House of Representatives features the
fanciful ``Car of History,'' a winged marble chariot which, since
1819, has borne the carved figure of Clio, the muse of history,
over the floor of the Old House Chamber, now Statuary Hall.
   Rep. John Quincy Adams, who served 17 years in the House after
his single term as president, was inspired in 1840 to dedicate a
poem to the muse who is shown recording in a book the events
unfolding on the floor of the legislative body below.
   Often at odds with his colleagues and irritated by their
conduct, Adams paid tribute to the muse for putting up with the
``wordy war'' conducted by the members.
   There was wit, there was wisdom, he acknowledged. But there was
also ``the conflicting jar of ranting, raving parties, day and
night ...''
   Adams concluded:
   ``Oh! Muse historic _ in thy march sublime
   Still urging onward on the wheels of time.
   Canst thou not whisper to the chosen band
   But for one day to calm their senseless rage,
   And let thy volume bear one blessed page
   Of deeds devoted to their native land.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Lawrence L. Knutson covers Congress and its lore
for The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890404-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 0241EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-S&amp;Ls     04-04 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Thrift Plan Would Water Down Bush Bailout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Banking Committee's proposal for
solving the savings and loan crisis waters down key sections of
President Bush's reform plan but also hands industry lobbyists
several defeats, according to a committee document.
   The proposal would make a number of changes sought by S&amp;L
executives regarding deposit insurance, regulatory structure and
capital requirements.
   However, other provisions, such as those restricting commercial
real estate lending and strengthening the Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp., are less favorable to the industry than Bush's Feb. 6
proposal.
   The document, obtained Monday by The Associated Press, was
prepared for closed-door meetings of the Senate panel starting
today. It outlines the recommendations of the staff of Sen. Donald
W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich., the committee chairman.
   The panel plans three private sessions this week in preparation
for public bill-drafting sessions beginning April 13. Meanwhile,
Democrats on the House Banking Committee plan a private strategy
session Wednesday, before the first open meeting on Thursday.
   Among the victories for the S&amp;L industry in the Senate proposal
are recommendations to:
   _Equalize deposit insurance premiums for banks and S&amp;Ls by the
year 2000. The Bush proposal, after a series of changes, would
charge S&amp;Ls 18 cents per $100 for their insurance versus 15 cents
per $100 for commercial banks.
   _Give the Treasury Department less control over S&amp;L regulators
than proposed by the administration.
   _Allow some weak S&amp;Ls to grow modestly after the June 1991
deadline for meeting tougher capital standards. Bush would prohibit
S&amp;Ls from expanding if their owners did not meet stricter
requirements on how much money they must put up to back their
institutions' loans. The Senate proposal also would give S&amp;Ls twice
as long, 20 years versus 10 years, to meet tougher standards on a
portion of capital known as goodwill.
   _Prohibit the government from hurting regional real estate
markets by selling repossessed property from failed S&amp;Ls too
quickly. It would add real estate expertise to the new government
board overseeing S&amp;L bailouts by expanding the board from three
government officials to five members, including two private
business persons.
   As expected, the Senate proposal would count S&amp;L rescue spending
``on-budget,'' as opposed to the complex administration plan for
keeping $50 billion in S&amp;L spending out of the budget deficit.
   Meanwhile, in a separate development, commercial banks sought
guarantees that they would get refunds of deposit insurance
premiums once the bank insurance fund regained its full strength of
$1.25 in reserves for every $100 in deposits, up from a depleted 80
cents per $100 now.
   The administration has said rebates could begin by the
mid-1990s, but the Bush bill allows regulators to decide whether or
not to offer them and FDIC Chairman L. William Seidman wants that
flexibility until the insurance fund reaches a level of $1.65 per
$100. Banking groups, led by the American Bankers Association, want
to make rebates automatic after the fund reaches the $1.25 level.
   In at least three respects, the Senate proposal would hand a
defeat to S&amp;L lobbyists:
   _Although the Senate would allow the S&amp;L regulatory agency, the
Federal Home Loan Bank System, greater independence from the
administration, it would transfer some of the bank system's most
important powers, such as setting capital and accounting standards
and supervising state-chartered S&amp;Ls, to the FDIC.
   _Current law and the administration plan permits S&amp;Ls to invest
as much as 40 percent of their assets in commercial real estate.
Under the Senate proposal, all but the healthiest S&amp;Ls would have
stricter limits.
   _Greater limits on activities would be permitted to
state-chartered S&amp;Ls, but forbidden to S&amp;Ls with federal charters.
   Other significant changes offered by the Senate include:
   _Removal of a section of the administration bill that could undo
many of the S&amp;L rescues put together by regulators last year.
   _Fixed terms for the chairman and members of the FDIC. The
administration wants the president to have the power to dismiss the
FDIC chairman.
   _Removal of tougher accounting standards for credit unions. A
dispute over the administration's proposal for that industry had
threatened to delay the S&amp;L package.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890404-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 0247EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-DebtTalks 690   04-04 0685</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Debt Talks, 690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brady Looks for Quick Action on US Debt Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Will be topped around 9 a.m. EDT with final communique</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is challenging the world's
democratic powers to move quickly and put in motion the Bush
administration's plan for easing the Third World's politically
explosive debt burden.
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady's proposals to ease the
seven-year-old debt crisis were slated for a final review today
from the executive committee of the International Monetary Fund and
the World Bank.
   Some participants at the spring meeting of the two organizations
have expressed concerns that unless action is taken on the Brady
plan, political unrest could be unleashed in the fragile
democracies of Latin America where the huge debt burden has
depressed living standards for most of this decade.
   At least 270 people were killed in riots in Venezuela in
February after the goverment imposed a new austerity program to
satisfy creditors.
   Brady, in an address on Monday, told the organizations it was
time ``to turn these concepts into specifics which provide a basis
for lasting progress in dealing with the debt problem.''
   Brady's scheme marks a sharp turn from past U.S. policy because
it seeks for the first time to reduce the $1.3 trillion Third World
debt by getting commercial banks to voluntarily forgive part of
their loans.
   Although America's allies were not in total agreement with every
element of the plan, Canadian Finance Minister Michael Wilson
predicted it would receive general approval.
   He told reporters that although much discussion had gone on
about the technical problems of putting the plan in motion, ``there
are no serious objections that have been put forward.''
   The plan got a major boost on Monday when the Japanese stepped
forward with a pledge to provide up to $4.5 billion in new loans to
Third World debtors over the next several years. The funds,
however, did not match the widely anticipated $5 billion to $10
billion expected from the Tokyo government.
   Brady also had been counting on other countries running large
trade surpluses, such as West Germany, to recycle a part of their
wealth into increased aid for developing nations.
   Britain's Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson made clear
there were some doubts about how completely the U.S. plan would be
adopted, saying its proposal to use World Bank and IMF resources to
guarantee interest payments raised ``all sorts of problems.''
   Lawson said the time had come for the commercial banks who had
made the loans to do more to resolve the crisis by writing off debt
without trying to shift the burden onto the backs of the
international lending organizations.
   The IMF and World Bank are supported by taxpayer funds from the
151-member countries, but the United States is the largest
contributor.
   ``What I do not find acceptable is the idea that our taxpayers
should bail out the commercial banks,'' Lawson told reporters at a
briefing.
   The two large international lending agencies have a key role to
play in the plan because they would be expected to put up about $12
billion each to guarantee to the banks that the remaining part of
the debt or the annual interest payments would be repaid.
   The administration won general approval for its new approach
from its six largest allies on Sunday, but the communique issued by
the United States, Japan, West Germany, Britain, France, Canada and
Italy promised only to ``examine'' the question of guaranteeing
interest payments to the banks.
   The Group of Seven's communique was more supportive of the less
costly idea of guaranteeing the reduced level of debt.
   Mailson Ferreira da Nobrega, finance minister of Brazil, the
largest Third World debtor with $110 billion owed, praised the
Brady initiative, calling it a ``major conceptual breakthrough''
with success depending on ``our capacity to move quickly and far
enough.''
   ``These new ideas raise new hopes,'' he said in his comments to
the IMF steering group. ``They should be translated into immediate
action. It is crucial that such new hopes do not give place to new
frustrations.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
