<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 0236EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     04-04 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Plunges, Stocks Soar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar plunged against the Japanese yen
Tuesday, while share prices rose sharply on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 131.05 yen, down 1.21 yen from Monday's
132.26-yen close. It opened at 131.63 yen and ranged between 130.88
yen and 131.88 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 203.39-point
gainer Monday, added another 270.18 points, or 0.82 percent,
closing at 33,312.25, yet another record high.
   Dealers said the reaffirmation of the desirability of stable
currency rates by finance officials from the Group of Seven leading
industrialized nations in Washington over the weekend forced the
U.S. currency lower.
   ``There were widely shared feelings and concern that the dollar
was becoming too strong,'' said a dealer at a major U.S. commercial
bank, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Dealers said dollar-selling by European central banks in New
York and London overnight also motivated traders to sell the dollar.
   Dealers said improved prospects for more stable exchange rates
resulting from the G-7 meeting, coupled with traditionally bullish
market sentiment in April, sent share prices soaring.
   ``Buying incentives are very strong in the market,'' said a
dealer at Nikko Securities Co. who also spoke on condition of
anonymity. ``The strong performance on the New York Stock Exchange
overnight also encouraged investors here.''
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 11.18 points to 2,304.80
in New York on Monday.
   The G-7 nations are Britain, Canada, France, Italy, Japan, the
United States and West Germany.
</TEXT>
