<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 0433EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Agnew-Taxes     04-04 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Agnew-Taxes,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Vice President Requests Tax Refund for Bribe Restitution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Vice President Spiro Agnew says he
should be able to deduct $142,500 in restitution he paid Maryland
for bribes he was accused of collecting while governor, a newspaper
reported today.
   The Los Angeles Times also reported that Agnew has asked a
California tax board to refund $24,197 in state income taxes.
   Agnew claimed the deduction on his 1982 California income tax
return after a Maryland judge ordered him to reimburse that state
for the kickbacks prosecutors said he had accepted during his
tenure as governor plus $101,235 in interest.
   The deduction was rejected four years later by a California
Franchise Tax Board auditor, who assessed Agnew additional taxes
and interest.
   The Times said Agnew appealed the auditor's decision to the
California State Board of Equalization, which has scheduled a
hearing Thursday.
   Agnew, who lives in Rancho Mirage, argued in his tax appeal that
he is entitled to a deduction on his California income tax because
he paid the $142,500.
   The kickback scandal came to light as the Watergate scandal was
bringing down the Nixon administration. Agnew resigned as President
Nixon's vice president Oct. 10, 1973, as part of a plea agreement
with federal prosecutors.
   He pleaded no contest to charges of income tax evasion on
thousands of dollars prosecutors said he had taken as Baltimore
County executive from 1962 to 1966 and as Maryland governor from
1967 to 1969. The kickbacks were in exchange for government
contracts, prosecutors said.
   Agnew was ordered to pay $148,000 to the federal government and
$14,105 to Maryland. Agnew is seeking the tax deduction in
California because by the time the final ruling was issued in the
Maryland case in 1981, he became a California resident and had
already made payment.
   Agnew also contended he was being taxed twice _ by Maryland when
he was directed to pay $14,105 in back taxes, and by California. He
also complained it is unfair to pay taxes on money he was not
allowed to keep.
   ``There is no doubt it is patently unfair,'' Agnew's lawyer T.
Rogers Harrison, of Maryland, wrote in the tax appeal.
   But lawyers for the California Franchise Tax Board said the
question of double taxation is something Agnew must resolve with
Maryland, not California. They said in Agnew's case, the tax was
paid before he became a California resident.
   ``The state of California has never received any income in the
form of taxes or otherwise, from the amounts (Agnew) allegedly
received as bribes during his various terms of office,'' Lazaro L.
Bobiles, a lawyer for the franchise board, wrote in replay to the
appeal.
   ``(Agnew) has made restitution of the alleged bribes only to the
state of Maryland and has paid taxes on the alleged bribes only to
that state and to the federal government.''
</TEXT>
