<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 0544EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Markets     04-04 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Stocks Hit New High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell sharply against the Japanese yen
today, while share prices finished at a new high on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 131.05 yen, down 1.21 yen from the previous
day's 132.26-yen close. It opened at 131.63 yen and ranged between
130.88 yen and 131.88 yen. The dollar now has fallen 2.20 yen in
the last four trading days.
   Traders said today's lower opening followed the dollar's
overnight losses on overseas markets amid dollar-selling by
European central banks in New York and London.
   ``Japanese investors already were reluctant to buy the dollar
after the Bank of Japan's dollar-selling, yen-buying intervention
yesterday (Monday),'' said an analyst with a commercial bank,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``That's why a rumor that the U.S. Federal Reserve Board made an
inquiry to one of the American banks in Japan spread in the market
during morning trading and further discouraged participants' dollar
buying,'' the analyst added.
   He said the Bank of Japan's intervention Monday had a strong
impact after the market's recent dollar-buying trend. The dollar
had climbed to a closing of 133.25 on Wednesday. The Japanese
central bank's dollar-selling intervention was its first since 1985.
   The communique released by the Group of Seven leading
industrialized nations in Washington Monday, in which finance
officials reaffirmed the desirability of stable currency rates,
also contributed to pushing the dollar lower, the analyst said.
   On the stock exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which
gained 203.39 points Monday, added another 270.18 points, or 0.82
percent, closing at 33,312.25, yet another high.
   The market's key index has climbed for the last six trading
days, gaining almost 1,800 points.
   Dealers said stability in oil prices and the yen's upward trend
in the foreign exchange market relieved investors and encouraged
buying.
   Both individual and institutional investors were trading
actively, said a dealer with New Japan Securities Co. Ltd. in
Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Trading was active, with first section volume estimated at 1.7
billion shares, compared with 1.4 billion Monday. Among the gainers
were construction and steel issues.
</TEXT>
