<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 0444EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Korea-PlaneBombing     04-04 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Plane Bombing,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Demand Death For Terrorist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors today demanded the death
penalty for a woman who said she was working for North Korea when
she blew up a South Korean airliner in 1987, killing all 115 people
on board.
   Calling the bombing ``an unpardonable crime to mankind,''
Prosecutor Lee Sang-hyung blamed ``the dictatorship in North Korea
for the grave crime of killing the passengers.''
   The prosecution said North Korea ordered the bombing in an
attempt to disrupt the Seoul Olympics, which were held without
incident in September.
   The defendant, Kim Hyon Yui, 27, bowed her head and sobbed and
told the court ``it is fortunate the truth has been disclosed.
   ``I now curse (North Korean President) Kim Il Sung and Kim Jung
Il (his son and heir),'' she said, wiping her eyes with a
hankerchief. ``I do not know how to atone for my crime.''
   Kim's defense attorney, Ahn Dong-il, said his client should not
be punished even though she admitted to planting the bomb because
she was ``forced to commit the act and it is someone else who needs
to be punished _ North Korea.''
   Sentencing was set for April 25.
   Court officials indicated privately that Kim may be pardoned
because they say she was duped by North Korea and has repented.
   ``Why do you keep her alive?'' screamed relatives of victims
allowed into the courtroom. ``Kill her,'' they wailed.
   Security was tight and hundreds of police and security agents
ringed the Seoul District Court during today's proceedings. In
South Korea, defendants must stand trial even if they confess.
   The defendant said on South Korean television in January 1988
that she planted a bomb on the South Korean airliner in November
1987 as part of a North Korean plot to disrupt the Olympic Games in
Seoul last summer.
   North Korea has denied involvement.
   Police Lt. Kim Moon-Ho, an explosives expert, testified today
that the mixture of explosives used in the bomb was so powerful
that it would have destroyed the aircraft in less than a second.
   ``There would be no time, no chance, to contact anybody,'' he
told the court.
   The Korean Air Boeing 707 disappeared on a flight from Baghdad
to Seoul over the Andaman Sea as it approached the Burmese coast.
   Kim said she and another intelligence agent pretending to be
Japanese tourists planted the bomb when they flew from Baghdad to
Abu Dhabi, where they got off.
   The pair were arrested a short time later in Bahrain and
attempted to take cyanide hidden in cigarettes. The other agent, an
elderly man, died, but Kim recovered and was extradited to Seoul.
   Details of the bomb, how it was planted and detonated have come
from Kim since little plane wreckage was ever found.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
