<DOCNO> AP890404-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 0617EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PoliceSting     04-04 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Police Sting,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Officer Charged With Assault in Window-Smashing Incident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white police officer has been charged with
misdemeanor assault for allegedly slamming a black man's head
through a store window in an arrest that was broadcast on national
television.
   Long Beach Police Officer Mark Dickey also was charged Monday
with filing a false police report in the Jan. 14 arrest of Don C.
Jackson, a self-styled activist against police brutality.
   Jackson, trying to prove his theory that Long Beach police
routinely mistreat minorities, drove into Long Beach on a Saturday
night with an NBC-TV crew following at a discreet distance.
   When Jackson was pulled over by police, the crew filmed the
ensuing violence, which was broadcast on the ``Today'' show. The
tape showed an officer shoving Jackson's head through a plate glass
window.
   ``What we have here is a situation where a citizen went out and
tried to provoke an incident,'' said District Attorney Ira Reiner.
``But after the officer had control of the suspect and control of
the situation, he lost control of himself.''
   Reiner told reporters that Dickey then compounded his misconduct
by filing a false report on the incident.
   Dickey, 28, was charged with assault. He and his partner, Mark
Ramsey, 26, were also charged with filing a false police report.
   The charges against Dickey carry a maximum sentence of one year
in prison upon conviction. The charge against Ramsey carries a
possible maximum of six months.
   Jackson, 30, a Hawthorne police sergeant on disability leave,
was originally was charged with resisting arrest. Those charges
were dropped March 22 by the Long Beach city attorney who also
dismissed a ticket given to Jeffrey Hill, driver of the car in
which Jackson was riding.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
