<SECOND>PM-BRF--Freeway Baby,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Life Begins Near The Fast Lane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ashley Nicole Richardson began life near the fast
lane, choosing to be born on the shoulder of Interstate 5.
   Her father, Bren Richardson, was trying to weave through Monday
morning rush-hour traffic hoping to get his wife, Pamela, to
Northwest Hospital on time.
   But when Ashley began to arrive in the family sedan, Richardson
pulled to the shoulder and jumped out.
   ``Two cars stopped instead of running over me and each one had a
nurse in it,'' he said.
   Richardson said he delivered his daughter with the nurses
telling him what to do. ``Then they took over and wrapped the baby
up,'' he said.
   ``Then I got in the back seat and just shook and shook. I wasn't
ready for this. Pamela's going to be the death of me.''
   Mother and daughter were taken to the hospital, tired but in
fine health, Northwest officials said.
   The baby had been expected Thursday.
   The Richardsons have another daughter, 19-month-old Kelsey.
