<FIRST>r a PM-Duke-Contributions     04-04 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Duke-Contributions,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Klansman Got Campaign Contributions From Throughout Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Klansman David Duke received
contributions from around the country in his successful race for a
state House seat, campaign finance records show.
   Duke's report filed Monday showed he collected $137,000 and
spent $116,000. Fellow Republican John Treen's report showed he
collected $198,900 and spent $189,000.
   Most races for the 105-member House cost candidates less than
$30,000.
   Duke, 38, defeated Treen by 227 votes in the Feb. 18 special
election to represent a nearly all-white district in Metairie, a
New Orleans suburb.
   The Republican National Committee donated $16,500 to Treen and
shunned Duke, a former grand wizard of the Ku Klux Klan and founder
of the National Association for the Advancement of White People.
   President Bush and former president Reagan had endorsed Treen,
and national GOP chairman Lee Atwater denounced Duke's victory.
   Nearly 2,700 people from California to New York sent money to
Duke, ranging from $1 to $500.
   Treen received money from fewer than 800 contributors.
   Treen, 63, called the totals in his report misleading, saying he
actually wound up with a deficit rather than a surplus because
$21,200 of his collections was money he loaned the campaign.
Collections include contributions, loans and in-kind services
according to state law.
   Treen said his campaign repaid some of the loan but still has
debts, ``including $13,000 to me,'' he said in a telephone
interview.
   Meanwhile, state GOP chairman Billy Nungesser announced a
campaign to lure more Democrats to his party but said he has ``no
plans to talk with Mr. Duke abbout this party.''
   ``Democrats elected David Duke to office. The Republicans in
that district supported Treen,'' Nungesser told the Press Club of
Baton Rouge.
   Only about 400,000 of the state's nearly 2 million registered
voters are registered Republicans.
</TEXT>
