<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 0550EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Chile     04-04 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chile,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pinochet's Finance Czar Resigns To Mull Presidency Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hernan Buchi, the architect of Chile's
successful free-market economy, says he has resigned as finance
minister to consider running for president.
   In response to Buchi's departure, President Augusto Pinochet
asked his 15 other Cabinet members Monday to resign so he could
reorganize the body.
   Government spokesman Miguel Angel Poduje said Buchi's
replacement and any other Cabinet changes would be announced on
Wednesday. No important changes were foreseen in economic policy.
   Buchi, 40, said he resigned to study the persistent appeals of a
group of conservative politicians and business leaders who want him
to run for president in the Dec. 14 elections.
   The group has plastered bumper stickers and posters supporting
Buchi's candidacy throughout the capital and said last week it has
collected 142,000 signatures from citizens backing the campaign.
   ``It never was, and is not, my intention to be presented for
this type of candidacy,'' Buchi told reporters at the Finance
Ministry. ``Nonetheless, the situation has reached the (point) that
my name is being publicly mentioned.
   ``I reached the conclusion that analyzing this situation was
incompatible with keeping my post as finance minister,'' he said.
   The December elections are the first since before Pinochet
seized power in a bloody 1973 coup, toppling an elected leftist
government. The 73-year-old army commander was obliged to call
elections after losing a referendum in October on a proposal to
extend his rule to 1997.
   Although his supporters want him to run, Pinochet insists he
will not be a candidate. The constitution bars him from running.
   Buchi, who holds a master's degree in business adminstration
from New York's Columbia University, joined the Pinochet
government's economic team at age 29 and rose swiftly to become its
chief.
   After serving as an advisor and as health undersecretary, he was
named planning minister in 1983, banks superintendent a year later
and finance minister in February 1985.
   Pushing exports and promoting foreign investment, the
government's economic program has produced five consecutive years
of growth while keeping inflation to a current annual rate of about
13 percent, far lower than most Latin American countries.
   It has elicited praise from financial experts, although
Pinochet's critics contend the policies carried a high social cost
and reduced the buying power of most workers' wages.
   Pinochet frequently boasts of his government's economic
successes and often praises Buchi in public. He has affectionately
called him ``our Prince Valiant,'' a reference to Buchi's ragged
pageboy haircut.
   A recent opinion poll showed Buchi as the strongest of several
potential conservative or rightist presidential candidates, but
lagging behind opposition leader Patricio Aylwin.
   Aylwin, 70, is candidate of the centrist Christian Democratic
Party and is seeking the backing of a coalition of 17 centrist and
leftist parties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
