<FIRST>r a PM-FatalFire     04-04 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fatal Fire,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grandfather Helps Save Five Children, But Six Die In Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>REMBERT, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With no telephone nearby and the fire
department three miles away, a man watched helplessly as flames
engulfed his mobile home and took the lives of six children, five
of them his grandchildren.
   ``I woke up when the fire bug (alarm) went off and tried to get
all the children out,'' English, 57, said Monday.
   Five other grandchildren who had been sleeping managed to escape
with English after the fire broke out early Sunday. One of them
suffered a burned hand, family members said.
   ``I heard the fire alarm and my cousins let the window up and
pushed the screen out and all four of us got out the window,'' said
Jacobia English, 11, who lost two brothers.
   Next-door neighbor Charlie Wright Jr. said he ``heard the
hollering'' from the double-wide trailer and ``knew the kids were
burning up.''
   Wright drove three miles to Rembert, a small town of about 500,
and set off a siren, but the fire had nearly consumed the home by
the time he returned with firefighters.
   Family members had gathered in this Sumter County town to
celebrate the birthday of English's daughter, Peggy Miller of
Beaufort. Her three children _ 8-month-old Nericaletha, 1-year-old
Kesim and 3-year-old Clyde _ died in the blaze.
   County Coroner Bill Gamble identified the other victims as the
Miller children's cousins, Travis and James English of Rembert,
ages 9 and 11, and a friend, Terrance Campbell, 5, of Camden.
Officials said the children died of smoke inhalation.
   Emma English, Jacobia's mother, had been with other family
members in a mobile home 150 yards down a dirt road from the
trailer when the fire broke out. The family gathered at the home
again Monday to mourn.
   ``I just can't get over it. It seems like a dream,'' said Mrs.
English said.
   ``This is the worst fire we can recall in Sumter County,'' Fire
Chief Larry Causey said. ``It's saddening to think something like
this can happen.''
   Investigators haven't determined the cause of the blaze.
</TEXT>
