<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     04-04 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Dives Before Stabilizing, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell sharply in early European trading
today but stabilized by late morning. Gold prices rose.
   Foreign currency dealers said they thought the dollar had
touched bottom for now and would probably fluctuate within narrow
margins before testing news lows again later this week.
   One trader in Rome said that Monday's central bank intervention,
especially by the Bank of Japan, yen-buying by Japanese industries
at the beginning of their fiscal year, and market rumors that West
Germany may raise interest rates combined to push the dollar lower
overnight.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 1.21 yen to a closing 131.05. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 131.03 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday:
   _1.8700 West German marks, down from 1.8835
   _1.6370 Swiss francs, down from 1.6488
   _6.3075 French francs, down from 6.3535
   _2.1078 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1230
   _1,371.50 Italian lire, down from 1,381.50
   _1.1883 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1896
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7030, more expensive for
buyers than late Monday's $1.6855.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $387 dollars a troy
ounce, up from $384.75 dollars bid late Monday. At midmorning
today, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended
price of $386.60.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $386.75, up from $385.25 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.14 to close at a bid price
of $388.42.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.83 a troy
ounce, up from Monday's $5.80.
</TEXT>
