<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 0638EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RacismClass     04-04 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Racism Class,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>University of Michigan Faculty Scrap Plan for Mandatory Racism Classes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Michigan faculty has
rejected a proposal to make racism courses mandatory following
several racist incidents on campus in recent years.
   Faculty instead agreed Monday to ask the curriculum committee of
the College of Literature, Science and the Arts to consider by next
fall ways to offer racism studies.
   Incidents at the university have included the distribution of a
flyer declaring ``open season'' on blacks in 1987, racist jokes by
a disc jockey on the student radio station and the stuffing of Ku
Klux Klan literature under black students' doors.
   Faculty defeated by 140-120 a proposal that would have required
students to take four credit hours of classes dealing with racism.
Classes could have been in economics, sociology or other fields.
   Philosophy Prof. Peter Railton, who drew up the proposal, said
he was optimistic despite the vote.
   ``The debate was a substantive and good one. I think the
discussion and the vote will have impact on thinking of the
(curriculum) committee,'' Railton said.
   About 5,000 of the university's 32,400 students are minorities,
some of whom say the campus has been plagued with racist and
anti-Semitic graffiti and occasional tauntings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
