<DOCNO> AP890404-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 0640EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     04-04 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Die In Latest Fighting, Power Plant Running Out Of Fuel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian gunners attacked
residential areas in and around Beirut with howitzers and rockets,
and police said at least six people were killed and 18 wounded
during a night of fighting.
   The bombardment that began late Saturday subsided into sporadic
exchanges at daybreak today.
   The overnight casualties raised the toll to 153 people killed
and 499 wounded since March 8, when the latest round of hostilities
broke out between Gen. Michel Aoun's Christian troops and an
alliance of Syrian and Druse forces.
   Meanwhile, Lebanon's electricity authority said in a statement
that its power station in the Christian suburb of Zouk would run
out of fuel oil today and it would stop providing power to most of
Lebanon.
   The statement said a freighter loaded with 30 tons of fuel oil
has not been able to unload its cargo at the power station's dock
because of the shelling.
   Insurance companies ``want a solid cease-fire before accepting
to cover any ship that wants to dock at the Zouk station,'' the
statement said.
   The independent daily An-Nahar and other publications today
carried front-page statements from the U.S. State Department and
the European Community calling for a cease-fire in Lebanon.
   Despite the relative lull today, civilians remained huddled in
basements and bomb shelters.
   A dozen families in the basement of an apartment building in the
Christian district of Adonis dispatched one man to a bakery for
bread.
   ``This is the safest way, we will send one of us to buy food for
the whole building every day until a cease-fire is declared and
accepted by both sides,'' Antoine Shedyak said.
   ``Yes, there is a lull, but there is no cease-fire. We will not
take any unnecessary risks,'' Shedyak, a mechanical engineer, said
in a telephone interview.
   Kuwaiti Foreign Minister Sheik Sabah Ahmad Sabah was due in the
Syrian capital of Damascus today to try end the present
confrontation.
   Sabah heads a six-man Arab League committee assigned to find a
settlement to a political crisis that threatens to cement Lebanon's
partition into sectarian mini-states.
   The leftist daily paper As-Safir, which is close to Syria, said
Sabah would propose a two-month truce in the conflict to give the
Arab League committee enough time to solve the crisis.
   Aoun, backed by 20,000 troops, has insisted that Syria be party
to any cease-fire accord. The current fighting broke out when Aoun
blockaded illegal militia ports that diverted $100 million from
government-run ports.
   The Syrians have 40,000 troops in predominantly Moslem areas of
Lebanon under a peacekeeping mandate their received from the Arab
League in 1976, two years after civil war broke out in Lebanon.
   Officially, the Syrians maintain that their troops in Lebanon
are not involved in the confrontation with Aoun's forces, which are
entrenched across a 310-square-mile Christian enclave northeast of
Beirut.
   Nabih Berri, the Shiite Moslem chief of the Amal militia, said
Monday in Damascus that 20 representatives of Moslem and leftist
groups would meet Sabah in Damascus on Wednesday.
   Press reports said the group would outline its desire for a new
political system that distributes powers equally among the various
Lebanese sects, the election of a new president and formal links
with Syria.
   The Christians are to dispatch a 10-man delegation for a meeting
with Sabah later in the week.
   Lebanon has been without a head of state since Sept. 22, when
the six-year-term of President Amin Gemayel expired with parliament
failing to elect a successor.
   Gemayel appointed Aoun, a fellow Maronite, head of an interim
military cabinet to rule pending the election of a new president.
   Syrian-backed Moslems rejected Aoun's appointment because it
violated a 45-year-old tradition of having a Sunni Moslem prime
minister.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
