<DOCNO> AP890404-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 0649EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-KoreanDissident     04-04 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korean Dissident,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korean Dissident Says He Doesn't Fear Arrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A South Korean dissident today called his
unauthorized visit to North Korea a success and said he was ready
to face arrest at home.
   ``I'm not nervous about my arrest but I hope I won't be
arrested,'' Rev. Moon Ik-hwan told a news conference.
   The Seoul government has said it will jail Moon for his trip to
Pyongyang. South Koreans are prohibited from visiting the north
without government approval.
   Communist North Korea has warned that Moon's arrest would hamper
dialogue between the sides.
   In South Korean, authorities imprisoned two dissident leaders
Monday in an apparent crackdown on dissent connected to the Moon
visit. Moon said his wife told him by telephone Monday night that
his three sons also had been arrested. Reports from Seoul said the
sons were under investigation.
   Moon, 71, has been arrested several times for anti-government
activities since the 1970s. Asked why his sons had reportedly been
detained, he smiled and said ``they have the wrong father.''
   Moon arrived in the Chinese capital Monday after a nine-day
visit to North Korea. He said he planned to leave Wednesday for
Tokyo, but that he had not decided when he would return to Seoul.
   The English-language Korea Times reported today that South Korea
has asked Japan to deny Moon a visa. In Tokyo, Foreign Ministry
officials said Moon had been granted a transit visa that would
allow him to spend nine days in Japan.
   The officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, did not say
whether South Korea had requested that Moon be denied a visa. They
said that Moon's request was treated the same as any South Korean
civilian's.
   In Seoul, Justice Minister Huh Hyong-koo said today that Moon
would be arrested when he returns for violation of national
security law. South Korean officials say the trip aided the north
in its attempts to cause unrest and discredited the Seoul
government.
   Moon met for seven hours with North Korean President Kim Il Sung
for talks on reunifying the peninsula.
   ``I think the success of the visit was greater than I expected,
and I am very happy,'' Moon said.
   Moon said he was pleased by South Korean President Roh Tae-Woo's
statement on July 7 calling for talks with the north and ``thought
it was natural to go to the north and have a meeting.''
   He blamed the Seoul government for failing to come up with a
concrete plan for reunification and said his visit to Pyongyang
``was a great surprise to them (the Seoul government) so it's
natural for them to react very strongly. I think they will come to
their senses.''
   Moon, an adviser to South Korea's main dissident group, the
United National Democratic Movement, was invited to North Korea by
the governmental Committee for the Peaceful Reunification of the
Fatherland.
   He was reunited with 18 members of his family living in the
North.
   North and South Korea have been bitter rivals since the division
of the peninsula in 1945, despite recent talks aimed at eventual
reunification.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
