<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to restore byline.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Strike Nation's Midsection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe thunderstorms moved through the central part of the
country today, with tornadoes touching down in Arkansas and Texas.
   Thunderstorms developing along and ahead of a cold front moved
through the Ohio Valley, the Tennessee Valley and the lower
Mississippi Valley early this morning, with strong thunderstorms
extending from western Kentucky to northeastern Texas.
   In Arkansas, thunderstorms spawned tornadoes Monday evening near
Amagon, Mount Ida, Jonesboro and Crystal Springs and golf ball-size
hail elsewhere. Strong winds downed trees and power lines in
southern Jefferson County.
   In Texas, thunderstorms generated a tornado northwest of Grand
Saline, hail 3{ inches in diameter near Quinlan and winds gusting
up to 70 mph.
   Heavier rainfall for the six-hour period ending at 2 a.m. EDT
included 2{ inches at Louisville, Ky., 1} inches at Evansville,
Ind., and nearly 1{ inches at Fort Campbell, Ky.
   Elsewhere, light rain was falling over northern Oklahoma,
southern Kansas and southeastern Colorado. Scattered showers were
over the upper Great Lakes and the upper Mississippi Valley, with
snow near Lake Superior.
   Scattered rain also fell over the northwestern part of the
country, while much of the Southwest enjoyed fair skies.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from the
Mississippi River to the East Coast; snow over northern Michigan
and northern Wisconsin; scattered rain and snow in the upper
Mississippi Valley and the northern and central Rockies; and rain
along the northern Pacific Coast.
   Highs were expected to be in the 30s and 40s over the northern
and central Rockies, portions of the Dakotas, the upper Mississippi
Valley and the northern Great Lakes; in the 70s and 80s from the
middle and south Atlantic Coast states across the Gulf Coast
states, New Mexico, much of Arizona and California; in the 90s in
the Desert Southwest; and the 50s and 60s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 4
degrees above zero at Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 77 degreees at Key
West, Fla., and Laredo, Texas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 66 fair; Boston 47 foggy; Buffalo 42 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 67 fair; Cincinnati 58 showers; Cleveland 51 rain;
Detroit 45 foggy; Miami 73 partly cloudy; New York 44 foggy;
Philadelphia 50 fair; Pittsburgh 57 thunderstorms; Portland, Maine
40 cloudy; Washington 58 partly cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 33 fair; Chicago 49 cloudy; Dallas-Fort Worth
68 partly cloudy; Denver 37 cloudy; Des Moines 41 fair;
Indianapolis 52 foggy; Kansas City 47 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 38
partly cloudy; Nashville 56 thunderstorms; New Orleans 73 partly
cloudy; St. Louis 48 partly cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 57 fair; Anchorage 32 fair; Las Vegas 76
fair; Los Angeles 66 fair; Phoenix 76 fair; Salt Lake City 37
showers; San Diego 62 fair; San Francisco 53 fair; Seattle 42 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 39 cloudy; Toronto 39 rain.
</TEXT>
