<FIRST>r i PM-Australia-Cyclone     04-04 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Australia-Cyclone,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cyclone Sweeps Across Australia Coast, Kills at Least two</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cyclone Aivu swept across Queensland
today and authorities declared part of the state a disaster area
after two people died, 10 were injured and dozens of homes were
damaged.
   The cyclone, packing 100 mph winds, began battering the east
coast as the country was recovering from three days of torrential
rains during which four people drowned and four others were missing.
   As the cyclone approached, the air force ordered a squadron of
fighter planes to move inland to avoid the storm.
   Police said one man died when his trailer was swept into a creek
near Ayr and another man died when his home was flattened in the
same town. Power and other services were cut.
   At least 10 people were injured by flying debris and 160 homes
were destroyed or badly damaged, police said. There were reports of
flooding, police said.
   Authorities declared the remote Burdekin tomato-growing and
fruit-producing region a disaster area.
   Earlier, rains dumped more than 12 inches in 24 hours and the
Weather Bureau said it was Sydney's wettest March in 26 years.
</TEXT>
