<HEAD>Pilot of Chased Plane Bails Out, Lets Plane Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to insert time element.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspected drug smuggler being chased by
federal agents set his plane on autopilot and bailed out, letting
the pilotless plane fly on for 180 miles before it crashed into the
Gulf of Mexico, officials said.
   Ronald Cox, 43, of Miami was arrested Monday and authorities
recovered 19 bales of marijuana from the wreckage, said U.S.
Customs Service spokesman Michael Sheehan.
   The plane was first picked up by radar about 140 miles southwest
of Key West, flying very low over the water toward Florida. A
Customs jet and a Coast Guard Falcon jet followed it for two hours,
Sheehan said.
   At times, up to five aircraft tailed the twin-engine Beechcraft
Travelair. After Cox bailed out over Sarasota, two Air Force F-15
fighter jets followed the plane ready to shoot it down if it
threatened a populated area.
   ``I guess it had a pretty good load of fuel in it,'' said Coast
Guard Lt.j.g. John Katinski.
   A Coast Guard cutter recovered the marijuana at the crash site
in the Gulf.
