<HEAD>Cuban Dissidents Arrested</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gorbachev-Castro</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAVANA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested as many as 10 dissidents this
morning who planned a demonstration calling for reforms in Cuba
similar to those championed by visiting Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev, a dissident said.
   Among those arrested was Samuel Martinez Lara, leader of the
Pro-Human Rights Party, said Elizardo Sanchez.
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman, Hector Argiles, said Martinez Lara
was arrested for engaging in unauthorized activities. Martinez
Lara, who was detained briefly and fined last week, had been
organizing a demonstration to be held tonight in front of the
Soviet Embassy.
   Sanchez said the demonstration was intended to support reforms
being carried out by Gorbachev and to request his backing for
similar policies in Cuba.
   Also arrested, Sanchez said, was Roberto Bahamonde, a member of
the Commission on Human Rights and National Reconciliation.
   Bahamonde called for capitalist reform in his unsuccessful bid
last month for a seat on a neighborhood council. It was believed to
be the first time a dissident ran for office since the revolution
30 years ago.
