<FIRST>u a PM-BridgeCollapse 1stLd-Writethru a0465 04-04 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bridge Collapse, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0465,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Water May Have Caused Bridge Collapse; Search for Bodies Continued</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to CORRECT that Jones would be eighth killed,
sted among seven known dead; search resumes; Picks up 4th graf, `Hurst
said ...'; SUBS 8th graf, `Monday a ...' with dragging resumed.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COVINGTON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the couple standing vigil beside a
collapsed highway bridge, the waiting was harder than knowing if
their loved one was killed along with seven others when the
55-year-old span gave way.
   ``They brought up a piece of car that was the same color as
his,'' Paul Hurst said Monday as searchers continued looking for
victims in the rain-swollen Hatchie River.
   Seven bodies have been pulled from river since the bridge
collapsed Saturday night. But authorities continued their search
today, operating under the belief at least one more car is still
submerged.
   Hurst said his half-brother, Adrain Jones, 26, has not been seen
since shortly before a 90-foot section of the U.S. 51 bridge fell,
sending cars and a tractor trailer rig plunging 25 feet into the
water.
   ``He left the hospital and I went to Memphis the same time,''
said Hurst, who with his wife, Brenda, has been waiting beside the
river since they first heard of the bridge collapse a few hours
after the accident.
   ``He didn't make it. He was going back to Ripley because his
daddy was sick and he was going to stay with him.''
   Authorities said they, too, are working on the assumption that
Jones' car is somewhere in the dark, swirling water.
   Monday, a dog trained to sniff bodies appeared to find
something. Authorities resumed dragging operations this morning.
Divers were forced to wait because of strong currents in the river,
about 50 miles north of Memphis.
   Also Monday, workers began cutting up the three 28-foot bridge
spans. When the 100-ton concrete slabs are jackhammered into
manageable pieces, a crane will be brought in to remove them, said
Jim Thacker, regional manager of the Tennessee Emergency Management
Agency.
   Terry Petty, a diver with the Tennessee Highway Patrol, said
searchers were unsure what they will find under the slabs, two of
which are known to be lying on at least three cars and a tractor
trailer truck.
   ``Anything's possible,'' he said.
   Also, Petty said, it is unclear if any vehicles went into the
river but were not trapped by the falling slabs.
   ``I don't know. With this current, if a car went off after it
fell, it could be a mile down the river,'' he said.
   The cause of the collapse was unknown, but state Transportation
Commissioner Jimmy Evans said heavy spring floods following two
years of drought may have undercut a bridge support. Two
inspections during the last 18 months revealed no problems, he said.
   The collapse apparently began when a support holding up one of
the bridge sections gave way, said Jacky Carter, a state inspector.
   As the cars and the 18-wheeler plunged of the bridge, the other
two highway sections came crashing down on them, he said.
   Residents say they have worried about the safety of the bridge
for some time, but Lauderdale County Executive Bill Tucker said his
office has not received any such complaints.
   ``I've crossed that bridge many times every week and I've never
had any fear of it,'' he said. ``Obviously, they're going to
complain now.''
   The bridge, eight-tenths of a mile long, carries two northbound
lanes of U.S. 51 across the Hatchie about five miles north of
Covington.
   A companion bridge, built in the mid-1970s to carry the
southbound lanes, was unaffected but has been closed indefinitely
while state and federal officials investigate.
   Joseph Osterman, an investigator with the National
Transportation Safety Board, said it would take his agency several
months to file a report.
</TEXT>
