<SECOND>PM-Mayor-Gambling, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0547,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mississippi Mayor Agrees To Resign In Wake Of Gambling Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Authorities charged ...' and 7th graf, `Rowan
has ...' to CORRECT spelling to Baldwyn.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small-town mayor said today he has
pleaded guilty to federal charges of operating a gambling business
and agreed to resign his post by May 15.
   Baldwyn Mayor Merle Rowan, 67, and his wife, Robbie Rowan, 51,
entered the pleas Monday in U.S. District Court. Mike Price, 32,
Rowan's stepson, agreed to cooperate with federal authorities in
exchange for charges being dropped against him, authorities said.
   The three, along with Rowan's son, Larry Rowan, 22, were named
in a seven-count indictment in November charging they operated the
gambling business from 1985 to 1988.
   In a telephone interview from his office in city hall, Rowan
acknowledged that he had entered a plea. ``I'm in my third term, I
will be here through the 15th'' of May, Rowan said.
   Authorities charged that the family conspired and placed video
poker gambling machines at five businesses in Lee County. One of
the businesses, a bar and dance hall near Baldwyn, was established
by state agents as part of an undercover investigation into
gambling and other illegal activities.
   In exchange for the pleas from Rowan and his wife, no other
charges will be pursued, court records showed.
   Rowan has been mayor of Baldwyn, a northeast Mississippi town of
about 3,500, since 1977.
   Rowan also agreed to forfeit poker gambling machines and two
vehicles that authorities charged were used to further the gambling
operation.
   He faces up to 10 years in prison and a $500,000 fine. The plea
agreement stated that federal authorities would not oppose
probation for Mrs. Rowan. No date was set for sentencing.
