<HEAD>Italian Architect Dies at 86</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Architect Andrea Busiri Vici, who helped design the
Italian pavilion at the 1939 World's Fair in New York, died Tuesday
at the age of 86.
   He died of heart failure at Rome's European Hospital, according
to the Italian news agency ANSA.
   Busiri Vici, who also designed homes in the Rome area and
published several books on art, was known for combining elements of
traditional and modern architecture. He and his brother, Michele,
worked on the Italian pavilion at the 1939 exposition.
   Services were scheduled for Wednesday.
