<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 1232EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     04-04 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gov't Heightens Crackdown on Labor, Student Protests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police firing tear gas charged
onto a university campus and into a housing complex Tuesday to put
down violent anti-government protests in two cities.
   In Ulsan, about 150 miles south of Seoul, thousands of workers
hurling firebombs and rocks fought riot police to protest a
crackdown on strikers at Hyundai Heavy Industries, the nation's
largest shipyard, news reports said.
   About 3,000 riot police stormed a complex of 150 high-rise
apartments, a stronghold of militant stikers, after battling 5,000
workers and radical students on the streets, according to the South
Korean news agency Yonhap.
   Television footage showed protesters yelling and throwing rocks
and firebombs from apartment balconies and roofs. Rocks rained down
on police, who retaliated with tear gas.
   The Korean Broadcasting System said police retreated after
several hours of battles that left about 60 police and workers
injured. Police gave no figures on arrests or injuries in the six
days of protest.
   Fighting has taken place daily in Ulsan since March 30 when
14,000 riot police stormed the shipyard to end a 109-day strike by
5,000 of the company's 19,500 workers who broke off from the
company union.
   Militant workers demanded more pay and better working
conditions. Hyundai officials say non-striking workers have been
assaulted and attacked leaving the yard and the workforce has
steadily declined. On Tuesday, about half the workers showed up.
   Stores, banks and schools near the shipyard must close part of
every day as fighting erupts. Hyundai officials worry the labor
unrest will spread to subsidiaries.
   Hyundai, one of South Korea's largest conglomerates, makes cars,
steel, electronics and other products, and employs 100,000 people
in Ulsan.
   Radical students attacked four Hyundai offices in three cities,
burning two cars and breaking windows, Yonhap said.
   In western Seoul, police in visored helmets stormed the campus
of Yonsei University, firing tear gas to disperse an
anti-government rally by 1,000 students. In the last two years,
police have stayed on the perimeters of colleges and fought
students mostly in and around school gates.
   The students burned an effigy of President Roh Tae-woo, then
drove police back by hurling firebombs and rocks. They shouted:
``Down with Roh Tae-woo, who blocks unification and stifles
workers' rights!''
   The fighting continued about an hour, and police said more than
400 students from other colleges were arrested for trying to enter
Yonsei to take part in the protest after school gates had been
sealed off by thousands of police. One student was injured in the
head by police hurling rocks.
   The students were protesting the police action in Ulsan and
supporting the trip to North Korea by a dissident, the Rev. Moon
Ik-kwan.
   Moon's unauthorized visit has provoked controversy in South
Korea, where government officials say he was serving interests of
communist North Korea. It has sparked a government crackdown on
dissidents, with security officials arresting Moon's colleagues and
questioning others.
   Security agencies and police raided dissident offices and homes
Monday. Dissidents alleged the government was using Moon's trip as
an excuse to crack down on dissent.
   Radicals students are a vocal minority with little public
support.
</TEXT>
