<FIRST>r a PM-MolesterLawsuit     04-04 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Molester Lawsuit,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Child Molester Sues His Victims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A child molester serving a 34-year
prison sentence is suing his victims, alleging he is unable to find
a new job and has suffered humiliation, anxiety and loss of health.
   John Taylor Booz, 62, filed a $2 million damage lawsuit March 28
in state district court.
   Defendants include two youths he was convicted of molesting.
Other defendants include a boy whose allegations were rejected by a
jury and members of at least two of the boys' families.
   Booz alleged that he lost his job as a salesman and cannot find
a new job in his field because of a conspiracy and accusations by
the people he sued.
   He alleged he has lost earnings and earning capacity ``into the
indeterminate future'' and has suffered ``extreme humiliation,
anxiety and loss of health.''
   District Attorney Robert Schwartz said he would defend the
families.
   He said he ``will not allow a convicted child molester to
revictimize the victims. ... I will do my best to see that this
legal assault comes to as final a conclusion as the sexual
assault.''
   Schwartz said he determined that neither the New Mexico Crime
Victims Reparation Commission nor the Risk Management Division can
cover legal expenses for the families, so he will provide the
defense.
   Booz was convicted Sept. 4, 1987, of 11 counts of criminal
sexual contact of a minor and one count of child enticement. His
conviction was upheld on appeal.
   The boys were about 10 to 11 years old at the time, Chief Deputy
District Attorney Michael Cox, who prosecuted the case, said Monday.
</TEXT>
