<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jetliner Crash-Lands, All Aboard Survive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A domestic jetliner carrying 130 people
crash-landed in flames at a jungle airport, the government news
agency said today. It said 14 people were injured, but reported no
deaths.
   The Faucett Airlines Boeing 737 crashed at 6:43 p.m. Monday at
the airport in Iquitos, after a flight from Lima, 715 miles away,
the Andina news agency said.
   The jet tilted sideways before touching down on the runway, and
one engine burst into flames, Andina said. The nose of the aircraft
rammed into the runway and both wings tore off as the jet skidded
off the runway.
   Andina said the 130 passengers and crew members scrambled off
the jet _ some leaving the plane before it came to a halt _ as
flames reached the fuselage.
   Fourteen people were injured, some with second-degree burns and
others as a result of jumping from the plane, the agency said.
   The body of the jet was destroyed by the fire, it said.
   Officials at Iquitos airport blamed the crash landing on
``unfavorable climatic conditions and strong tropical rains,''
Andina reported.
   Repeated calls to Faucett Airlines went unanswered today.
   In the last serious airplane accident in Peru, 12 people were
killed when a jetliner of the state-owned airline Aeroperu crashed
on takeoff in October in the highland city of Puno.
</TEXT>
