<FIRST>r i AM-Europe-Weather     04-04 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Europe-Weather,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>April in Paris: Snow in the Blossoms</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PAR2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frigid weather chilled France on Tuesday, bringing
Paris its first snowfall since the winter of 1987-88.
   The blustering cold followed days of balmy weather crowned by
spring blossoms that started sprouting a week ago as temperatures
soared to the 70s.
   Tuesday's early morning temperatures hovered around freezing in
the northern half of the country with gusts of wind reaching 30 mph.
   The snow coated trees and lawns but did not disrupt morning
traffic because it melted as soon as it hit the streets.
   The Paris weather bureau said the impression that a cold wave
had struck stemmed from the contrast between the freezing
temperatures and the warm weather last week. Forecasters said snow
and cold temperatures are normal for early April in the northern
part of the country.
   In the south, in Provence and along the French Riviera, where
there was concern about the lack of moisture, one-half to nearly 2
inches of rain fell in the past 24 hours. Rain also fell in the
Pyrenees along the Spanish border.
   In the English Channel, winds gusted up to 50 mph and waves of
20 feet were reported off the Channel Islands.
   Snow and sleet hit Belgium, chilling residents who also had been
enjoying warm weather. Temperatures dropped to 36 degrees and the
winds picked up.
   Over the weekend, Belgian beaches saw the first sunbathers in
swimsuits and the public parks were full of families enjoying
68-degree temperatures.
   But on Tuesday, the weather office reported more than an inch of
snow _ the first in more than a year _ in central Belgium.
   Forecasters said temperatures were expected to warm up again
later this week.
</TEXT>
