<HEAD>Weather, Radar Problems Wreak Havoc At Lambert Airport</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Storms Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Travelers using Lambert Airport faced long
delays and cancellations early this week because of fog,
thunderstorms and a radar malfunction, but the weather cleared and
operations were normal today.
   Lambert can land from 60 to 84 planes an hour, but because of
poor weather and the radar problem, that figure was reduced to 36
on Sunday and Monday, traffic manager Sam Smith said.
   Smith said the weekend weather forecast was favorable when the
decision was made last week to replace a radar antenna. The switch
was made Saturday, but a ``glitch'' blitzed the system Sunday
morning. The local radar went down, and Lambert had to rely on an
auxiliary system piped in from Kansas City.
   Bad weather forced the Federal Aviation Administration to put a
``ground hold'' on Lambert, meaning planes in other airports were
not allowed to take off if their destination was Lambert.
