<HEAD>Voters Go To the Polls As Daley Favored To Follow Father's Footsteps</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to insert new Daley quote; Picks up 3rd graf,
``That's a ...'; INSERTS 1 graf after 11th graf, `This is ...' with Vrdolyak
voting, quote.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos CX2,3,4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters turned out in heavy numbers today to
decide whether Richard M. Daley should inherit his father's
political mantle and end black control of the mayor's office.
   ``Now I got two votes,'' Daley joked after he and his wife
Maggie voted late this morning.
   The first few hours of voting indicated that 70 percent of the
city's 1.56 million registered voters would go to the polls, said
Tom Leach, spokesman for the Chicago Board of Elections.
   ``That's a pretty good vote, third highest in history for a
municipal election,'' he said.
   The Democratic nominee, whose father ruled Chicago for 21 years
until his death in 1976, has enjoyed double-digit leads in the
polls but warned of complacency on the eve of the ballot.
   ``It's a problem when these polls come out and they tell you you
are so far ahead,'' Daley said Monday night. ``I think it's going
to be a close election.''
   The Cook County prosecutor's chief rival, Alderman Timothy
Evans, campaigned with Jesse Jackson and appealed to blacks by
invoking th black people saying they want a black mayor.''
   Elsewhere, voters were choosing mayors in St. Louis, Madison,
Wis., Wichita, Kan., and Omaha, Neb. Voters in Kansas City, Mo.,
were voting on a proposal to give more power to the mayor and limit
the mayor and city council members to three consecutive four-year
terms.
   Residents of suburban Winnetka were voting on a non-binding
resolution to ban handguns. Last May 20, Laurie Dann carried three
handguns into a Winnetka school where she shot and killed an
8-year-old boy and wounded several others. She later committed
suicide.
   In Alabama, Democrat Glen Browder, the secretary of state, was
favored to defeat Republican state Sen. John Rice for the 3rd
District congressional seat left vacant by the death of Rep. Bill
Nichols, a Democrat.
