<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 1336EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China     04-04 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0715</SECOND>
<HEAD>Many Legislators Vote Against Autonomy for Free-Zone City</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A law giving one of China's free-enterprise
cities the right to make its own laws ran into unprecedented
opposition in the legislature Tuesday, and after passage a member
demanded a recount from the floor.
   Negative votes or abstentions were recorded on all nine laws or
motions presented on the last day of the annual legislative
session. All were approved by large margins.
   One of the most important measures give people the right to sue
officials, but a Western legal expert said its purpose was to
increase central control, not protect the rights of citizens.
   The law that caused the stir in the National People's Congress
gave special legislative freedom to Shenzhen, a city in Guangdong
province.
   Most of the 2,688 deputies supported the bill, but 274 voted
against it and 805 abstained in the greatest show of opposition
since the legislature was established 40 years ago.
   Fellow deputies cheered when Huang Xunxin, representing Taiwan,
spoke out against the bill from the floor. He said the congress was
usurping powers of Guangdong province and other cities also would
demand autonomy.
   A woman deputy screamed for a recount but her demand was
ignored. A third member strode to the microphone after the vote to
repeat his opposition.
   It was an unusual performance in a legislature that customarily
rubber-stamps Communist Party policies, but was more indicative of
the session's conservative tone than of a new independent spirit.
   China's leaders stressed to the congress that power must be
recentralized, but the new law does the opposite in Shenzhen, one
of the Special Economic Zones where most capital is foreign and
most products are intended for export.
   At last year's congress, by contrast, legislators made bold
statements about the necessity for ambitious economic reform.
   This year, the reform program started in 1978 to introduce
market forces received several setbacks and political reform was
put on hold. Human rights was labeled ``an abstract concept'' and
control of the state-run press was tightened.
   At the start of Tuesday's session, the legislature approved a
report given by Premier Li Peng on opening day, March 20. It
stressed the need for social stability and a return to centralized
economic power.
   Li's report was a reaction to such economic problems as record
annual inflation of 36 percent, widespread corruption and scarcity
of staple goods. He recommended at least two years of austerity and
restoration of government controls over some aspects of the economy.
   Other reports approved by the legislature put new taxes and
restrictions on fledgling private and collective enterprises, the
most active part of the economy.
   Deputies also passed a budget equivalent to $77.2 billion that
devotes more money to education and agriculture and has a deficit
equal to about $2 billion.
   In its resolution approving the premier's report, the congress
called for stronger central management and adherence to such ideals
as socialist morality, collectivism, thrift and hard work.
   Members made 120 changes in Li's report, most of them minor. One
that requires feasibility studies for major policies apparently was
designed to keep powerful ministers from making decisions
recklessly.
   Another change revives a model-worker program, which seems to be
a step back toward the days when portraits of ``Socialist Worker
Heroes'' adorned post office walls.
   The law allowing citizens to sue the government takes effect in
October 1990. It gives people the right to sue officials for
specific acts but not to challenge laws or regulations.
   A Western legal expert who attended the congress said its aim
was to further centralization of power by using the threat of legal
action to restrict the often wide powers of middle-level officials.
   He said it is not designed to protect the rights of citizens
even though it is couched in such language.
   ``If an official follows the state's laws and regulations then
he is immune, but if he ignores those regulations someone might
bring him to court,'' he said. ``That is the message here.''
   As with the opening session, 84-year-old senior leader Deng
Xiaoping was absent. Deng said he excused himself to preserve his
health.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
