<FIRST>r w PM-US-CentralAmerica 4thLd-Writethru a0575 04-04 0807</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Central America, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0575,830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arias Pleased With Bipartisan Accord on Nicaragua</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Mideast Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Inserts grafs 10-11, He also, with further Fitzwater comments.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Costa Rican President Oscar Arias Sanchez said
today it's time to ``change bullets for ballots'' in Central
America, but that cannot be done without the support of Cuba and
the Soviet Union.
   Following a meeting in the Oval Office with President Bush,
Arias praised the United States for finding a joint
executive-legislative compromise on a program of almost $50 million
in aid for the Nicaraguan Contra rebels.
   ``Now people here can talk with one single voice,'' he told
reporters gathered in the White House driveway following his nearly
hour-long meeting with Bush. ``I think, this time, they are,
indeed, in good faith trying to support the efforts of the five
Central American presidents to reach democracy and peace at the
negotiating table.''
   Arias said that Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, who is
visiting President Fidel Castro in Cuba, must persuade Castro not
to support guerrillas in El Salvador if ``he supports sincerely the
Central American peace plan.''
   ``War has taught us ... that violence is not the solution,'' he
said. ``I think we have learned that we must change bullets for
ballots, and we cannot do this without the support of Cuba and the
Soviet Union.''
   Bush paused amidst a series of meetings with Mideast leaders to
get an update on the Central American situation from Arias, who won
the Nobel Peace prize two years ago for his mediation efforts in
the region.
   Neither Bush nor his guest would answer reporters' questions
during a picture-taking session at the outset of the Oval Office
meeting.
   Press secretary Marlin Fitzwater told reporters the two ``had a
very friendly and productive discussion.'' Fitzwater said Arias
asked for U.S. assistance in helping to negotiate loans with the
International Monetary Fund and World Bank to pay off Costa Rican
debts, and said Bush agreed to look into that.
   On Central American policy, the spokesman said that ``our
fundamental common ground'' with Costa Rica is the two countries'
interest in democracy in Central America. ``Both presidents agreed
that their goals were ... demobilization of the Contras and
repatriation into their country,'' Fitzwater said.
   He also said reported remarks by Soviet spokesman Gennady
Ge4rasimov about Soviet opposition to ``export of revolution'' were
``very encouraging in terms of Central America.''
   Fitzwater said the comments ``could be very significant if they
mean the reduction of Soviet military support in Nicaragua or if
they mean that Soviet surrogates would cease supporting'' leftist
guerrillas in El Salvador.
   The talks with Arias come more than two weeks after Bush and
bipartisan congressional leaders announced agreement on the new
humanitarian aid plan.
   Taking reporters' questions at the conclusion of his White House
meeting, Arias said it was crucial that the repatriation of the
counter-revolutionaries occur simultaneously with the institution
of democratic reforms by the Sandinista government headed by
President Daniel Ortega.
   Otherwise, he said, ``you cannot persuade the Contras to go back
to Nicaragua ... if you have nothing for them there. You need a big
carrot.''
   Arias noted that there long had been arguments about whether the
Contras should lay down their arms following democratization moves
by the Sandinistas, or whether they should be dismantled as a
fighting force before such steps are undertaken.
   ``I think this should be simultaneous,'' he said. ``With
repatriation there should be a democratic climate in Nicaragua or
there is no reason for them to go back.''
   Arias, however, said he told Bush he was concerned about how
free elections could be achieved in Nicaragua, noting there had
been no such elections there in some 50 years.
   ``I am really worried as a Costa Rican about the organization of
the next elections,'' he said.
   Bush acknowledged last Friday that there was ``not a snowball's
chance in hell of getting a dime'' of military aid for the
counter-revolutionaries.
   The Bush administration is demanding, as the Reagan
administration did for eight years, that the Sandinistas make good
on promises of democratization they made to the Organization of
American States in 1979, at the time they overthrew the
dictatorship of Anastasio Somoza.
   In the meantime, Arias is pushing a new plan aimed at
dismantling the Contras in exchange for free and open elections in
Nicaragua by February 1990.
   Arias scheduled the Washington visit while passing through en
route to an official visit to Canada, said White house press
secretary Marlin Fitzwater.
   Bush said last Friday that by getting humanitarian aid ``that
goes with this (February 1990) election, I am hopeful that the
Nicaraguans will go forward and do that which they give rhetorical
support for _ but that which they've failed to implement and that
means democracy _ free, certifiable elections.''
</TEXT>
