<SECOND>AM-People-Gore's Son,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gore's Son Hit By Car After Orioles' Game</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 6-year-old son of U.S. Sen. Albert Gore Jr.
was in serious but stable condition Tuesday after being hit by a
car as the two left Memorial Stadium following the Baltimore
Orioles' season opener.
   Albert Gore III suffered a broken rib, thigh fractures, a
ruptured spleen, bruised lung and a concussion, said Elaine
Freeman, a spokeswoman for Johns Hopkins Hospital.
   According to police, witnesses said the child let go of his
father's hand and was hit by a car when he ran out into the street
near the stadium.
   The driver of the car, Jasper McWilliams, 22, of suburban Middle
River, was not speeding and no charges were filed, police said.
   Gore, D-Tenn., spent the night at the hospital Monday and
remained there Tuesday.
   Gore and his wife, Tipper, who also have three daughters, live
in Arlington, Va.
   The baseball season-opener, in which the Orioles beat the Boston
Red Sox 5-4 in 11 innings, began with President George Bush
throwing the first ball.
