<DOCNO> AP890404-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 1339EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-NATO     04-04 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NATO,0644</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO Turns 40 _ Still Cautious About Soviet Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BRU2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The NATO alliance, shaped out of the
fears of Soviet expansionism, turned 40 on Tuesday with Western
officials expressing caution and uncertainty about the dramatic
changes gripping the Soviet Union.
   Manfred Woerner, secretary-general of the 16-nation North
Atlantic Treaty Organization, said the Soviet Union will still
remain a strong military power even if promised cuts are carried
out in troops and military spending.
   ``The intentions of the current Soviet leadership ... are
peaceful ones,'' Woerner told a news conference at NATO
headquarters in Brussels. Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, he
said, ``doesn't want to wage a war.''
   But he cautioned, ``There is still a risk because intentions may
change. We have no control over them. Personalities, leaders may
change.''
   Woerner's remarks capped a morning of ceremonies marking the
signing of the NATO treaty on April 4, 1949, forming a security
alliance that links the United States and Canada with Western
European nations. The Western nations joined the pact to unite
against the threat of expansionism posed by Moscow in the years
following World War II.
   Gorbachev's recent agenda of economic and social reforms and his
promises of military cuts have diminished the public's perception
of that threat and raised questions about NATO's role.
   Anniversary speeches, celebrations and a few protests held
elsewhere in Europe reflected the new situation.
   British Defense Secretary George Younger, in a speech at NATO
offices north of London, credited the alliance with helping bring
about ``the long overdue changes'' under way in Eastern Europe.
   Five members of the Christian Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament
demonstrated outside the NATO complex, undeterred by a rare spring
sprinkling of snow. NATO officials served them hot tea.
   In Oslo, Norwegian Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland called
NATO ``the most successful alliance we know'' and Foreign Minister
Thorvald Stoltenberg called it ``more important than ever.''
   A small group of protesters in Rome, including Greens Party
deputy Gianni Mattioli, organized a conference called ``40 Years Is
Enough.'' They demonstrated outside the premier's office and
particuarly objected to the scheduled relocation of a squadron of
U.S. F-16 fighters from Spain to Italy.
   A naval exercise and marching bands marked the anniversary in
Copenhagen, while a few hundred peace activists staged a
demonstration. No incidents were reported.
   Woerner, former German defense minister, led off the outdoor
celebrations at NATO headquarters on an unseasonably cold day in
Brussels.
   Military bands from Belgium, Denmark, Britain, Luxembourg and
the Netherlands marched and played music before an audience of
diplomats and military officials. The flags of the 16 member
nations were unfurled against the gray sky.
   Woerner reminded the audience that the alliance was formed out
of the post-war hostilities.
   ``Forty years ago,'' he said, ``Europe lay in ruins; the most
terrible war ever conducted had left its bloody traces of
destruction. ... Communist expansionism threatened to subjugate the
whole of Europe.''
   The allies, he said, ``have once again reached a crucial and
decisive historical junction'' as they did when they signed the
treaty.
   ``The old post-war European order is on its way out,'' he said.
``The future is an open book full of challenges, opportunities and
risks.''
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's Christian Democratic party
recommended on Monday that NATO be awarded the Nobel Peace Prize.
   In a statement, Kohl said NATO had secured ``the longest period
of European peace since the Middle Ages. We must be thankful for
that.''
   The United States, Canada and 10 European nations _ Belgium,
Britain, Denmark, France, Iceland, Italy, Luxembourg, the
Netherlands, Norway and Portugal _ were the original NATO members.
   Greece, Turkey, West Germany and Spain later joined the Alliance.
</TEXT>
