<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia-Police     04-04 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia-Police,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Namibian Police Are Combat-Hardened Veterans</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Namibia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Namibian policemen battling
black nationalist guerrillas are combat-hardened fighters more
accustomed to bush warfare than routine law enforcement.
   The black patrolmen and their mainly white South African
officers wear military uniforms and move about in heavily armored
personnel carriers equipped with machine guns.
   They have played a leading role in fighting guerrillas of the
South-West Africa People's Organization since a special police
counterinsurgency unit was formed in 1979, 13 years after the black
nationalist fighters began the war for independence from South
Africa.
   Known as ``Koevoet'' _ the Afrikaans word for crowbar _ the unit
officially was disbanded in January as a goodwill gesture after
South Africa agreed to end its rule of Namibia.
   However, most of Koevoet's estimated 3,000 men were integrated
into the regular police and were ready for combat when heavy
fighting erupted Saturday as a cease-fire was suppposed to take
effect.
   Guerrilla leaders accuse police of initiating the fighting by
hunting down guerrilla units which had no intention of staging
attacks.
   Under the U.S.-sponsored United Nations plan for Namibia's
independence, guerrilla and South African troops as well as those
of the South-West African Territorial Force were to be confined to
their bases from Saturday. The territorial police force of 8,300
men was entitled to operate freely, with full responsibility for
maintaining law and order during the transition to independence.
   More than 90 percent of Namibia's policemen and soldiers of its
territorial force are blacks. They are led by white officers,
mainly South African. Most South African army troops in Namibia are
white.
   Koevoet's history is clouded with controversy. Its effectiveness
is widely acknowleged, but many Namibians attribute its success to
ruthlessness. Several dozen of its members have been accused of
atrocities against civilians, although only a few have been
convicted.
   Koevoet claims to have killed 2,812 guerrillas between 1979 and
1988 for the loss 132 black and 19 white members.
   Leaders of the guerrilla's legal political wing in Namibia
describe Koevoet members as ``programmed killers'' who will be
required to undergo ``reorientation'' if the guerrillas win
independence elections.
   Defenders of Koevoet say the criticism is tacit acknowledgement
of the unit's prowess.
   ``Counterinsurgency work is not very easy, and sometimes things
get a little tense,'' Koevet commander Gen. Hans Dreyer said last
month. ``But without the support of the local people, we would not
have had any success.''
   In a standard Koevoet operation, four armored personnel carriers
with 10 blacks and a white commander each would head into the bush
for a week at a time, questioning villagers and looking for traces
of guerrillas.
   Koevoet trackers sometimes would follow a trail for days, even
crossing into Angola, where most of the guerrillas are based. Most
Namibian policemen are recruited in the north of the country among
the Ovambo people who are famed for their tracking and other bush
skills.
   The guerrillas almost always were on foot, and often were
mismatched when overtaken by the personnel carriers or by
helicopter gunships which Koevoet would call in.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
