<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 1345EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-EducationSpending     04-04 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Education Spending,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deficit Shouldn't Stand in Way of Handicapped Education: NEA President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal deficit should not be an obstacle
to serving all handicapped and disadvantaged students eligible for
help under federal programs, the president of the nation's largest
teachers union said Tuesday.
   ``I do not believe that the children of America created the
deficit,'' said Mary Futrell, president of the 1.9 million-member
National Education Association.
   The organization is calling for an extra $10 billion in federal
education spending to counter ``a shocking erosion'' in services
under four major programs for disadvantaged students, low-income
college students, handicapped students and students with limited
proficiency in English.
   In a report called ``Federal Education Funding: Present
Realities and Future Needs,'' the group says many federal programs
reach only a fraction of those they are meant to serve. Serving all
students currently eligible for the four programs would cost more
than $10 billion, it says.
   ``I'm not an expert so I can't say where we would get the
money,'' Futrell said at a news conference. But she said the union
has offered to sit down with Bush administration officials and
members of Congress to look at the overall budget and re-arrange
priorities.
   ``We are aware of the fact that we can't do this in one year,''
Futrell said. ``It might take five years or 10 years. But what's
important is that we recognize the problem ... and make the
commitment to fully fund these programs in 1993 or 1998.''
   The report looks specifically at Chapter 1, grants to bolster
basic skills among disadvantaged younsters; the Education for All
Handicapped Act, which helps states educate disabled youngsters;
bilingual education, grants to make sure students with native
languages other than English succeed in school; and Pell grants for
college students from low-income families.
   The NEA reported the following statistics:
   _Chapter 1. The number of students served declined from 7
million in 1980-81 to 5.7 million in 1988-89. The program reached
65 percent of eligible students in 1980-81 but only 40 percent by
1986.
   Congress provided $4.6 billion for Chapter 1 in fiscal 1989,
enough to serve 47 percent of eligible students. To serve the
estimated 8.5 million who will qualify next year would cost about
$6.9 billion, a $2.3 billion increase over current levels.
   _Handicapped. The federal share of costs to local school
districts started at 12 percent 15 years ago and was intended to
rise gradually to 40 percent. Instead it stayed at 12 percent until
1980 and has fallen to 7 percent today. To reach the 40 percent
target would cost $8.4 billion, a $6.5 billion hike over current
levels.
   _Bilingual education. Such programs serve one in 18 of students
who need help in English skills. An increase of more than $1
billion would be needed to serve all 1.6 million students states
say are eligible.
   _Pell grants. Such funds have increased slightly when adjusted
for inflation, but the increases have not come near matching the
soaring costs of postsecondary education. In addition, Congress has
``fallen far short'' of meeting its own authorized maximum fore
individual grants. Some $600 million would be needed to fully fund
the maximum $2,900 Pell grant permitted in fiscal 1990.
   The NEA report was based on charts provided by Federal Planning
Services Inc. of Washington, D.C., an independent statistical
analysis firm, and statistics from government agencies including
the Education Department and the Census Bureau.
</TEXT>
