<FIRST>r w PM-Lujan-Spill 1stLd-Writethru   04-04 0838</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lujan-Spill, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0442,810</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interior Secretary Says Spill Could Harm Oil Development</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs new from morning hearing, picks up 2nd graf
pvs: Lujan's remarks xxx</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The massive Alaskan oil spill could put the
brakes on petroleum exploration there and in other areas _ at least
temporarily _ Environmental Protection Administrator William Reilly
said today.
   ``We will take apart the environmental planning for every aspect
of oil development in Alaska and in other sensitive areas where the
environment potentially could be threatened.,'' Reilly told a House
appropriations subcommittee.
   Asked by Rep. Bob Traxler, D-Mich., if the disaster in Prince
William Sound would prompt a re-evaluation of the environmental
threat posed by oil development policy, Reilly added:
   ``We are doing that, as you know, off the coast of California
and the coast of Florida - looking at three proposed lease sales
there for oil and gas that appear to have significant environmental
concerns associated with them.
   We'll do it in Prince William Sound and look very carefully at
future contingency planning there. And we'll do it on the North
Sslope. I think we owe that to the environment. We owe that to
common sense.''
   Rep. Bill Green, R-N.Y., asked Reilly if he meant that the
administration would not move forward on a controversial proposal
for oil exploration in the Alaska National Wildlife Refuge until a
review had been completed.
   ``There is a very clear understanding that we will not move
forward if we have any significant concerns that have not been
resolved, yes sir,'' he responded.
   Reilly's comments came just a day after Interior Secretary
Manuel Lujan Jr., said the oil spill off Alaska could become the
petroleum industry's Three Mile Island if steps aren't taken to
assure the public that oil developers are capable of protecting the
environment.
   Lujan's remarks to an oil and gas industry conference Monday
suggested the massive spill last month into Prince William Sound
off Alaska by the tanker Exxon Valdez could have long lasting
effects on the petroleum industry if some public damage control is
not undertaken.
   ``It takes a long, long time to recover from these things,''
said Lujan, comparing the Exxon Valdez spill to the accident a
decade ago at the Three Mile Island nuclear plant in Pennsylvania.
The nuclear industry has yet to recover from that accident.
   ``If the image of an uncareful and uncaring industry prevails
among the U.S. public, then we can kiss goodbye the domestic oil
and gas development in (the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge),
offshore and in the public lands,'' Lujan told a conference of the
National Ocean Industries Association.
   The group represents about 235 companies involved in offshore
oil exploration and drilling.
   Lujan, nevertheless, emphasized that the Bush administration
continues to support ``environmentally sound'' oil development in
the arctic refuge and declared, ``Unless we pursue a coordinated
policy to develop this country's domestic energy sources, including
offshore oil and gas, every American will pay dearly for our
failure.''
   President Bush generally has supported offshore drilling, but in
one of his first steps as president ordered a review into the
proposed sale of oil leases involving two areas off the California
coast and one off the Everglades in Florida because of
environmental concerns.
   On the spill from the Exxon Valdez, the worst oil tanker spill
in U.S. history, Lujan said inadequate recovery equipment likely
prevented any chances of an effective cleanup within hours after
accident. The vessel ran aground during the early hours of March 24
outside the port of Valdez, Alaska.
   ``If it happened (again) someplace now you'd have the same
disastrous situation,'' the interior secretary told reporters after
his speech to the petroleum industry group.
   Lujan said a key lesson learned from the accident is that
cleanup equipment and preparedness for such a disaster must be
improved.
   ``We need to be a little bit more prepared,'' said Lujan. ``...
I understand about 80 percent of the oil was lost in the first hour
or two. I don't know that we could ever have contained it. Maybe it
got away too quick.''
   Later he told reporters, ``The kind of equipment that we have
(available) ... isn't enough to take care of a spill like this.''
He said it was found that floating containment booms broke and oil
skimmers were of little help.
   The characterization that the cleanup effort was doomed within
hours of the accident has been disputed by some Alaska fishermen,
who have complained that opportunities were missed when little was
done while relatively calm weather prevailed for two days after the
accident.
   Oil company officials have acknowledged they did not begin to
deploy cleanup booms around the hemorrhaging tanker until at least
10 hours after the accident.
   Exxon officials have blamed some of the delay on the government
for not providing an early go-ahead to use chemicals to disperse
the oil, while fishermen and state officials have accused the oil
company of misleading them as to their cleanup capabilities.
</TEXT>
