<FIRST>r i AM-Cuba-US     04-04 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba-US,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Memo Draws Strong Cuban Reply</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev-Cuba, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAVANA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba accused the United States on Tuesday of
preparing new plans to increase military and economic pressure as a
means of undermining its revolution.
   A top Communist Party official, Julian Rizo Alvarez, said the
United States once again is suffering from illusions about Cuba.
   ``As always, they are confused and they make mistakes,'' he
said. ``Today we are a harder a more difficult bone to swallow than
ever before,'' he said.
   Rizo spoke to a ceremony honoring a contingent of Cuban soldiers
returning from Angola.
   He alluded to a memo made public last week in which Secretary of
State James A. Baker III said the United States has no plans to
improve relations with Cuba because of this country's continued
``unacceptable behavior.''
   Baker's memo, Rizo said, augers ``new machinations, new
campaigns and plans to continue pressurng us militarily and
economically and to reinforce its attacks in the political
terrain.''
   He added that it seems the United States has not had enough as
yet of the ``defeats suffered in their efforts to crush us, to
erase us from the face of the earth.''
   Baker's confidential memo, first disclosed last week by The
Associated Press, said Cuba contynues to provide the Soviet Union
with major political, strategic and intelligence benefits and to
support subversive movements in the hemisphere.
   Baker said he wanted to set the record straight because there
have been reports of a ``warming trend'' between the two countries
following Cuba's agreement in December to withdraw its troops from
Angola.
</TEXT>
