<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 1429EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-B-1BGrounding     04-04 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-B-1B Grounding,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Force Finds Lubricant Problems in Many B-1B Bombers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force has discovered a problem with
lubricant levels in a wing gear box on its B-1B bomber fleet that
is slowing the return of the bombers to the air, the Pentagon said
Tuesday.
   Dan Howard, the Pentagon's chief spokesman, said the Strategic
Air Command had cleared the B-1B bomber fleet to return to flight
status on Sunday as individual planes underwent a final safety
check, and more than 35 of the planes would be flying Tuesday.
   During the course of the final safety checks, however, Air Force
mechanics began discovering a problem with gear boxes that are part
of the assembly to move the wings back and forth, the spokesman
continued.
   Howard said the Air Force now expects roughly 90 of the B-1B's
to be certified for flight operations by the weekend.
   The problem involves a loss of the lubricant contained inside a
sealed gear box that handles what is known as the angle gear drive
shaft, Howard said. That angle gear drive shaft is a key component
of the wing-moving assembly.
   According to the Air Force, of 80 B-1B's receiving the final
safety inspection so far, 70 showed insufficient lubricant levels
inside that gear box.
   Howard denied Tuesday the Air Force had uncovered any evidence
showing that a loss of lubricant in that gear box was the cause of
a March 27 incident that led to a week-long grounding of the B-1B
fleet.
   In that incident, a B-1B undergoing a pre-flight check at Dyess
Air Force Base, Texas, suffered a tear in a fuel tank when the left
wing swung too far forward.
   Howard disclosed Tuesday that accident investigators probing the
mishap had discovered a fractured ``quill shaft'' in a main wing
gear box and a fractured ``angle gear drive shaft.''
   Other sources, who insisted on anonymity, said the Air Force
``does now suspect that a lubricant seal problem led to the March
27 mishap,'' probably by allowing too much torque pressure to build
up on the shaft.
   ``At first blush, that's exactly what we believe caused the wing
to go too far,'' said one source. ``There's a very definite
connection.''
   Howard, referring to the two fractured shafts, said ``we don't
know what sequence those occurred in.''
   ``We don't know what the first cause was yet _ whether it was a
procedural problem, a maintenance problem or a hardware problem.
But simply in the course of investigating every possible problem
that they could have had, they did discover this potential problem
(with the lubricant).''
   The Air Force said the sealed gear boxes were manufactured by
the Sundstrand Corp. and when mechanics were finding one with
insufficient lubricant, it was being replaced and sent off to the
contractor for repair.
   ``I think it's fortunate we had the incident at Dyess on the
ground, because that led to the kind of detailed investigation that
enabled us to catch something that we might not have caught,''
added one Air Force source.
   The four-engine B-1B is the first addition to the manned bomber
force in more than 25 years. To improve its performance, the plane
features wings that can be swept forward or backward in flight. The
wings are normally swept back for high-speed attack runs and
forward for takeoffs and landings.
   Built by the Rockwell International Corp., the B-1B has a
maximum speed of about 1,000 mph and a range of more than 7,000
miles.
   The Air Force built 100 of the planes during the Reagan
administration to modernize the old B-52 bomber force while it
developed the new B-2 stealth bomber. Three B-1B's have been lost
in accidents, leaving 97 in the fleet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890404-0094 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 1430EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-People     04-04 0989</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,1031</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Bond star Timothy Dalton and actress Vanessa
Redgrave won undisclosed libel damages Tuesday for newspaper
allegations that he was rude to his producer and that colleagues
dreaded her arrival on a movie set.
   Their lawyer, Oscar Beuselinck, told High Court Judge Michael
Davies the settlement had been reached with Mirror Group Newspapers
Ltd.
   The Sunday Mirror alleged in October that Dalton was rude and
behaved unprofessionally toward producer Cubby Brocolli during
filming of ``License to Kill.''
   Beuselinck told the court the newspaper also claimed Redgrave
``was in the habit of making life impossible whenever she appeared
on a film set'' and that people making the movie ``were at one
stage dreading her arrival on the set of the film.''
   Julie Scott-Bayfield, the newspaper's lawyer, said the Sunday
Mirror withdrew the ``wholly untrue'' allegations and apologized
unreservedly.
   Neither Dalton nor Redgrave were in court but Beuselinck said
after the hearing: ``Miss Redgrave is delighted that this matter
has been resolved and Mr. Dalton will almost certainly give his
money to charity.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
