<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Astronaut Frederick ``Rick'' Hauck, who commanded
the first post-Challenger mission, said he felt some vulnerability
as Discovery rocketed into space last September.
   The anxiety started about six minutes into the jarring ride,
long after the solid-fuel rocket boosters had fallen away, but
while a trio of main engines were still blazing.
   ``I remember thinking this is amazing that human beings can put
together machinery like this,'' recalled Hauck, a veteran of three
shuttle missions. ``And I remember thinking, I hope this thing
holds together.''
   Hauck left the National Aeronautics and Space Administration on
Monday for a Pentagon post. The 47-year-old Navy captain and
Vietnam-era combat pilot said he will serve as an adviser to the
chief of naval operations beginning in May.
