<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 1436EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-Plane     04-04 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Plane,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Demand Death For North Korean Plane Bomber</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SEL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors demanded the death
sentence Tuesday for a professed North Korean spy who told the
court she wants to die to atone for killing 115 people in the 1987
bombing of a South Korean airliner.
   Prosecutor Lee Sang-hyung also blamed North Korean President Kim
Il Sung and ``the dictatorship in North Korea for the grave crime
of killing the passengers.'' It was ``an unpardonable crime to
mankind,'' he said.
   Lawyer Ahn Dong-il argued his client, Kim Hyon-hui, was ``forced
to commit the act and it is someone else who needs to be punished _
North Korea.''
   Ms. Kim, 27, was a ``scapegoat of the world's most isolated
communist dictatorship,'' Ahn said to yells of abuse from relatives
of victims.
   ``Why do you keep her alive?'' some screamed. ``Kill her!''
   Scores of other relatives were kept out of the courthouse by
hundreds of police and security agents who ringed the building.
   In her final testimony, Ms. Kim told the court: ``I am really
sorry for relatives of the victims. I feel like dying to atone for
what I did.''
   She, too, blamed the Korean leader and his son and heir, whom
she says ordered her to bomb the plane. ``I now curse Kim Il Sung
and Kim Jong Il endlessly,'' she said, sobbing into a handkerchief.
   The verdict and sentence will be issued April 25.
   Lee said Ms. Kim might deserve sympathy because she was a
``puppet'' of North Korea and had repented.
   ``But as a signatory to the Montreal Convention that governs the
safety of civil aviation, the Republic of Korea is obliged to
severely punish the defendant without fail, irrespective of
ideology,'' he said.
   Ahn said Ms. Kim should be kept alive to counter Pyongyang's
charges that she is a South Korean agent and that the bombing was a
frame-up by Seoul authorities.
   Government officials have indicated Ms. Kim may get a
presidential pardon because they say she was duped by North Korea
and has repented.
   She said on South Korean TV in January 1988 that she planted the
bomb as part of a North Korean plot to disrupt the summer Olympics
in Seoul. North Korea denies involvement.
   Police explosives expert Lt. Kim Moon-Ho testified Tuesday that
the mixture of explosives used in the bomb was so powerful it would
have destroyed the aircraft in less than a second.
   ``There would be no time, no chance, to contact anybody,'' he
said. Details of the bomb come from Ms. Kim since little plane
wreckage was found.
   The Korean Air Boeing 707 disappeared Nov. 29, 1987, on a flight
from Baghdad to Seoul over the Andaman Sea as it approached the
Burmese coast.
   Ms. Kim said she and another intelligence agent pretending to be
Japanese tourists planted the bomb when they flew from Baghdad to
Abu Dhabi.
   The pair were arrested in Bahrain shortly afterward and
attempted to take cyanide hidden in cigarettes. The other agent, an
elderly man, died. But Ms. Kim recovered and was extradited to
Seoul.
   In South Korea, defendants must stand trial even if they confess.
</TEXT>
