<SECOND>PM-Visitor-AIDS, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0530,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dutch Visitor With AIDS Detained</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf to CORRECT that conference begins Wednesday, sted
today. Deletes now extraneous 5th graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congresswoman is trying to win the
release of a Dutch visitor who was detained at a Minnesota airport
because he has AIDS.
   Hans Paul Verhoef, 31, of Rotterdam, was being held by the
Immigration and Naturalization Service, which declared he cannot
enter the United States with an infectious and communicable
disease, said Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif.
   Verhoef had planned to attend the national Lesbian and Gay
Health Conference that begins in San Francisco on Wednesday,
according to Steve Huber, a conference spokesman.
   ``We do not believe the intent behind the immigration law was to
exclude tourists,'' said Pelosi, who is approaching the U.S.
attorney general for a waiver that would allow Verhoef to proceed
to San Francisco. Federal law prohibits people with AIDS from
visiting the United States without such a waiver.
   Verhoef was taken to the Scott County Jail, about 20 miles from
the Minneapolis-St. Paul airport, after U.S. Customs officials
discovered the drug AZT in his baggage on Sunday, according to a
friend who was with him.
   Steve Morin, an aide to Pelosi, said Verhoef told customs and
immigration employees he had AIDS when he was questioned about the
AZT, a drug used to treat people infected with the human
immunodeficiency virus.
   ``He didn't try to hide it,'' Morin said. ``We also question
this on humanitarian grounds, putting someone in jail under these
circumstances.''
</TEXT>
