<FIRST>r w AM-US-Namibia     04-04 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Namibia,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Namibia, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>US Calls On SWAPO To Pull Back Into Angola</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States on Tuesday urged guerrillas
of the South-West African People's Organization to pull back into
Angola and allow the Namibian independence process to get under way.
   The U.S. statement came as fighting continued for the fourth day
in Namibia between thousands of Soviet-backed SWAPO guerrillas and
South African troops and local police.
   ``SWAPO's intention apparently was to establish bases in
Namibia, in clear violation'' of a U.S.-brokered peace agreement
signed last December. The pact, negotiated over two years by
Assistant Secretary of State Chester Crocker, calls for Cuba to
pull its troops out of Angola and for South Africa to grant
independence to neighboring Namibia.
   The agreement went into effect April 1 but was threatened by the
fighting, which has claimed 180 lives, according to police figures
that could not be independently verified.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said the United
States does not think the agreement is in danger of unraveling ``at
this point.''
   U.S. diplomats are still in touch with the Soviet Union, Cuba
and Angola, asking them to use their influence with SWAPO to
restore calm in Namibia, she said. The United States, for its part,
is asking South Africa to rein in its troops, who were scheduled to
begin demobilizing Sunday once the peace agreement went into effect
and U.N. peacekeepers were deployed.
   ``The United States position is that SWAPO must withdraw the
forces it has sent into Namibia to north of the 16th parallel in
Angola,'' Ms. Tutwiler said. Under the peace agreement, SWAPO
guerrillas were supposed to stay in their Angolan bases, about 100
miles north of the Namibian border.
   She said that despite rebel claims, there was no doubt that the
guerrillas had crossed the border on Saturday.
   Guerrilla officials and the Angolan government claim the
fighters have been in Namibia for some time and fired in self
defense after security forces attacked them.
   Villagers in northern towns, most of whom support the rebels,
said they believe the guerrillas left Angola to return home and did
not expect a fight because the independence process officially has
begun.
   Asked whether the U.N. force, which has just 1,000 of its
planned 4,650 soldiers deployed so far, should have foreseen the
SWAPO incursion, Ms. Tutwiler replied that ``hindsight is always
great, but I don't think anybody anticipated this.''
</TEXT>
