<DOCNO> AP890404-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 1444EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Elections     04-04 0840</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Elections,0865</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir's Plan Centers on Elections But Palestinians Reject Terms</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Mideast, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The peace proposals Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir will submit to President Bush focus on elections in the
occupied territories to choose Palestinians who would negotiate
with Israel on limited self-government.
   Many prominent Palestinians welcome the idea of balloting but
argue that free elections cannot be held as long as Israeli troops
occupy the West Bank and the Gaza Strip.
   In interviews and through his aides, Shamir said he was willing
to have Palestinians choose mayors to speak for major population
centers or political figures to represent the whole region.
   The elected Palestinians would then meet with Israeli
negotiators to work out a temporary solution for the 1 million
residents of the West Bank and the 650,000 inhabitants of the Gaza
Strip.
   The most Palestinians could expect from this process would be
limited self-rule with Israeli troops still stationed in the
occupied lands. But Shamir has said troops could be pulled out of
population centers once an autonomy scheme was agreed upon.
   Under Shamir's proposals, the final status of the West Bank and
Gaza Strip would be the subject of further negotiations after
autonomy was implemented.
   Shamir's advisers also hint he is ready to release some
Palestinian prisoners and take other steps to reduce tension.
However, they link any change to a truce in the Palestinian
uprising _ intefadeh in Arabic _ in which 419 Palestinians and 18
Israelis have died since December 1987.
   ``The condition is that life in Judea and Samaria (West Bank)
must return to normal. The intefadeh must end,'' said Yossi
Ahimeir, a Shamir spokesman. The Shamir ideas closely parallel the
1978 U.S.-mediated Camp David Accords signed by Egypt and Israel
but rejected by the Palestinians and Jordan. The major difference
is that Shamir proposes electing negotiators before autonomy is
implemented instead of members of an autonomous council after
self-government is defined in talks.
   ``I believe that this will be the one big and important
contribution that Mr. Shamir is bringing to Washington,'' said an
Israeli official who described the proposal as a ``major change''
in the government's position.
   Shamir, however, rules out direct or indirect talks with the
PLO, which means elected representatives could not act as
intermediaries.
   He gives Palestinians little hope of seeing an end to occupation
because he has rejected Palestinian demands for statehood and
refused to endorse the idea of returning any captured land to Arab
sovereignty.
   In this, the right-wing prime minister takes a harder line than
Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin and Finance Minister Shimon Peres,
the leaders of the left-of-center Labor Party which shares power in
the coalition government.
   Labor supports returning some of the captured land in exchange
for peace agreements.
   Municipal elections have been held twice in the West Bank since
Israel captured the land from Jordan in the 1967 Middle East War.
In the last balloting in 1976, voters chose 23 mayors _ nearly all
of them supporters of the PLO.
   Only six remain in office with most of the rest having been
deported or deposed by Israel for nationalist activities.
   In the Gaza Strip, elections were last held in 1946, under
Egyptian rule.
   The main flaw in Shamir's plan is that he has been unable to
find Palestinians willing to go along with the elections proposal.
But some Palestinians have met secretly with the prime minister or
openly with military officials to discuss the idea.
   Saeb Erakat, a political science professor at the An Najah
University in the West Bank city of Nablus, said that if, as the
PLO has proposed, Israeli troops withdraw and turn over the
occupied territory to U.N. peacekeepers, ``then we will consider
elections.''
   He said electing city officials would be meaningless if
occupation persisted.
   ``Will elected mayors be able to prevent arrests, stop the
deportation of Palestinian leaders, halt the confiscation of land
or the closure of schools? We would just wind up electing people
who have the authority to collect the garbage,'' said Erakat.
   Soon after the uprising against Israeli occupation began, a
group of prominent Palestinians in Jerusalem in January 1988
presented a 14-point list of demands that included a call for
elections.
   The idea was hotly debated among Palestinians until Bethlehem
Mayor Elias Freij proposed a cease-fire in the intefadeh, or
uprising, in exchange for elections and the release of thousands of
Palestinian prisoners.
   PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat responded by threatening to shoot
anyone who proposed a truce and graffiti appeared on Bethlehem
walls threatening Freij's life. Support for the idea rapidly waned.
   Hanna Siniora, editor of the pro-PLO daily Al Fajr and a
proponent of the 14-point list, said there was deep suspicion that
Shamir was meeting with Palestinians and talking about elections in
an effort to perpetuate ``the illusion that there are alternatives
to the PLO.''
   ``So far, what we see from Shamir is an attempt to repackage
what was refused earlier, autonomy under Camp David,'' said
Siniora, a leading moderate.
</TEXT>
