<FIRST>r i AM-Refuseniks     04-04 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refuseniks,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Refusenik Given Permission to Leave for Medical Treatment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Jewish refusenik whose emigration case had been
pressed by British officials said Tuesday he was given permission
to receive medical treatment in London.
   The case of Georgy Samoilovich has been on a list British Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher intends to raise with Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev, who is to arrive in London on Wednesday.
   ``Undoubtedly, the two events are connected,'' Samoilovich, 66,
said in a telephone interview. ``This is happening only thanks to
the work of the two governments, the British and the American, and
the work of my friends throughout the world.''
   In London, a Foreign Office spokesman speaking on condition of
anonymity said the action ``reflects a considerable achievement in
Anglo-Soviet relations.''
   The list Mrs. Thatcher plans to discuss includes the wife of
Oleg Gordievsky, a top Soviet spy who defected to the West in 1985,
officials confirmed Tuesday. The Foreign Office refused to say how
many people are on the list.
   The Soviet decision came a day after a protest by about 40
refuseniks in front of the British Embassy in Moscow who said they
hoped the talks in London would help resolve their cases.
   Samoilovich, who has life-threatening lymphoma, first applied to
emigrate in 1979. He was sacked from a defense-related job and the
Soviets have refused repeated applications on grounds he was
involved with secret work. Samoilovich argues that everything he
knew is now public material.
   Officials of the Soviet visa office summoned him Tuesday and
told him the prohibition on his emigration due to access to state
secrets had been removed, Samoilovich said.
   Refuseniks accuse Soviet officials of applying regulations that
allow them to deny emigration because of access to secrets in many
inappropriate cases.
   He said he was told he would be allowed to leave for medical
treatment in London, and that his wife Vera and son, Viktor, would
be allowed to emigrate after they submit new documents to Soviet
officials.
   Samoilovich said he hoped to receive his international passport
Wednesday or Thursday after using his internal Soviet passport to
prepare legal documents testifying that the entire family wishes to
leave.
   Once in London he said he hoped not to return to the Soviet
Union, but would wait in Britain for his family. The family hopes
to settle in the United States, where it has close friends,
Samoilovich said.
   Samoilovich has been offered free medical treatment both at
London's state-run Royal Marsden Hospital and in the United States
at the Hackensack Medical College in New Jersey.
   A Geneva-based agency that helps to resettle Soviet Jews said
Tuesday the number who arrived in Vienna in March was 3,893, a
10-year high.
   But it said only 114, or 2.9 percent, wanted to go to Israel.
Most of the rest intended to go to the United States, said Reghina
Boucault, spokeswoman for the Intergovernmental Committee for
Migration.
   Jewish emigration from the Soviet Union reached a peak of 51,328
in 1979 but then dropped sharply and in the mid-1980s only about
1,000 a year were released.
   In the past two years, however, many long-time refuseniks have
been permitted to leave the Soviet Union and the number of emigres
increased to more than 20,000 in 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
