<FIRST>r w AM-US-Haiti     04-04 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Haiti,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Denies Giving Haiti List of Drug-Trafficking Officers</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON (AP ) _ The State Department denied Tuesday that it
had given the Haitian government a list of officers it wanted
cashiered from the that nation's army because of alleged
involvement in drug trafficking.
   ``No, we did not'' provide such a list, State Department
spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler told reporters when she was asked
about the suggestion that the U.S. demand had led to Sunday's
attempted coup d'etat.
   She said that last month Richard Melton, a department envoy,
discussed with Haitian President Prosper Avril ``the broad range of
U.S. interests in Haiti, which would include narcotic cooperation,
along with democratic reforms, respect for human rights and
credible development programs.''
   ``We did not deliver any list of names; nor did we give any kind
of ultimatum,'' Ms. Tutwiler said.
   She said was unable to comment on the announcement by Haitian
state television that the three military commanders who led the
coup attempt had been given safe passage to the United States via
the Dominican Republic.
   Asked whether the trio had sought asylum in the United States,
Ms. Tutwiler said, ``Not that I'm aware of.''
   Haitian radio had reported Thursday that four high-ranking army
officers were discharged for drug trafficking a day after Melton
had tied the resumption of U.S. aid to progress in stopping the
drug trade.
   A $90 million U.S. aid package was suspended after November 1987
elections were aborted by thugs protected by soldiers.
</TEXT>
