<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Italy-Train     04-04 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Italy-Train,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Toll Reaches Eight in Derailment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SEVERO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers on Tuesday pulled three more
bodies from the wreckage of a train that derailed and slammed into
a station in this southern city, bringing the death toll to eight.
   Authorities said 17 people were injured, one critically, in the
accident Monday. Casualties occurred both on the train and in the
station.
   Police identified the dead as the two train engineers, the chief
of the station and two assistants, a railroad worker, a passenger
on the train and a passenger in the station.
   The eight-car train derailed as it entered the station. Two cars
slammed into the station wall, demolishing the bar, ticket booth,
and freight and baggage section.
   Railroad authorities said the train apparently arrived at the
station at a greater speed than the customary 18 mph. The Italian
news agency AGI reported the train was traveling at more than 60
mph.
   National Transportation Minister Giorgio Santuz ordered an
investigation into the crash.
