<FIRST>r a AM-TurkeyPoint     04-04 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey Point,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leak Problem Prolongs Nuke Plant Shutdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Turkey Point nuclear plant already off line
because operators failed routine retesting was shut down completely
after technicians discovered a tiny cooling-water leak, officials
said Tuesday.
   The leak was found in the weld around a tube holding instruments
that measure conditions in the core of the Unit 3 reactor, said
Nuclear Regulatory Commission spokesman Ken Clark.
   Several leaking and cracked tubes were found in the same
location in January, forcing Florida Power &amp; Light Co. to shut the
reactor down at that time as well.
   ``A weeping tube in and of itself normally is not serious, but a
situation like this deteriorates, and the utility usually shuts it
down,'' Clark said.
   Until the leak was discovered Saturday, Unit 3 had been on ``hot
standby'' in the wake of the NRC's discovery that half of the plant
operators taking regular recertification tests had failed. The leak
forced the utility to completely shut down the reactor.
   NRC examiners are expected to review later in the week the
performance of all the plant's reactor operators, a process that
usually takes several days.
   Repairing the leak and retesting the reactor and the
cooling-water system will delay Unit 3's restart even longer,
utility spokeswoman Stacey Shaw said. The utility originally had
hoped to get the reactor back on line by the weekend, but the
delays are likely to add another week, she said.
   ``We're moving along a step at a time,'' said Ms. Shaw.
   The other Turkey Point reactor, Unit 4, is down for routine
refueling and is projected to go back on line in mid- to late
April, she said.
   The NRC has hit Turkey Point with about $1 million in fines over
the past five years for safety and security violations, identifying
the plant as one of the nation's 10 worst. Ralph Nader's
environmental group, Public Citizen, has also called it one of the
worst-managed commercial facilities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
