<FIRST>r i AM-Peru-Violence     04-04 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru-Violence,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peru Attack Reveals Weakness in Halting Rebel Insurgency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is losing its battle against
leftist insurgents, newspapers and magazines said Tuesday, one week
after guerrillas wiped out a jungle police post, killing 13 and
injuring 14 others.
   Last week, 24 policemen and 26 villagers died in other violence
linked to the rebel group known as the Shining Path.
   Also on Tuesday, leftist Tupac Amaru rebels exploded six bombs
in downtown Lima, wounding two pedestrians and causing minor
damage. On Monday, Shining Path guerrillas killed 10 men and women
in central Huancavelica state for selling food to soldiers.
   But less than a month ago, the government vowed to review its
anti-insurgency policy, which media reports said is compromised by
the country's economic crisis and mismanagement.
   In the police post attack, troops reached Uchiza only 12 hours
after fighting began, even though Prime Minister Armando Villanueva
was in touch by radio throughout and promised quick reinforcements,
news reports said.
   Uchiza, located 245 miles northeast of Lima, is an hour's flight
from Lima and five minutes by helicopter from a police base in
Santa Lucia. Officials said soldiers could not reach the town
earlier because bad weather prohibited flights, and travel by land
was ruled out for fear of mines.
   ``The explanations have not been satisfactory. They are open to
further questioning,'' said El Comercio, Peru's leading newspaper,
in an editorial.
   Political infighting and poor coordination among police,
military and the government have crippled the fight against
insurgents, the newspaper said.
   ``Police have once again paid with blood for the incapacity of
this government to confront terrorism,'' according to the Lima
magazine, Oiga.
   Caretas, another magazine, said the attack highlighted the
insurgency's superiority in manpower and weapons.
   The government is strapped by Peru's worst economic crisis this
century. Inflation is expected to reach 10,000 percent this year.
   Rumors of military coups have surfaced repeatedly in the past
six months.
   More than 14,000 deaths and $10 billion in damage have been
attributed to the Shining Path guerrillas since 1980, when the
rebels turned from propaganda to violence in their fight for a
Marxist state.
   Uchiza is situated in the heart of Peru's cocaine-producing
jungle, where rebels protect drug runners in exchange for weapons
and money.
</TEXT>
