<FIRST>r i AM-Czech-Rights     04-04 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czech-Rights,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czechoslovak Court Upholds Sentences Against Activists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court on Tuesday convicted an
activist for distributing leaflets and sentenced him to four months
in prison Tuesday, and an appeals court upheld sentences for seven
others in a crackdown on dissent.
   The court in the central city of Brno convicted Jarolsav Popelka
of disturbing public order, said dissident sources in Prague.
   Popelka, 32, was arrested March 24. He had handed out flyers
last year calling for the resignation of a hard-line communist
leader and for genuine reforms and environmental protection.
   Also on Tuesday, Judge Jan Roit upheld convictions against Jana
Petrova, a 22-year-old peace activist, and Ota Veverka, 32,
stemming from banned protests in January, said Charter 77 activist
Anna Sabatova. On Feb. 22, Ms. Petrova was sentenced to nine months
in prison and Sabatova received 12 months in prison.
   Ms. Petrova and Veverka were among dissidents who tried to lay
flowers Jan. 16 in Wenceslas Square in memory of Jan Palach, a
student who burned himself alive 20 years earlier to protest the
presence of Soviet troops in his homeland following the 1968
invasion that crushed communist-led reforms.
   The appeal hearing also left unchanged suspended sentences for
five other activists, Charter 77 signatories Jana Sternova and
David Nemec, Petr Placak of the youth group Czech Children,
Stanislav Penc of the John Lennon Peace Club and Charter 77
spokesman Alexander Vondra. They had received suspended sentences
ranging between two and six months at the Feb. 22 trial.
   More than 50 supporters applauded and cheered the defendants at
Prague Municipal Court and chanted ``We are with you!'' when the
seven were escorted out, said sources speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Security was reported tight in the area and police checked
identities of those entering the court.
   In Moravia, south of Brno, the trial of Charter 77 activist
Tomas Hradilek began Tuesday, Ms. Sabatova told The Associated
Press in Vienna.
   Hradilek, one of this year's Charter spokesmen, has been charged
with inciting others to rebellion through mass media and slandering
the country abroad. He could face a jail term of up to five years.
   Officials postponed a third trial scheduled for Tuesday against
two activists who protested police brutality used to disperse the
crowds in January, said activists and emigre sources contacted in
Vienna.
   Vlasta Chramostova and Libusa Silhanova, both Charter 77
signatories, face up to one year in jail for a letter they wrote
protesting the police break-up of the banned rallies. No new date
was set for their trial, the sources said.
   The police violence in January also drew criticism from
thousands of establishment intellectuals who signed at least three
different petitions to the government protesting the police actions
and the detention of prominent dissidents including banned
playwright Vaclav Havel.
   Havel was sentenced to nine months in prison in February in
connection with the January demonstrations. His sentence was
reduced by one month by an appeals court March 21.
</TEXT>
