<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 2156EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i BC-Haiti-Chronology     04-04 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Haiti-Chronology,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chronology of Events in Haiti</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Haiti, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Chronology of events in Haiti:
   Oct. 22, 1957 _ Francois ``Papa Doc'' Duvalier becomes president
in disputed election and in 1964 proclaims himself president for
life.
   April 21, 1971 _ Duvalier dies and 19-year-old Jean-Claude
``Baby Doc'' Duvalier becomes president.
   Feb. 7, 1986 _ Duvalier flees to exile in France after a month
of anti-government unrest leaves more than 50 people dead. A
three-man junta led by Duvalier's army chief of staff, Lt. Gen.
Henri Namphy, takes power.
   March 29, 1987 _ Voters overwhelmingly approve a new
constitution putting elections for a president and National
Assembly in the hands of a civilian election commission.
   Nov. 29 _ Election Day. Thugs kill at least 34 voters and
confiscate ballots. The election is called off three hours after it
begins. Namphy and junta dissolve election commission. The United
States suspends $70 million in aid in protest.
   Jan. 17, 1988 _ Leslie Manigat, a 57-year-old university
professor, is elected president in the newly scheduled elections.
Few Haitians vote, and most opposition leaders refuse to
participate.
   June 19 _ Troops storm the National Palace, deposing Manigat and
replacing him with Namphy. Namphy abolishes the National Assembly a
day later.
   Sept. 17 _ Namphy is ousted in a coup led by noncommissioned
officers and exiled in the neighboring Dominican Republic.
   Sept. 18 _ Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril, chief of the Presidential
Guard and a former Duvalier adviser, declares himself president.
   March 13, 1989 _ Avril partially restores the suspended 1987
constitution.
   March 28 _ Four high-ranking army officers are reportedly
accused of drug trafficking and discharged. The action comes one
day after a U.S. official ties resumption of U.S. aid to progress
in stopping the drug trade.
   April 2 _ Gunfire breaks out at the presidential palace. The
government later says it has foiled a coup attempt by rebel
officers. The U.S. Embassy says loyal soldiers rescued Avril as he
was being driven away to be deported.
   April 3 _ Avril goes on national television to announce that the
coup has ended unsuccessfully and says power-hungry soldiers were
behind it.
   April 4 _ Government placates rebel soldiers by releasing and
deporting three army officers who led the coup attempt against
Avril. Rebel soldiers accept new commander and insurgency seems
over.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890404-0117 </DOCNO>
