<FIRST>r i AM-France-Lebanon     04-04 0136</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Lebanon,0141</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Intellectuals Ask For Lebanese Citizenship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a gesture of solidarity with an embattled
country, 68 French journalists, artists and intellectuals applied
together Tuesday to become citizens of Lebanon.
   The group, including journalist Jean-Francois Revel, film
director Rene Tavernier and philosopher Andre Glucksmann, presented
their applications at the Lebanese Embassy.
   In a statement, they said Lebanese citizenship was ``synonymous
with independence, with coexistence among peoples and religions.''
   ``Without of course renouncing our nationality, we wish to
acquire Lebanese nationality as well, to share _ at least
symbolically _ the fate of a country threatened with death,'' the
statement said.
   Hundreds of other people accompanied the group when they
presented their applications, waving Lebanese flags and banners
reading ``Save Our Lebanon.''
   Lebanon has been torn by civil war for 14 years.
