<DOCNO> AP890404-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 1628EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-CentralAmerica     04-04 0849</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Central America,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arias Welcomes Bush Efforts in Central America</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev-Cuba Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Costa Rican President Oscar Arias on Tuesday
said President Bush's efforts on Central American peace are welcome
after the ``lip service'' of the Reagan years, and should be an
example for the Cubans and Soviets.
   Arias, who met separately with Bush and Vice President Dan
Quayle, endorsed the administration's plan for non-lethal aid to
the Nicaraguan Contra rebels, a plan developed with bipartisan
support from congressional leaders.
   ``Now people here can talk with one single voice,'' he said, in
contrast to years of division among members of Congress and the
Reagan administration.
   As for the situation in Nicaragua itself, he said he was
concerned about the elections scheduled for February 1990 and said
steps assuring fairness must be taken, including giving all parties
access to television and other mass media.
   Asked whether the nearly $50 million in non-military aid
recommended for the Contras would not undermine the Central
American presidents' proposal to disband the rebel army, Arias told
reporters, ``These people need some support.''
   He said disbanding of the Contras and returning them to
Nicaragua must occur simultaneously with democratic reforms by the
Sandinista government.
   The U.S. decision not to revive military aid to the Contras
should spur reciprocal action by the Cubans and Soviets in El
Salvador, added the Costa Rican, who won the Nobel peace prize for
his efforts in bringing the five Central American presidents to a
regional accord in 1987.
   Arias said he told Cuban President Fidel Castro that in view of
the Bush's emphasis on non-military Contra aid, ``It was time for
him ... if he supports our peace plan ... to stop supporting the
guerrillas in El Salvador.''
   Arias also urged action by Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev,
who is currently on a visit to Cuba.
   ``If he supports sincerely the Central American peace plan he
has to ... persuade Fidel Castro not to keep the support of the
guerrillas in El Salvador. War has taught us in Central America
that violence is not the solution. We have learned that we must
change bullets by ballots and we can only do this with the support
of the Cubans and the Soviet Union,'' he said.
   The United States has accused the Soviets, through their aid to
Cuba and Nicaragua, of supporting the leftist rebels in El Salvador
where the government is backed by the United States.
   U.S. officials also estimate that the Soviets provide $1 billion
a year, half in military aid and half in economic assistance, to
the Nicaraguan government opposed by the U.S.-backed Contras.
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Tuesday that
reported remarks by Soviet spokesman Gennady Gerasimov about Soviet
opposition to ``export of revolution'' were very encouraging in
terms of Central America.
   Those comments ``could be very significant if they mean the
reduction of Soviet military support in Nicaragua or if they mean
that Soviet surrogates would cease supporting'' guerrillas in El
Salvador, said Fitzwater.
   In his Oval Office meeting with Bush, Arias spoke of a need to
have the United States and other democracies scrutinize the
election rules set up by the Nicaraguan government as well as next
February's election itself, an administration source said.
   Later, Arias told reporters in a photo session with Quayle that
the Nicaraguans must allow establishment of an independent
television station, with access by opposition parties, as part of
the proof that its elections will be free and fair.
   The Central American presidents had agreed that ``there should
be equal opportunity and equal access to all mass media by all
political parties. Otherwise it will be very difficult to talk
about free elections,'' he said.
   He also said time must be allowed for such things as voter
registration and fair campaigning.
   Comparing the Bush administration to the Reagan years, Arias
said, ``I breathe a new atmosphere, a new environment, because I
have no doubts Mr. Bush and the Bush administration is going to
sincerely support the Guatemala accord, the Arias plan'' for
Central American peace.
   ``This is something that in the past that I got some lip service
when people mentioned they were happy with our efforts to
democratize and bring peace to Central America, the neogtiating
table,'' Arias said about the Reagan years. ``I think that now they
are quite sincere and they are doing what they are doing in good
faith.''
   He said he had discussed with Bush his concerns about making
sure the Nicaraguan elections are fair.
   ``I am really worried as a Costa Rican about the organization of
the next elections,'' he said, though he also said he has no reason
to doubt the Sandinistas commitment to fulfilling their promises.
   He noted arguments about whether the Contras should lay down
their arms following democratization moves by the Sandinistas, or
whether they should be dismantled as a fighting force first.
   ``I think this should be simultaneous,'' he said. ``With
repatriation there should be a democratic climate in Nicaragua or
there is no reason for them to go back.''
</TEXT>
