<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Adoption     04-04 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Adoption,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rules Against Couple In Adoption Case Gripping Italy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PIA HINCKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The law prevailed over the heart Tuesday as a family
court refused to return a 3-year-old Filipino girl to the Italian
couple who illegally adopted her.
   The case of Serena Cruz has gripped Italy for weeks, provoking
newspaper editorials, petition drives and even a hunger strike.
   The tearful parents, Rosanna and Francesco Giubergia, announced
they will appeal to the European Court of Human Rights in
Strasbourg, France, to get the child back.
   The case focused attention on Italy's adoption system and the
reasons that have led hundreds of Italian families to look abroad
to adopt children.
   ``The family violated the codes of the law but not those of the
heart,'' said an editorial in Il Popolo, newspaper of the dominant
Christian Democrat Party.
   Serena was brought to Italy from the Phillipines by the
Giubergia family in January 1987 and taken away from them by a
judge last month.
   The couple, from Racconigi, near Turin, admitted they lied in
the adoption procedure to skirt the red tape. Francesco Giubergia,
36, head of shipping for the state railway in Turin, had gone to
Manila and declared that he fathered the child.
   The couple legally adopted a Filipino boy in 1985 after Mrs.
Giuberia, 34, was advised by her doctors not to have children.
   A judge ruled they could no longer have custody of Serena on
grounds it would only encourage illegal adoptions, and placed the
child in an orphanage March 16.
   In Tuesday's ruling, the Family Court in Turin said the child
had not suffered psychological damage from the three-week
separation and therefore will be placed with a new, legal family.
   Residents of Racconigi, 20 miles southwest of Turin, have formed
a ``Committee of Solidarity with Serena'' and gathered 70,000
signatures on a petition urging President Francesco Cossiga to
intervene.
   Cossiga asked Justice Minister Giuliano Vassalli to look into
the case. Vassalli then met with the family but said the court had
the right to decide.
   According to a report released last week by the Institute for
Political and Social Studies in Rome, requests for adoption of
foreign children in Italy have increased as much as 1,000 percent
between 1984 and 1987.
   The report, entitled ``A House for Every Child: 1984-1987,''
said that about three-quarters of the foreign adoptions in Italy
are not done through official procedures and are legalized only
after the child has been brought to the country.
</TEXT>
