<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 1652EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Nielsens     04-04 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nielsens,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABC's Oscars Coverage Heads TV Ratings; NBC Still Leads Overall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC's coverage of the 61st Academy Awards
captured half the TV audience and first place in the Nielsen
ratings for the week ended April 1.
   However, NBC handily won the week for the 41st straight time
despite the Oscar ceremony's 29.8 rating and 50 share, the highest
for the show since 1984. An estimated 75 million people watched all
or some of the presentation of the Oscars.
   NBC's ``The Cosby Show'' was in second place ahead of
third-place ``Roseanne,'' the new ABC comedy that had been first
for the past three weeks. NBC's ``Cheers,'' in fifth place, got its
highest rating of the season.
   NBC took five of the Top 10, including the Sunday Night Movie
presentation of ``The Hillside Stranglers,'' which was sixth. ABC
had three and CBS two.
   The A.C. Nielsen Co. said NBC won the week with a rating of
15.8, extending the network's record for its longest winning
streak. ABC was second with 14.4 and CBS was third with 12.4.
   For the season to date, NBC leads with 15.8, ABC is second with
12.9 and CBS is third with 12.7. Each ratings point represents
904,000 households with television. The share is a percentage of
sets in use.
   Here are the Top 10: 61st Annual Academy Awards, ABC; ``The
Cosby Show,'' NBC; ``Roseanne,'' ABC; ``A Different World,'' NBC;
``Cheers,'' NBC; ``NBC Sunday Movie ``The Hillside Stranglers,''
NBC; ``Murder, She Wrote,'' CBS; ``The Golden Girls,'' NBC; ``The
Wonder Years,'' ABC; ``60 Minutes,'' CBS.
   The NBC drama ``Quantum Leap'' was in 55th place for its
premiere.
   ABC's ``Moonlighting,'' newly moved to Sunday with new episodes,
was in 70th place. It was the fourth lowest rated network show of
the week.
   The new ABC comedy ``Anything But Love'' finished in 19th place,
but has been steadily dropping in the ratings since its premiere.
It completes its six-week spring tryout next week and will be
replaced by ``Have Faith,'' a comedy about four Catholic priests in
a Chicago parish.
   Fox Broadcasting's ``Married ... With Children'' was its
highest-rated show, finishing in a three-way tie for 59th place.
Fox's ``America's Most Wanted'' was in 62nd place.
   The five lowest-ranked network shows were NBC's
``Nightingales,'' ABC's ``Moonlighting,'' ABC's HeartBeat,'' ABC's
``Great Circuses of the World'' and ABC's ``Men.''
   Among the news shows, ``The CBS Evening News'' was first with a
rating of 10.6. ABC was second with 10.4 and NBC was third with 9.4.
</TEXT>
