<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 1659EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon     04-04 0749</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0776</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beirut Bombarded For Fourth Day; Americans Evacuated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian gunners traded
shellfire across Beirut before dawn Tuesday, bombarding the city's
residential suburbs non-stop for the fourth day.
   A U.S. Embassy official said two American officers were
evacuated Monday. The officers were part of a three-man technical
team assigned to Lebanon's Defense Ministry.
   Ambassador John McCarthy told reporters after a meeting with
army commander Gen. Michel Aoun that, ``This fighting must stop
quickly. ... It has caused tremendous damage, killed many people
and brought Lebanon's economy to its knees.''
   McCarthy met Aoun at the bunker of the battered presidential
palace in suburban Baabda, five miles east of Beirut.
   Aoun heads the Christian military Cabinet in Lebanon's dual
government. His 20,000 mostly Christian troops have been fighting
an alliance of Syrian and Druse forces in and around Beirut for the
past four weeks.
   Police said overnight clashes killed six people and wounded 18
in Moslem and Christian areas before shelling dwindled to sporadic
exchanges after daybreak. The shelling began Saturday.
   Two more civilians were killed and seven wounded when the
shelling intensified in the afteroon, said a police spokesman who
cannot be identified under standing rules.
   The latest casualties raised the toll to 155 people killed and
506 wounded since March 8, when the current round of hostilities
broke out between Aoun's Christian troops and the Syrian and Druse
Moslem fighters.
   Also Tuesday, Syrian soldiers allowed a convoy of four tanker
trucks to cross from north Lebanon into the Christian hinterland
northeast of Beirut to provide a power station with fuel oil.
   Mohammed Mawlawi, manager of the state oil refinery in the
northern town of Tripoli, said the tankers would bring 1,000 tons
of fuel oil for the station over the next four days.
   ``A total power failure would be disastrous to the whole of
Lebanon,'' Mawlawi said in a broadcast on the Moslem Voice of the
Nation radio.
   Supplies were allowed in after the electricity authority warned
its power station in Beirut's Christian Zouk suburb would run out
of fuel oil Saturday, triggering a power failure across most of
Lebanon.
   The Christian Voice of Lebanon radio said Christian army gunners
Monday set ablaze a Syrian army ammunition depot in the mountain
resort of Abadieh, east of Beirut.
   It said the depot ``contained lethal chemical materials which
forced the Syrian army to evacuate civilians from the Abadiyeh
area.'' The report could not be verified.
   Despite the relative lull that prevailed over Beirut and the
surrounding mountains from 5 a.m., civilians remained huddled in
basements and bomb shelters to avoid any sudden escalation of
hostilities.
   A dozen families sheltering in an apartment building basement in
the Christian Adonis district dispatched one man to a nearby bakery.
   ``This is the safest way. We will send one of us to buy food for
the whole building every day until a cease-fire is declared and
accepted by both sides,'' Antoine Shedyak, a mechanical engineer,
said by telephone.
   Kuwaiti Foreign Minister Sheik Sabah Ahmad Sabah, head of a
six-man Arab League mediation committee, was due in Damascus on
Tuesday to try to arrange a settlement of the confrontation.
   The leftist daily paper As-Safir, which reflects official Syrian
views, said Sabah would propose a two-month truce between Aoun and
his opponents to give the Arab League committee time to work out a
solution to Lebanon's six-month-old political crisis.
   Aoun has been insisting that Syria be a party to any cease-fire
accord with his 20,000 troops.
   The Syrians, with 40,000 troops in predominantly Moslem
terrritories of Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping
mandate, are the main power brokers in the country.
   Aoun and other Christian leaders accuse the Syrians of failing
in their mandate by siding with the Moslems against the Christians
in the 14-year-old civil war.
   Officially, the Syrians deny their troops in Lebanon are
involved against Aoun's forces entrenched in the 310-square-mile
Christian enclave northeast of Beirut.
   The political crisis erupted Sept. 22 when President Amin
Gemayel's 6-year term expired with parliament failing to elect a
successor. Gemayel appointed Aoun, a Maronite Catholic like
himself, head of an interim military cabinet to rule pending the
election of a new president.
   Syrian-backed Moslems rejected Aoun's appointment because it
violated a 45-year-old tradition of having a Sunni Moslem premier,
a Christian president and a Shiite Moslem parliament speaker. They
pledged allegiance to Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni who
governed under Gemayel.
</TEXT>
