<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 2046EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-S&amp;Ls     04-04 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel's S&amp;L Proposal Wins Praise, Criticism from Adminstration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior administration official on Tuesday
praised the Senate Banking Committee's savings and loan proposal
for maintaining tough capital standards, but criticized it for
creating a loophole in the Gramm-Rudman budget-balancing law.
   The committee is meeting behind closed doors this week in
preparation for public bill-writing sessions next week. On Tuesday,
the panel began going over a series of changes to the
administration plan proposed by the staff of the committee
chairman, Sen. Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich.
   According to a committee document obtained by The Associated
Press, the Senate plan would deviate only slightly from the
administration's requirement that thrift owners invest more of
their own money, or capital, to back up the loans they make.
   The administration would prevent S&amp;Ls from expanding after June
1991 if they do not meet stricter capital standards. The Senate
proposal keeps the deadline, which S&amp;L lobbyists have been trying
to push back, but would permit some weak S&amp;Ls to grow modestly even
if they missed it.
   ``We would applaud the fact that ... they have resisted watering
down the capital standards,'' Assistant Treasury Secretary David W.
Mullins, one of the key architects of the administration's
proposal, said in a telephone interview.
   Of the proposed capital changes, he said, ``I don't see anything
that's grossly out of line.''
   However, he warned that the Senate proposal for raising $50
billion to close or sell failed S&amp;Ls ``fundamentally threatens the
Gramm-Rudman process'' by setting a precedent that could be used
again for other spending programs.
   The Bush administration has put togther a complex mechanism that
combines taxpayer and industry funds and keeps the $50 billion out
of the budget deficit by selling bonds through a quasi-government
agency.
   Riegle advocates including the spending in the budget deficit
and raising the money through the sale of regular Treasury bonds, a
method he says would save $4.5 billion over 30 years because
Treasury bonds carry a lower interest rate. Riegle would avoid
Gramm-Rudman's automatic spending cuts by raising all of the money
in the current fiscal year, now that the deficit target deadlines
have passed.
   The administration believes its scheme for evading Gramm-Rudman
can't be readily applied to other kinds of programs, while the
Riegle plan could be used every year to avoid deficit limits.
Mullins also warned that opposition to Riegle's proposal from
Gramm-Rudman advocates could delay passage of the entire S&amp;L
package.
   Groups representing commercial banks are particularly happy with
Senate amendments that would shift more power over S&amp;Ls to the
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., a commercial bank regulator.
   The administration wants to give the FDIC control over the S&amp;L
deposit insurance fund. The Senate plan would expand the agency's
power further by giving it control over accounting and capital
standards for S&amp;Ls and by making it the primary regulator of
state-chartered S&amp;Ls. That would leave the S&amp;L regulator, the
Federal Home Loan Bank System, with little power.
   Edward Yingling, executive director of government relations for
the American Bankers Association, said expanding the FDIC's control
over S&amp;Ls would ensure that S&amp;L standards did not become looser
than bank standards.
   Kenneth Guenther, executive vice president of the Independent
Bankers of America, said he was pleased by the Senate change that
would give the FDIC chairman a set term. The administration wants
the president to have the power to dismiss the FDIC chairman at
will.
   ``We think Sen. Riegle has moved very much in the right
direction in terms of making the FDIC board considerly more
independent of the White House and Treasury Department. We think
that's a major plus,'' Guenther said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
