<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 2047EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NorthTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0603 04-04 0962</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0603,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Co-Worker Says He Took North's Words with `Grains of Salt'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 6 grafs at end with afternoon testimony</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former National Security Council staffer
testified Tuesday he took much of what Oliver North said with
``with four grains of salt'' and recalled making a Pinocchio-like
nose-growing gesture whe he read a letter to Congress that North
was drafting.
   Vincent Cannistraro said he felt that North, in his efforts to
help the Nicaraguan Contras, had crossed ``the line from
objectivity to advocacy.''
   Although he was called as a defense witness, Cannistraro's
testimony was peppered with critical references to North, who is on
trial on charges including withholding information from Congress in
connection with the Iran-Contra affair.
   Cannistraro jousted with prosecutor John Keker who tried in
cross examination to cast doubt on the witness' credibility,
suggesting more than once that he had lied.
   Keker asked whether North, formerly a Marine lieutenant colonel
attached to the staff of the NSC, had been considered trustworthy.
   ``I had considered Colonel North a trustworthy person but there
were occasions when myself and others had some questions about the
veracity about some of the things he told us,'' Cannistraro said.
   Keker asked whether he remembered testifying before a grand jury
that he took things North said with four grains of salt.
   ``Maybe three,'' said Cannistraro.
   Keker then read what the witness had told the grand jury:
   ``With Colonel North you never could be certain if what he was
telling was true or fantasy or deliberately meant to mislead. My
practice was to take everything with four grains of salt.''
   To that reading, Cannistraro responded: ``It was the way I came
to feel about him in the summer of 1986.''
   Cannistraro recalled a comment by a CIA official, ``that
whatever Ollie was doing he was bound to get us all in a lot of
trouble and he wanted to stay far away from him.''
   North lawyer Brendan Sullivan drew from the witness that he
admired North for ``his dedication and his persistence'' and would
want him ``in a foxhole with me when the first rounds were coming
in.''
   Keker asked about a time when North was drafting answers to
inquiries by two congressional committees. One of the charges
against North is that he made false statements in those letters,
which were signed by then-National Security Adviser Robert C.
McFarlane.
   ``He showed you some of his answers?'' Keker asked.
   ``I asked him if they were accurate and they did not appear to
be so,'' said Cannistraro.
   ``Did you do anything?'' said Keker. Cannistraro balked,
appealing to the judge on whether he had to answer. ``I want to
know what you did,'' Keker continued.
   ``I suggested ...'' Cannistraro began, and the prosecutor put
his hand to his nose and stretched his arm out, as if to show a
long nose.
   ``Not that long,'' said Cannistraro, and even North at the
witness table joined in the laughter.
   ``Whose nose grew?'' Keker asked.
   ``I was trying to convey to Colonel North his answer did not
reflect the facts,'' said Cannistraro. ``He said it was out of the
suggestion of Mr. McFarlane and he was not a free agent in the
matter.''
   McFarlane testified earlier in the trial that he was responsible
for the letters and that North contributed just two innocuous
paragraphs to one of the letters.
   Keker also brought out that Cannistraro had made no mention in
his 1987 grand jury appearance of his assertion Monday that
then-CIA Director William Casey said President Reagan had
designated North as the man who would assist the Contras if
Congress enacted a military aid ban.
   ``You know it's easy to blame things on a dead man,'' Keker told
the witness.
   ``Yes,'' responded Cannistraro.
   Under questioning from U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell,
Cannistraro said that Casey's comments were at a different meeting
from the one he discussed before the grand jury.
   Cannistraro said that at the time he was being ``intimidated''
by members of the special prosecuting team and that ``my agenda was
to try to be cooperative ... but ... avoid going into significant
detail when not asked.''
   ``I did not lie to the grand jury,'' Cannistraro said at one
point.
   In rapid succession, three more defense witnesses testified
Tuesday afternoon before the jury was sent home until Thursday. The
one-day recess was called because of a death in the family of a
juror.
   _Norman H. Gardner Jr., a CIA official, testified that he had
the job of drafting testimony that Casey was to give on Capitol
Hill on Nov. 21, 1986, after the diversion of Iran arms sales
profits to the Contras became known.
   Casey was in a Central American country, so the CIA arranged for
Gardner to be flown in an Air Force C-130 to take him the draft,
the witness said. He and an armed guard were alone with the crew on
the plane, which can carry more than 42,000 pounds of cargo.
   _William Charles Haskell, who owns a tax-preparation franchise,
told of being detailed by North to help with getting the land for
an air strip in Costa Rica. Haskell credited North with saving his
life when both were Marine platoon leaders in Vietnam.
   ``I saw an opportunity to help this country,'' he said. ``To
this day I think everything I did and everything Ollie did was
helpful to this country.''
   _Gaston Sigur, who was assistant secretary of state for East
Asian and Pacific affairs at the State Department in March 1986,
said that at North's request he got North together with
representatives of Taiwan, South Korea and China. North told each
about the Contras' needs and eventually Taiwan contributed $2
million.
</TEXT>
