<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 2046EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FORSCOM     04-04 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FORSCOM,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Powell Takes Charge Of Army's Largest Command</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM E. SCHULZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Colin L. Powell, the former White House
security adviser, said Tuesday that despite turmoil in the Soviet
Union, that country's armed forces were strong and ready to fight.
   Powell was installed as head of the U.S. Army Forces Command and
said his job was to keep 1 million active, reserve and National
Guard troops in the United States ready for combat ``with the hope
they will never be needed.''
   ``The Soviets are going through wrenching historic change,
beginning with the irreversible acknowledgement that their system
is broken and has to be changed,'' Powell said at a ceremony at
Fort McPherson, the headquarters of the command, which is known as
FORSCOM.
   Despite the Soviets' internal turmoil, ``there is nothing wrong
with their deployed forces,'' he said. ``Their FORSCOM is strong.
We must be strong.''
   Powell said a priority was National Guard and reserve units,
which ``are not as ready as we would like them to be. We don't have
the resources.''
   Powell said he saw a role for the military in the war on drugs,
but cautioned against its use as a police force.
   ``I will not be resistant to finding ways for the military to
help civilian authorities in defense against a major threat,'' he
said. ``I think there are opportunities for our men to get good
training'' in interdiction.
   Powell cautioned that even an apparently innovative leader like
Mikhail Gorbachev would need time to make major changes in Soviet
life.
   ``It took them 70 years to acknowledge their system is not
working. They're not going to fix it in one or two years,'' he
said. ``It is the West that is strong. He has to be innovative. He
has to be imaginative.''
   Powell, who will be 52 Wednesday, succeeded Gen. Joseph T.
Palastra Jr., who had the post for three years and was retiring.
   Powell, who served in Korea and Vietnam, became President
Reagan's national security adviser in January 1987.
   Powell said the Army was in a higher state of readiness with a
better quality of soldier than at any time in his 31 years of
military service.
   In the old days, he said, soldiers would keep a pinball machine
in a corner of their barracks. ``Today there's a computer there.''
</TEXT>
