<FIRST>r a AM-PlaneChase     04-04 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane Chase,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot of Chased Plane Bails Out Before Aircraft Crashes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspected marijuana smuggler being chased by
federal agents bailed out of his aircraft, prompting NORAD to
launch an Air Force F-16 to shoot down the pilotless plane,
officials said Tuesday.
   But the sophisticated military jet wasn't needed when the
twin-engine Beechcraft crashed into the Gulf of Mexico about 190
miles west of Naples on Monday night, after five aircraft joined
the chase.
   Footage of the plane slamming into the sea was filmed from a
U.S. Customs Service chase plane.
   Ronald Arthur Coxe, 42, a commercial pilot from Miami, set his
Beechcraft Travelair on automatic pilot and _ making his first jump
_ parachuted over Highlands County in south-central Florida, said
Coast Guard Petty Officer Luis Diaz.
   ``He said he almost took his head off. He was upside down and
the cables were around his neck when he pulled the cord,'' Diaz
said.
   In custody later, Coxe said a companion he refused to identify
had bailed out before him.
   ``We don't know anything about a second person,'' said Customs
spokesman Michael Sheehan.
   A Coast Guard Blackhawk helicopter in pursuit of the Beechcraft
saw Coxe swing a U-turn and bail out over land just north of Lake
Josephine, Sheehan said.
   ``They saw a large object with a parachute leave the plane,'' he
said, adding that agents weren't certain at first what went out the
door at 7,500 feet. They landed and took Coxe into custody.
   Coxe, charged with smuggling marijuana by aircraft, was taken
before a magistrate Tuesday and ordered held without bond pending
another hearing Friday.
   A Coast Guard radar plane spotted a small plane flying
suspiciously low at about 200 feet over the water 150 miles
southwest of Key West on Monday afternoon, Sheehan said. The
helicopter and a Coast Guard Falcon jet took off after it.
   Three hours after the saga began, Customs contacted the North
American Air Defense Command requesting an F-16 to shoot down the
unmanned aircraft.
   The F-16 from the Florida Panhandle base tailed the Beechcraft
and was ready to shoot it down had it veered back toward land and
posed any danger to populated areas, said Coast Guard Lt.j.g. John
Katinski.
   The plane crashed after narrowly missing a Coast Guard
air-surveillance balloon tethered to a ship in the Gulf of Mexico,
authorities said.
   A Coast Guard cutter sped to the crash site and fished more than
600 pounds of marijuana from the wreckage, Sheehan said.
   ``We're asking for pretrial detention because this man is a
danger to the community,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney William Jung
told U.S. Magistrate Linnea Johnson. ``This man parachuted from a
plane over a populated area. The plane flew around and it was a
bomb that easily could have landed anywhere.''
   A passport seized from Coxe indicated he had left Belize on
Monday, Suarez said.
</TEXT>
