<FIRST>r a AM-FireAnts     04-04 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fire Ants,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey Finds Fire Ants Send 21,000 To Doctor Yearly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire ant stings send at least 21,000 people a
year to doctors in 13 Southern states, a survey has found.
   The survey of physicians for the American Academy of Allergy and
Immunology also found that 413 people were treated for
life-threatening reactions to fire ant stings last year and that 32
died, most of them because they were hypersensitive to the ant's
poison.
   In most of those who died, the ant stings triggered an
anaphylactic or allergic response which caused the body's
respiratory system to shut down.
   ``People and physicians should take these stings seriously,''
said Robert Rhoades, a pediatrician at the Medical College of
Georgia.
   People who are allergic to other kinds of insect stings should
be especially cautious, said Rhoades, who heads a special panel
that monitors medical problems caused by fire ants.
   Fire ants arrived in Florida by boat from South America and have
been slowly moving northward and westward. Cold weather has
seemingly confined them to the Deep South.
   But recent studies have shown the ant is crossbreeding and that
the hybrid, which can withstand lower temperatures, may push its
range farther north into the north Georgia mountains and Tennessee.
   More than 2,000 physicians in 13 states, or about 10 percent of
those polled, responded to the allergy academy survey, indicating
they treat about 21,000 patients a year for fire ant stings. Most
of those stung were treated successfully with over-the-counter
antihistamines.
</TEXT>
