<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Cyprus     04-04 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Cyprus,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greek and Turkish Cypriots Both Agree to Unstaff Tense Green Line
Posts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governments of the Greek and Turkish
Cypriot communities have agreed to withdraw their soldiers from
three tense observation points on the Green Line in Nicosia,
officials said Tuesday.
   Rauf Denktash, president of the breakaway Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus, confirmed in an interview that his government had
fully agreed with the U.N. plan for the pullback.
   The agreement in principle marks the first time the Cypriot
government and the administration of the Turkish Republic have ever
concluded a military withdrawal agreement, said officials from both
communities.
   Greek Cypriot troops are only 10 yards from Turkish Cypriot
troops at some points in Nicosia.
   In 1988, a Turkish Cypriot and a Greek Cypriot were killed in
separate sniping attacks across the Green Line, as the unofficial
buffer zone dividing the two ethnic communities is known.
   Under the terms of the U.N. plan, both the Greek and Turkish
Cypriot forces will withdraw from the posts, but will not
necessarily have to dismantle their defense works, said a Turkish
Cypriot official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Cypriot Defense Minister Andreas Aloneftis said his government
has agreed to the U.N. plan. Both sides still have to sign formal
documents with the United Nations.
   If the plan succeeds, Denktash said, it would ``naturally'' lead
to further steps toward demilitarization, ``provided the U.N. is
between us. Our armed people must not see each other from different
points.''
   The U.N. Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus, known as UNFICYP, was
established in 1964. Since 1974, it has patrolled the Green Line in
an attempt to defuse hostilities. It has about 2,100 troops and 34
police monitors from nine nations.
   Denktash and Cypriot President George Vassiliou are in New York
for a third round of talks mediated by Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar on how to reconcile the Greek and Turkish
communities on Cyprus.
   Denktash said Tuesday he has little hope the talks will result
in progress toward reunifying the divided island.
   The East Mediterranean island has been unofficially partitioned
since the Greek government fomented a coup and Turkish troops moved
into the northern sector in 1974 to protect the Turkish minority
community.
   The coup failed, but about 30,000 Turkish troops remain and
about 50,000 Turks moved from the mainland to settle in northern
Cyprus.
   Vassiliou's government demands the removal of the Turkish troops
and settlers as part of the process of establishing a national
republic with two states with virtual autonomy in local affairs.
   Dentash's Turkish Cypriot community declared itself a nation in
1983, but has only been recognized by Turkey.
   The Turkish Republic covers about 37 percent of northern Cyprus,
and has 120,000 residents, mostly Moslems. They form about 18
percent of the entire population of the island.
</TEXT>
