<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 2240EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BellSuit     04-04 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bell Suit,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses To Silence Town Bell That Keeps Couple Awake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTHAMPTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Hatfield town clock can keep on
chiming at night despite a couple's lawsuit charging that it keeps
them awake, a judge ruled.
   Superior Court Judge John F. Murphy Jr. said, in rejecting a
request for a temporary injunction Monday, that silencing the clock
until trial ``will not best serve the public's interest.'' The
judge also said Richard and Pamela Carnall failed to show they
would suffer irreparable harm if the clock was allowed to continue
to toll the hours.
   The Carnalls, who moved to the little farming community of 3,200
people last summer when the 200-year-old clock was not working,
sued last month after selectmen declined to shut off the clock at
night.
   The couple contends the clock, located in the steeple of the
First Congregational Church about 50 feet from their home, booms
the hours at 75 decibels, 15 decibels louder than a vacuum cleaner
and 25 decibels above the level the Federal Aviation Administration
has set as the loudest people can sleep through.
   Murphy said in his decision that expert testimony would be
required at trial to determine decibel levels as well as the
mechanical feasibility of installing a timer to shut off the chimes
late at night.
   The Carnalls were away from home and could not be reached for
comment Tuesday. But their attorney, W. Michael Ryan, said he would
seek to bring the case to trial as quickly as possible.
   ``Most people are sympathetic to the Carnalls, even people who
want the bell to keep ringing,'' Ryan contended.
</TEXT>
