<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Treasurer     04-04 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Treasurer,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>There'll Be a New Name on Your Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Catalina Vasquez Villalpando is about to
become one of the most widely publicized names in America _ if you
look at the fine print on paper money.
   She was picked by President Bush on Tuesday as the next
treasurer of the United States. That entitles her to put her
signature on all paper bills printed by the Treasury.
   Ms. Villalpando, a Texan now working in Washington for a
communications company, is also chairman of the Republican National
Hispanic Assembly.
   If confirmed by the Senate, she will succeed another woman of
Hispanic ancestry, Katherine Davalos Ortega.
   The president, filling out his economic team, also said he will
nominate Richard Schmalensee to the three-member Council of
Economic Advisers, which is led by chairman Michael Boskin.
   Schmalensee, who once served as a junior economist on the CEA,
has been a professor of economics and management at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology since 1967. He would succeed
Thomas Gale Moore.
   Also Tuesday, Bush announced he had selected Delos Cy Jamison, a
House committee staff adviser, to serve as the new director of the
Bureau of Land Management.
   Jamison, 40, has been since 1985 a legislative adviser to the
national parks and public lands subcommittee of the House Interior
and Insular Affairs Committee.
   Previously, he was field director for Rep. Ron Marlenee of
Montana, and House liaison for the Interior Department, and a
Republican consultant on the Interior and Insular Affairs
subcommittee on oversight and investigations.
</TEXT>
