<FIRST>u i AM-NorthernIreland     04-04 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northern Ireland,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Father Of Four Slain, Police Officer Shot, Bomb Defused</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The IRA said it shot and
wounded a part-time police officer after one of its members was
killed in bed on Tuesday while his 3-month-old daughter slept in a
crib beside him.
   IRA member Gerard Casey, 29, a father of four children, was the
26th victim of sectarian strife to die in Northern Ireland this
year and the 2,737th to die in nearly 20 years of religious
violence in the British province.
   Casey was shot by two men who stormed his home in Balleymoney,
40 miles northwest of Belfast. Police said Protestant
paramilitaries were responsible for the attack. The IRA, in
messages to Belfast media, said Casey was a member of its North
Antrim brigade.
   Later Tuesday, a part-time police officer who had stopped his
car at a pedestrian crossing in west Belfast was shot and wounded
by men firing from the sidewalk, police said. The IRA said it
carried out the attack.
   The police officer, who was not identified, was in stable
condition with wounds to his back, police said.
   In a third incident, police said security forces found and
defused a bomb in a Belfast house after a two-day search after the
IRA said it had abandoned a bomb in the area.
   The mainly Catholic IRA is fighting to end British rule in the
province and unite it with the overwhelmingly Catholic Irish
Republic. Most Protestants want Northern Ireland to remain under
the British flag.
   In another development Tuesday, a court heard how the last
moments in the lives of two British soldiers slain by the IRA at a
funeral in west Belfast were filmed by an army helicopter hovering
helplessly above.
   Henry Maguire, 29, and Alexander Murphy, 31, pleaded innocent to
the murders on the first day of their trial at Belfast Crown Court,
which is expected to last six weeks.
   Twenty-seven more people, three of them accused of murder, have
been charged in the case and will be tried later.
   Prosecutor Ronald Appleton said the helicopter crew saw
Corporals Derek Wood, 24, and David Howes, 23, drive into the
funeral procession for a slain member of the IRA.
   He said their car was surrounded and the two soldiers dragged
out, beaten, kicked, stripped almost naked, driven in a black taxi
to an empty lot and thrown over a 9-foot wall.
   A man seen getting a gun nearby returned to the soldiers and
stretched out his arm in a firing position first over one and then
the other, Appleton said. Afterwards, the crowd dispersed.
   He said Wood was later found to have been shot six times and
stabbed four times. Howes was shot five times.
   Appleton said Maguire and Murphy had bloodstains on their
clothes of the same types as the two soldiers when they were
arrested in a taxi near the spot where the soldiers' car was
stopped.
   The helicopter had been monitoring the funeral procession on
March 19 last year of IRA member Kevin Brady.
</TEXT>
