<FIRST>r a AM-DexterKing     04-04 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dexter King,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dexter King Installed As President Of King Center</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dexter Scott King, younger son of the Rev. Martin
Luther King Jr., on Tuesday officially became a leader in the civil
rights movement his father left behind exactly 21 years ago.
   King, 28, was installed as president of The King Center, a
policy center created in his father's memory, succeeding his
mother, Coretta Scott King.
   He will manage day-to-day operations while Mrs. King serves as
chief executive officer and spokeswoman for the center.
   ``After being charged, super-charged and turbo-charged, I hope I
can say I am in charge,'' King said.
   He used his first minutes as president to make an appeal for
money, saying building an endowment for the center is a top
priority.
   ``It's not about what Dexter wants,'' King said. ``It's about
what the King Center needs. Read my lips: money.
   ``The time has come. The generation before us has paved the
way.''
   Mrs. King, whose husband was assassinated in Memphis, Tenn., on
April 4, 1968, said she felt ``a mother's pride'' in sharing the
center's leadership with her son.
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson, who had been scheduled to attend but was
grounded in Chicago because of bad weather, encouraged King via
telephone to maintain the ``rhythm and momentum'' of the civil
rights movement.
   ``Dexter, there'll be no cure in heavy moments,'' Jackson said.
``Your young leadership means so much to those of us who watched
you grow. ... Your energy and strength and work are what we need.''
   The Rev. Joseph Lowery, president of the Southern Christian
Leadership Conference, said the SCLC is ready to work closely with
The King Center under Dexter King's leadership.
   Also attending was Zenani Mandela Dlamini, daughter of
imprisoned South African leader Nelson Mandela.
</TEXT>
