<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 2242EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ServiceChiefs 430   04-04 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Service Chiefs, 430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Chiefs Picked</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney has selected
three experienced defense officials to become the secretaries of
the Army, Navy and Air Force, administration officials said Tuesday.
   The officials, who insisted upon anonymity, said Cheney
forwarded the names to the White House for President Bush's
approval within the past few days and expected their formal
nominations to be announced shortly.
   The sources said Cheney wants Assistant Defense Secretary
Richard L. Armitage to become the secretary of the Army; Navy Under
Secretary H. Lawrence Garrett III to take over the top job with
that service, and Donald B. Rice of the think tank Rand Corp. to
head the Air Force.
   All three appointments will require Senate confirmation.
   Two weeks ago, sources first disclosed that Cheney had asked
Armitage to remain at the Defense Department as a service chief.
The 43-year-old Armitage is the assistant secretary of defense for
international security affairs and had been slated to leave the
Pentagon for an executive position at the State Department.
   At Cheney's request, he agreed to give up the State Department
position and remain at the Pentagon. In his current job, he has
played a key role in overseeing American security assistance
programs around the world as well as counter-terrorism and Vietnam
POW-MIA issues.
   Armitage will replace John O. Marsh, who has held the position
since the first day of the Reagan administration and who had made
clear his desire to retire once a successor was picked.
   Garrett, 49, a former Navy officer, was an associate counsel to
former President Reagan from 1983 to 1986. He then moved to the
Pentagon as the department's general counsel and assumed the post
of under secretary, or No. 2 in the civilian heirarchy, in 1987.
   Garrett will replace William O. Ball, who took over the top job
for the last year of the Reagan administration. Ball was an
associate of former Texas Sen. John Tower and had been expected to
retain the post if Tower had been able to win Senate confirmation.
   With Tower's defeat in the Senate and Cheney's selection as his
replacement, Ball's prospects of remaining diminished.
   Rice, 49, is an engineer and economist who has been a cost
analyst at the Pentagon and White House Office of Management and
Budget. Since 1972, he has been chief executive at the Rand Corp.,
a major military think tank.
   Rice would take over the top civilian Air Force job from James
F. McGovern, the acting secretary. McGovern, another associate of
Tower, announced his intention to resign on March 24.
</TEXT>
