<FIRST>r i AM-Venezuela     04-04 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Venezuela,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Protesting Economic Measures Battle Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students protesting government
austerity measures battled police Tuesday. Officials said one
demonstrator and a policeman were injured and 30 people were
arrested.
   Police reinforcements rushed to Catia, a Caracas suburb, when
hundreds of youths began burning tires after bus drivers refused to
give students a 50 percent fare discount authorized by a government
decree.
   A police spokesman said of the injured: ``The policeman was shot
in a leg with a projectile and the student sustained several
injuries from plastic shotgun pellets.''
   Students outside the Caracas Central University of Venezuela
later seized a bus and set it on fire. No casualties or arrests
were reported.
   In Maracaibo, 300 miles west of Caracas, most university and
public high school classes were suspended Tuesday, the day after
students burned a bus and a police truck. The Maracaibo protesters
also said bus drivers were not allowing the discount for students
and were charging them full fare.
   Demonstrations have been frequent since the government began
applying in February the provisions of an economic package approved
by the International Monetary Fund.
   Bus fares were increased, but the government earmarked $10
million to subsidize the 50 percent discount for students.
Transport companies said the reduced fares didn't cover their
expenses.
   More than 300 people were killed in riots that erupted Feb. 27
to protest price increases. Most of the deaths were in Caracas,
where about 3,000 stores were looted.
   President Carlos Andres Perez' Social Democratic administration
has continued to implement its ``economic adjustment plan'' based
on IMF guidelines that include the reduction or removal of many
government subsidies.
   Venezuela's inflation is expected to exceed 70 percent this year.
</TEXT>
