<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 2248EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CaribouReturn     04-04 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Caribou Return,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woodland Caribou Return to Maine Wilds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GLENN ADAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILLINOCKET, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tranquilized caribou were loaded onto
a van Tuesday and carried north toward their new home in the
wilderness under a plan to restore the reindeer-like animal in
Maine.
   Six to eight caribou, some weighing as much as 250 pounds, were
to be taken to Baxter State Park, a 200,000-acre wilderness
preserve.
   After being shot with tranquilizer guns, the ungainly creatures
were lifted on canvas stretchers and carried onto a van for the
70-mile journey. Blindfolded to reduce stress, they were placed
side by side on a bed of straw.
   Scientists hope the animals will use their new home as a
breeding ground.
   Maine's once-abundant caribou were wiped out in Maine by
overhunting and disease. The last native woodland caribou to be
seen in Maine was spotted in 1908 on mile-high Mount Katahdin in
the park's southern end.
   Dr. Ladd Heldenbrand, a veterinarian monitoring the animals, was
optimistic about the animals' chances of flourishing in the wild.
The biggest threats to the caribou are parasites and predators,
Heldenbrand said.
   ``We hope the public is educated enough to leave them alone,''
he said. ``They're the public's animals. We hope they will respect
them.''
   Release of the 1- and 2-year-old caribou caps a two-year effort
begun in Canada.
   Biologists and state officials in 1986 had more than two dozen
rounded up in Newfoundland and trucked 1,200 miles to the
University of Maine. Calves born since then will be the nucleus of
the new herd.
   By Wednesday, officials hoped to have transported 14 of the
docile, tan animals to Baxter State Park, officials said.
   The animals will be fitted with radio collars so scientists can
keep track of them and determine whether they are being pursued by
coyotes and bears, said biologist Mark McCollough, director of the
privately funded project.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890404-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 2249EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Honduras-Nicaragua     04-04 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honduras-Nicaragua,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honduras Accuses Nicaragua of Blocking Regional Peace Effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honduras on Tuesday accused
Nicaragua of trying to use a regional peace effort to get rid of
the Contra rebels without giving up anything in return.
   Foreign Minister Carlos Lopez Contreras told a news conference
Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government refuses to talk to the
U.S.-backed rebels.
   ``Nicaragua doesn't want to solve the political and social
crisis in Central America,'' Contreras charged. ``It ... just wants
a bilateral accord with Honduras to fix the problem of the
Contras.''
   Between 10,000 and 11,000 Contra fighters and their families
began moving into Honduran base camps near the border with
Nicaragua last spring after U.S. military aid ended and a
cease-fire began.
   Nicaragua, which announced another of its monthly, unilateral
extensions of the cease-fire Tuesday, had no immediate comment on
the Honduran charges.
   Lopez Contreras said ``Nicaragua should offer internal political
conditions that permit the quick return of the Contras, their
families and more than 40,000 Nicaraguan refugees that have been in
Honduras since 1981.''
   Honduras wants the Contras ``to return to Nicaragua as quickly
as possible. But this is the responsibility of the Sandinistas, who
absolutely refuse to talk with the Contras,'' he said.
   In February, the presidents of Nicaragua, Honduras, Guatemala,
El Salvador and Costa Rica agreed to come up with a plan by mid-May
for disarming the rebels and for their voluntary repatriation or
relocation. Nicaragua also agreed to hold free elections next year.
   The accord has bogged down over the timing of the repatriation
in relation to the elections. Nicaragua, which scheduled elections
for February 1990, wants the rebel force dismantled quickly.
   Lopez Contreras said the ``outlook for regional peace is very
gray and appears stalled. The signs are not good. The problem of
the Contras has not been resolved.''
   In Washington, Costa Rican President Oscar Arias acknowledged
intense arguments over timing and said the Contras should return at
the same time as the Sandinistas make democratic reforms.
   ``You cannot persuade the Contras to go back to Nicaragua ... if
you have nothing for them there,'' he told reporters after a
meeting with President Bush.
   Lopez Contreras said the Sandinistas ``stubbornly refuse'' to
talk with the Contras.
   He and his Central American counterparts ended a two-day meeting
last week without agreeing on demobilization of the Contras. They
also postponed the next summit from May 15, the deadline for coming
up with a plan to dismantle the Contras, to June 15.
   Lopez Contreras said implementing the presidential accord will
be ``difficult'' unless the Sandinistas agree to talk, directly or
indirectly, to the rebels.
   ``Lamentably, the problem has negative repercussions for the
entire region,'' he said. ``We hope the Sandinistas might meditate
on the future of Central America'' and change their attitude.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
