<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-BombAlert     04-04 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Bomb Alert,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Squad Explodes Harmless Package</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIVERPOOL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bomb experts conducted a controlled
explosion Tuesday night when a suspect package was found on a
flight from Northern Ireland, but the parcel was harmless, police
reported.
   ``When the package was examined, it contained a printed circuit
and a floppy disc for a computer _ nothing suspicious at all,'' a
Merseyside police spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   Liverpool's Speke Airport was evacuated and flights to the port
city in northwest England were diverted for three hours, he said.
   After passengers left the Manx Airlines shuttle from Belfast,
crew members noticed the package and alerted police because they
thought it looked suspicious, said airport manager Chris Preece.
   He said the Shorts 360 aircraft arrived via the Isle of Man and
Manx Airlines said it would return there for repair of minor damage
to the luggage rack.
   Preece said police knew the identity of the passenger involved.
   ``The passenger boarded the aircraft at Belfast,'' he said.
``His hand baggage had been taken through a security scan. It
passed through the scans and was safe.
   ``Each incident has to be treated seriously and checked out
thoroughly. We feel that the traveling public deserve to feel safe
these days. There must be no exceptions.''
</TEXT>
