<FIRST>r w AM-BaseClosings     04-04 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Base Closings,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>CBO: Base Savings Said Too High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal commission that recommended
shutting down 86 military bases and partly closing five more was
optimistic in its assessment that the move will save $5.6 billion
over 20 years, a congressional budget official said Tuesday.
   ``The commission's estimates of savings fell at the upper end of
the range suggested by our data,'' Robert F. Hale, assistant
director at the Congressional Budget Office, told a Senate
subcommittee. ``Unfortunately, missing historical data and
differences in definitions make comparisons of one-time costs and
savings unclear.''
   The commission did not include the cost of federal economic
assistance in estimating the plan's savings but did include the
expected revenues from sale of the land presently used by the
bases, Hale said.
   However, the office's analysis found that of the 33 bases closed
during the 1970s, the government only got 35 percent of the
fair-market value for sale of the land. In some cases, the property
was donated for educational use and other public services.
   The commission estimated savings of $694 million a year, with
20-year savings estimated at $5.6 billion.
   ``Based on the historic data, they were optimistic ... not
wildly so,'' Hale told the Senate Appropriations subcommittees on
defense and military construction.
   Lawmakers expressed concerns about the commission's
recommendations at two separate Senate hearings while acknowledging
the plan will likely go into effect next month and base closings
will begin in 1990.
   Congress can block the proposal, which former Defense Secretary
Frank Carlucci approved in January, but the chances are unlikely.
The House Armed Services panel voted 43-4 last month to support the
commission's recommendations to close 86 facilities, partially
close five others and change the mission in 54 other installations.
The full House is expected to follow suit later this month.
   Nevertheless, legislators held hearings to question the planned
closing of some of their local bases.
   At the Senate Armed Services subcommittee on readiness,
sustainability and support, Chairman Alan Dixon, D-Ill., cited
recently unclassified transcripts of the commission's meetings in
which members discussed time constraints that prohibited a more
extensive examination of available data on each base.
   Dixon argued against the planned closing of Chanute Air Force
Base, near Champaign, Ill., and railed against the rating system
the commission used to make its decision.
   ``Who was the mother, father or brainchild of the rating
system,'' Dixon asked.
   ``A lot of people on the commission staff,'' responded Dr.
Hayden G. Bryan, executive director of the commission staff.
   Seated behind Bryan were 10 members of his staff and Dixon
called on each one to stand and give their name. The Illinois
senator also asked the staff members to write down their names and
addresses.
   ``The commission gave responsibility to faceless people,'' Dixon
said.
   In defense of the commission's decision, Bryan noted the base
closing was ``recommended by the Defense Department, chartered by
Congress.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
