<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 1905EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Abortion-Justice     04-04 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion-Justice,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department Attorneys Protest Abortion Position</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 200 Justice Department attorneys
submitted a petition Tuesday to Attorney General Dick Thornburgh
criticizing the department's attempt to persuade the Supreme Court
to overturn the landmark 1973 decision legalizing abortion.
   ``We believe that every woman has the right to make her own
decision about whether or not to continue her pregnancy in
accordance with the guidelines set forth in Roe vs. Wade,'' the
petition said, referring to the 1973 case. ``We oppose any
governmental interference with this basic right.''
   The petition bearing 248 names, most of them attorneys, was
given to Thornburgh's office late in the afternoon, according to
one of the signers.
   Dave Runkel, a top aide to Thornburgh, said the petition ``won't
have any impact on the department's position.''
   ``These people come in six months after the decision was made to
appeal this case to the Supreme Court,'' he said. ``It's not
timely. ... If they wanted to have an impact on what the department
was doing on this, they're six months too late.''
   One of the signers, an attorney who spoke only on condition of
anonymity, said the petition was submitted late because attorneys
at the department are very busy and it took a long time to get the
organization in motion. In addition, she said the signers hope the
petition will make an impact on other cases.
   She said Thornburgh and the department had involved themselves
in partisan politics by intervening in the case.
   Runkel said he didn't expect any retaliation against the people
who signed the petition, saying, ``The attorney general understands
this is a controversial issue that people disagree on.''
   ``I don't anticipate any impact ... unless people decide that
they so disagree that they can no longer work here,'' he said.
   The case before the Supreme Court is called Webster vs.
Reproductive Health Services, and it concerns a Missouri law that
prohibits the use of public funds or public employees from
``encouraging'' or ``performing'' or ``assisting'' an abortion. The
8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals rejected key portions of the law
last July 13.
   The Supreme Court could act on the Webster case without touching
the 1973 Roe vs. Wade decision, but the Justice Department, in a
brief filed in February, urged the court to overturn its earlier
ruling and leave decisions on abortions to legislators.
   The signer who commented on the petition said the majority of
those who signed are women.
   She said the many female attorneys at Justice give the issue
relevance, serving as reminders that their ability to pursue
careers would be compromised by unwanted pregnancies.
   Colleen O'Connor of the American Civil Liberties Union praised
the employees who signed the petition.
   ``Quite apart from the issue of what the department is doing on
Roe vs. Wade, it's heartening to know there are a few government
lawyers willing to exercise their First Amendment rights,'' she
said.
   ``The attorney general obviously can respond any way he wants to
that petition, but he of all people has to know that his employees
should not bear any recriminations for expressing their views on an
issue as important as this one,'' O'Connor said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890404-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 2256EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Beech-NutDebarment 620   04-04 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Beech-Nut Debarment, 620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Banned From Doing Federal Business</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighteen months after it was convicted of
selling bogus apple juice to consumers, the Beech-Nut Corp. has
been debarred from doing any business with the federal government
through 1991.
   The corporation, suspended from federal contracting since
December 1986, is now being debarred ``to protect the government's
interest in doing business only with contractors who conduct
business with honesty and integrity,'' the Pentagon's order states.
   The debarment, which Beech-Nut contested, was announced Tuesday
by the Defense Logistics Agency. The company was advised of the
decision in a letter dated March 3, the Pentagon added.
   A suspension is normally the first step toward a company either
being debarred or allowed to resume bidding on government work. A
contract debarment is the harshest administrative sanction the
Pentagon can impose on a contractor.
   Such an order, whose term can vary, prevents a company from
bidding on or receiving any new contract from any agency of the
federal government _ not just the Defense Department.
   In Beech-Nut's case, the Pentagon announced in January it was
changing the suspension of the Beech-Nut Nutrition Corp., a wholly
owned subsidiary, to a debarment. By taking the same action Tuesday
against the parent Beech-Nut Corp., the Pentagon has barred any and
all units of the corporation from receiving any government contract
``through Dec. 4, 1991.''
   The Beech-Nut Nutrition Corp. was convicted Nov. 13, 1987, in
federal court in New York on a total of 215 counts involving
charges of introducing adulterated food into commerce and violating
the federal Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act.
   ``The criminal conduct of Beech-Nut Nutrition involved
manufacturing juice for babies which was labeled as and represented
to be pure apple juice, but in fact contained little, if any, apple
or fruit juice,'' the Pentagon noted in its order.
   The financial impact of Tuesday's action on the company appears
slight. The Defense Logistics Agency purchases Beech-Nut products
for resale in military commissaries around the world.
   Larry Wilson, a DLA spokesman, said he could not immediately
estimate the value of the government's business to the company
before it was suspended in 1986. Other Pentagon officials said,
however, the total was well below $1 million a year.
   Nonetheless, the company had strongly fought the debarment
action since being advised of the possibility last December,
arguing an entirely new management team had taken over and any
damage that had been incurred had been incurred by consumers and
not the federal government.
   ``The government bought the juice for resale to military members
and their families in commissaries,'' countered Gerald H. Werfel,
the DLA's special assistant for contracting integrity, in the
debarment order.
   ``The government paid for 100 percent pure apple juice, received
artificial juice, and government employees were offered the
artificial juice while assuming that the juice was 100 percent pure
applie juice. To say that the government was not damaged in these
circumstances is further evidence of Beech-Nut's continuing lack of
responsibility.''
   Werfel added the evidence was clearly sufficient to show that
``the Beech-Nut Corp. was and is responsible for the actions of
Beech-Nut Nutrition Corp., including its criminal activity from
December 1981 through March 1983.''
   Beech-Nut, which is headquartered in Fort Washington, Pa., said
it found the DLA's action ``inexplicable.''
   ``It is beyond question that our products today are authentic,
pure and safe,'' added a company spokesman, who asked not to be
named.
   ``This happened nearly six years ago, and stringent quality
control programs were put in place by the new management. We are
puzzled by this move and find it inexplicable that DLA is impugning
the current management by this action.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890404-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 1920EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Namibia-SWAPO     04-04 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia-SWAPO,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>SWAPO Guerrilla Chief Vows To Return To Namibia Soon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Namibia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN EDLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Namibian guerrilla chief Sam Nujoma
vowed Tuesday he would shortly return to his homeland, scene of the
bloodiest clashes between security forces and guerrillas in 23
years of war.
   His return would effectively end more than two decades as an
exile, wanted by the South African rulers of Namibia as a terrorist.
   But aides said it would not be his first visit home.
   ``He has been in and out with his men quite often,'' said one
official, who spoke on condition of not being identified.
   Nujoma addressed a news conference after he urged the U.N.
Security Council to immediately bolster its cease-fire monitoring
forces in Namibia.
   Asked if he would be going to Namibia, Nujoma replied, ``Yes,
very soon.''
   Nujoma reiterated denials that 1,200 of his men infiltrated
Namibia from Angola in violation of the cease-fire accord,
insisting ``our people have been fighting inside Namibia in the
past 20 years.''
   He said that in his 90-minute talks Tuesday with mission chiefs
of the five permament Security Council members _ America, the
Soviet Union, China, Britain and France _ he expressed ``utter
disgust over the killing of innocent Namibians, some of whom were
celebrating the start of the cease-fire.''
   A cease-fire is the initial stage of an independence transition
period for Namibia, a onetime German colony ruled for the last 74
years by South Africa.
   Nujoma, head of the South-West Africa People's Organization,
said he urged the Security Council through the envoys to stop the
South African-led security forces ``from butchering Namibians and
confine the South African army to their barracks.''
   He described as ``full-scale war'' the fighting that first broke
out last Saturday, the day the cease-fire was to go into effect.
   The combat has killed 169 of his fighters, 19 police and one
South African soldier.
   Meeting with Nujoma were U.S. Charge d'Affaires Ed Fugat, who
heads the U.S. Embassy while appointment of a new ambassador is
awaited; British High Commissioner (ambassador) Ramsay Melhuish;
and ambassadors Arrkadi Gloukhou of the Soviet Union, Song Ghoqing
of China and Pierre Garriague-Guyonnaud of France.
   Nujoma, who directs SWAPO from exile in the Angolan capital of
Luanda, is expected to discuss the crisis this week with leaders of
the so-called Front-line states _ black African nations that border
on South Africa or are particularly concerned with events there.
   That regional bloc _ Angola, Botswana, Mozambique, Tanzania,
Zambia and Zimbabwe _ spearheads African efforts to end South
Africa's policy of apartheid, or racial segregation. Front-line
leaders often expressed fears Pretoria would try to sabotage moves
towards Namibian independence.
   Nujoma is in Harare for a three-day meeting on Namibia of 150
legislators from the Association of West European Parliamentarians
against Apartheid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
