<FIRST>r i AM-Marcos     04-04 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marcos,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paper Says Imelda Will Embalm Marcos for Display</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Imelda Marcos says she will embalm
her husband's body when he dies and display it in Hawaii until she
can return and scatter his ashes to ``fertilize'' the Philippines,
a newspaper reported Tuesday.
   ``Not only will it be a political statement: It will be a
spectacle _ an international spectacle to have Marcos (lie is
state) here,'' she told BusinessWorld in an interview at the Marcos
home in Honolulu over the weekend.
   President Ferdinand E. Marcos, his family and several cronies
fled to Hawaii when a military-civilian uprising in February 1986
put Corazon Aquino in power.
   Marcos, 71, has been hospitalized in Honolulu since Jan. 15 with
heart and lung ailments. Hospital officials say he remains in
guarded condition.
   Mrs. Aquino has repeatedly rejected requests that the former
president be allowed to return. Cabinet Secretary Jose de Jesus
said in February the president and Cabinet had agreed, for security
reasons, that not even his body would be allowed into the country.
   The paper quoted Mrs. Marcos as saying: ``I'll keep Marcos here
until 1992, then I'll bring him home.'' President Aquino's term
ends in that year.
   In May, Marcos' mother died at age 95, and her body was embalmed
and put on display. Relatives say they are waiting to bury Josefa
Edralin-Marcos until the former president returns.
   Her body lies in state at the Marcos home in Batac, 240 miles
north of Manila. A mortician visits every two months to inject
embalming fluid and retouch the makeup on her face.
   Imelda Marcos was quoted as expressing optimism that Mrs.
Aquino's successor would let them return and fulfill a wish of her
husband to be cremated and have his ashes scattered ``to fertilize
his country.''
   She is more than 20 years younger than her husband and once was
groomed to succeed him, but the paper quoted her as saying she had
no intention of running for the presidency in 1992.
   ``I've seen it all,'' she said. ``I've had it all. Now all I
want is to be left alone.''
   The Marcoses have been indicted on racketeering charges by a New
York grand jury. Mrs. Marcos pleaded innocent at her arraignment
last October but the former president's arraignment has been
postponed because of his health.
   They are accused of stealing more than $100 million of public
funds and using it to buy real estate in New York. The Aquino
government says the Marcoses and their associates plundered at
least $10 billion during his 20 years in power.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
