<FIRST>u i AM-PeruJetCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0713 04-04 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru Jet Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0713,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peruvian Jetliner Crashes On Landing, 11 People Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with company saying 11, sted 14,
injured and 137 aboard; company version of accident. Pickup 10th pvs, `In
Seattle...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Peruvian jetliner carrying 137 people
crashed and burst into flames as it landed at a jungle airport,
injuring 11 passengers and crew members, Faucett Airline reported
Tuesday. It said the others escaped unharmed.
   The privately owned airline said the Boeing 737 crashed at 6:43
p.m. Monday at the airport in Iquitos, 715 miles northeast of Lima,
during a heavy rainstorm.
   It said the craft skidded off the edge of the runway, a landing
gear and the right wing broke off and fire broke out. The pilot and
co-pilot were among the 11 injured, all of whom were Peruvians,
according to Faucett. It said most of the injuries were minor but
two people were hospitalized.
   The government's Andina news agency said earlier 130 people were
aboard the jet and 14 were injured, suffering second-degree burns
or hurt when they leaped to safety as flames engulfed the plane.
   It said some of the people jumped from the plane even before it
came to a halt.
   Andina's account gave a slightly different version of the
accident. It said the airliner tilted sideways when it was about
1,500 feet from the runway and one engine exploded in flames.
   The nose of the craft rammed into the runway and both wings tore
off as the plane skidded along the tarmac, according to Andina.
   It said the flames destroyed the fuselage, but Iquitos airport
officials reported the fire damage to the fuselage was minor. The
airport officials also said the fire broke out after the plane had
landed and went out of control.
   Andina said there had been no indications that the jetliner,
Flight 302 en route to Iquitos from Lima, had encountered earlier
difficulties.
   Airport officials blamed the crash on ``unfavorable climatic
conditions and strong tropical rains.''
   In Seattle, Boeing spokesman David Jimenez said the company had
not received any direct information on the crash. He said the
company and the U.S. National Transportation Safety Board could
send observers for any investigation if invited by Peruvian
authorities.
   NTSB spokesman Mike Benson said in Washington the agency has not
received a request from Peru concerning the accident and would not
become involved unless invited to participate.
   In the last serious accident of a jetliner in Peru 12 people
were killed when an airliner of state-owned Aeroperu crashed on
takeoff in October in the city of Puno, 610 miles southeast of Lima.
   On March 10, eight American tourists and two crew members
perished when a British-made twin-engined plane crashed into a
two-story university building in a Lima suburb.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
