<FIRST>r a AM-SegregatedSigns 1stLd-Writethru a0629 04-04 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Segregated Signs, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0629,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blacks Want Segregation-Era Signs Removed From Courthouse</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with five grafs to CORRECT that signs are etched into
the wall, sted painted; PICKS UP 6th graf pvs, ``We've got ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELLISVILLE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Signs that once identified segregated
drinking fountains are still etched in the wall of the Jones County
Courthouse, but a supervisor said Tuesday he supports plastering
over them.
   Manuel Jones, NAACP county president, asked county supervisors
Monday that the signs be covered, saying they remind people of a
bygone era in the South when public buildings often had segregated
facilities and entrances.
   The signs were painted over some time in the past, but the words
``white'' and ``colored'' still can be made out.
   Supervisor Calvin Holifield said that he would support
plastering over the signs because ``obviously they are offensive to
some people.''
   Fellow supervisors Monday tabled Jones' request to cover the
signs, saying they want to consult with the Jones County Historical
Society.
   ``We've got so many problems in Jones County that we haven't
taken action on this,'' Holifield said. ``The courthouse is listed
on the National Register of Historic Places and when you touch
something like that you have to consult them.''
   Ellisville is the seat of the economically depressed, largely
rural county in the southern part of the state.
   The courthouse was built in 1907.
   Bill Thames, president of the Jones County Historical Society,
said the society had not considered the signs.
   Holifield, who has served on the board one year, said it was the
first time anyone had brought the markers to his attention.
   The Civil Rights Act of 1964 prohibited segregation.
</TEXT>
