<FIRST>r p AM-AlabamaCongressional 1stLd-Writethru a0644 04-04 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alabama Congressional, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0644,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Seek To Hold Seat In Conservative Deep South District</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last graf to CORRECT name to Rice sted Browder. No pickup.
Matter below dash will stand; polls close at 8 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENDAL WEAVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats were favored to hold an
Alabama congressional seat in a special election Tuesday that
amounted to a test run for Republicans hoping to gain ground in the
Deep South in 1990.
   Secretary of State Glen Browder, the Democratic nominee, faced a
lesser-known Republican foe, state Sen. John Rice of Opelika, in a
roughhouse, name-calling race for the 3rd Congressional District
seat.
   The seat was left vacant in December with the death of Rep. Bill
Nichols, a conservative Democrat from Sylacauga who held the mostly
rural, 13-county east Alabama district for 22 years.
   The district, which is about 75 percent white and dotted with
small towns, appeared ready-made for the GOP's plan to bring such
conservative-leaning Southern seats into the Republican House
column next year. President Bush captured over 60 percent of the
district's votes last November.
   But Democrats sought a second straight off-year special election
victory over Republicans.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Two weeks ago, Democrat Jill Long won an Indiana congressional
seat that once was held by Vice President Dan Quayle and was viewed
as a GOP stronghold. A third off-year congressional election will
be held April 26 in Wyoming to fill Defense Secretary Richard
Cheney's House seat.
   Browder, 46, a former political science professor at
Jacksonville State University, was strongly supported by blacks and
organized labor. He has a reputation as an election reform advocate
and was endorsed by all six daily newspapers that circulate in the
district. Browder is from Jacksonville, but lives outside the
district in Montgomery.
   Rice, 37, a real estate developer from Opelika who switched
parties last year after getting elected to the legislature as a
Democrat, pinned his hopes on a campaign strategy of relentlessly
labeling Browder as a liberal.
   Gov. Guy Hunt, Alabama's first Republican governor this century,
toured the district regularly on behalf of Rice.
   Browder ran television spots calling Rice a ``hand grenade'' who
had taken potentially explosive stands to cut federal aid to the
elderly in half while voting to raise his legislative salary by 50
percent.
   Browder also called Rice an ``off-the-wall radical.'' Rice
countered by calling Browder ``a wimp ... a liberal ... a liar.''
   Rice's campaign received heavy financial support from national
Republican Party organizations in the GOP bid to gain congressional
ground in the South.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
