<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-04 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms in the Southeast; Snow in the Rockies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A band of thunderstorms whipped through the Southeast on
Tuesday, with tornadoes snapping trees and power lines in Georgia
and Alabama. A storm stalled over Colorado dropped more snow and
raised the risk of avalanches.
   In Haubstadt, Ind., divers searched two rain-swollen creeks for
the body of a 16-month-old toddler swept away after the family car
stalled on a flooded road. An Evansville woman was electrocuted by
a fallen power line.
   Tornadoes dipped across north Georgia Tuesday afternoon,
damaging homes and buildings, downing power lines and uprooting
trees. Power outages were widespread.
   A Georgia Power spokesman said approximately 26,000 customers
were without power.
   In Alabama, thunderstorms packing 70 mph wind ripped down trees
and knocked out electrical power to some 18,000 homes. State and
local police reported many homes with roof damage and some rural
roads closed by fallen trees.
   A tornado watch was posted Tuesday night over parts of Georgia,
North Carolina, Tennessee, Mississippi, Alabama and Florida.
   In Colorado, advisories were posted for an additional 6 inches
of snow Tuesday and wind gusting to 40 mph across the northern and
central mountains. The storm has dumped more than 6 feet of snow
during the past week, increasing the avalanche danger.
   Breckenridge has reported 73 inches of snow during the past
seven days, while Copper Mountain reported 62 inches and Mary Jane
58 inches.
   Showers were scattered over central and southeast New England
into northeast New York.
   Rain continued along the northern Pacific Coast. Snowshowers
were scattered in Montana, Wyoming and Nebraska.
   Heavier rainfall during the 6 hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT
included 2{ inches at Greenwood, Miss., and 1\ inches at Columbus,
Miss.
   The low temperature for the nation Tuesday morning was 7 degrees
below zero at Yellowstone, Wyo.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 27
degrees at Yellowstone, Wyo., to 96 degrees at Long Beach,
Oceanside, Ontario and Thermal, Calif.
   In Los Angeles, a 79-year-old record fell Tuesday when the
temperature hit 100. Lifeguards scrambled for help as residents hit
the beaches for relief.
   The forecast for Wednesday called for showers and thunderstorms
from central Florida across eastern Pennsylvania and New Jersey;
rainshowers from the remainder of Pennsylvania across the lower
Great Lakes, New England and much of lower Michigan, and rain from
northwest Montana across the northern Pacific Coast.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 40s over the Great Lakes,
Minnesota, North Dakota and northeast Montana; in the 50s and 60s
from New England across much of the Virginias, the Ohio Valley, the
Tennessee Valley, northern portions of the states from Georgia
across Mississippi, from Iowa across Arkansas, over the remainder
of the northern and central Plains, Oklahoma, the Rockies, the
northern half of the Plateau, and the northern Pacific Coast; in
the 80s over the Florida Peninsula; with 80s and 90s from southern
New Mexico across the southern third of inland California; near 100
over the desert Southwest, and in the 70s over the rest of the
nation.
</TEXT>
