<FIRST>u a AM-BridgeCollapse 1stLd-Writethru a0649 04-04 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bridge Collapse, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0649,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eighth Victim Found In River</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with inspectors sent out; PICKS
UP 4th graf pvs, `Crews searching ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COVINGTON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Divers pulled a car from the Hatchie
River on Tuesday and recovered from it the body of an eighth victim
of a weekend bridge collapse that may have been caused by flood
damage.
   Four state inspection teams fanned out across western Tennessee
to check other bridges for weather damage.
   State Transportation Commissioner Jimmy Evans said heavy spring
floods after two years of drought probably contributed to the
collapse Saturday night by washing sandy soil away from the bridge
supports.
   ``We're trying to make sure there's nothing that we have
overlooked in this area,'' he said.
   The body found Tuesday in a gray compact station wagon was not
immediately identified.
   Seven other victims were recovered earlier.
   Crews searching the flooded river earlier in the day discovered
signs of a possible fifth vehicle lost when a 90-foot section of
the U.S. 51 bridge gave way.
   A dog trained to smell bodies buried in rubble or under water
pointed searchers to a section of the river adjacent to the
accident on Monday.
   The object's position was confirmed Tuesday by a boat crew using
a magnet, and a wrecker pulled the car out in the afternoon.
   Crews also set up a crane to lift away the concrete slabs
covering at least three other cars and a tractor-trailer.
   Workers had used jackhammers since the accident to break up the
three slabs into pieces small enough to be raised by the crane.
   State officials said the collapse about 50 miles north of
Memphis may have been caused by flood waters washing out the soil
around the bridge supports.
   The span that collapsed was 55 years old and carried two lanes
of northbound traffic. The adjacent bridge, which carried
southbound traffic, was not damaged but has been closed.
</TEXT>
