<FIRST>r a AM-TankerCaptain 1stLd-Writethru a0660 04-04 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Captain, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0660,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family Says Oil Spill Captain Wants to Surrender</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with authorities saying no surrender Tuesday.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives of the captain of the oil tanker
that spilled its load in Alaska told police he wanted to surrender
to face Alaskan charges but was awaiting advice from his attorney,
an official said Tuesday.
   Law enforcement authorities said they are not sure where Joseph
Hazelwood is, but a source who spoke on condition of anonymity said
the captain left Anchorage last week on a flight to New York.
Hazelwood lives in Huntington, on Long Island.
   ``We talked to his parents last night,'' said Lt. Thomas Fazio,
commander of the State Police on Long Island. ``They told us
something will probably be happening soon.''
   ``But they said it was up to the attorney to decide when and
where,'' he added.
   But after Long Island law enforcement authorities waited a
second day for Hazelwood to turn himself in, the Suffolk County
district attorney's office announced there would be no surrender on
Tuesday.
   A lawyer for Hazelwood talked with the district attorney on
Tuesday, said John Williams, a spokesman for Suffolk District
Attorney Patrick Henry.
   The attorney, who was not identified, gave no indication when a
surrender would take place, Williams said.
   Hazelwood, a 20-year veteran of Exxon, is accused of being drunk
when the supertanker Exxon Valdez struck a reef March 24 and
spilled more than 10 million gallons of oil into Alaska's Prince
William Sound. He has been fired.
   Hazelwood's parents, Joseph and Margaret, who also live in
Huntington, told police they did not know where their son is.
   ``There was no deal cut,'' said Fazio. ``We told the family that
it would be better for him, down the road, to turn himself in
voluntarily.''
   If Hazelwood, 42, does not surrender within the next two days
police will actively pursue him, Fazio said.
   ``Right now if we see him on the streets, we will lock him up,''
said Fazio. ``We are anxious to bring him into custody.''
   The captain is charged with operating a ship while drunk,
reckless endangerment and negligent discharge of oil. The charges,
all misdemeanors, carry up to two years and three months in prison
and a $10,000 fine.
</TEXT>
