<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 2344EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Dissidents     04-04 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Dissidents,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-China</HEAD>
<HEAD>Petition Calling For Amnesty Given To Congress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A petition calling for the release of China's
political prisoners and signed by 24,000 people was given to
China's legislature a week after it was seized by customs officers,
state media said Tuesday.
   The official Xinhua News Agency said customs officials in
Tianjin forwarded the petition to the National People's Congress,
which closed its annual session Tuesday.
   The petition was seized last Tuesday from a group of Hong Kong
human rights activists who were attempting to bring it into China.
   A day later, the activists brought their case to the legislature
and requested that the petition be forwarded to the congress.
   Xinhua quoted a spokesman of the Tianjin customs office as
saying the request had been granted ``to respect the right of those
Hong Kong compatriots who took part in the signing to express their
views and suggestions.''
   The official said other materials seized, such as magazines and
pro-democracy periodicals, would not be released.
   The petition was signed by 24,163 people. Most of the
signatories were Chinese from Hong Kong and the West, but people
from 34 other countries also participated.
   The petition demanded specifically that China release Wei
Jingsheng, serving a 15-year sentence for ``counterrevolutionary''
crimes. Wei was arrested 10 years ago after he called for democracy.
   A growing number of intellectuals in Communist China are calling
for an amnesty for political prisoners. Since January,
intellectuals here have written four open letters urging an amnesty
and democratic change. So far, about 200 people have signed.
   Amnesty International, the London-based human rights group,
estimates that Chinese jails hold thousands of prisoners jailed for
their beliefs. China has ruled out an amnesty and says it has no
political prisoners.
   The Xinhua report said customs officers seized the petition and
the periodicals under a law that prohibits people from bringing
items ``in excess of their personal use.''
   Members of the group said they believed the seizure of the
petition did not bode well for human rights in China and for the
future Chinese treatment of Hong Kong.
   Hong Kong, a British colony since the 19th century, returns to
China in 1997. China has guaranteed to keep Hong Kong's liberal
economic and political system in place for 50 years but many Hong
Kong intellectuals are skeptical.
   In a related development, students at Beijing University said
Tuesday authorities there are forbidding students from meeting to
discuss democracy and political change in China.
   A poster that appeared on a wall Monday urged the university to
``protect our rights of freedom of speech and association.'' By
Tuesday afternoon, it had been taken down.
   The poster, signed by more than 60 students, said democratic
change in China ``is not simply a matter of saying a few empty
words.''
   It urged the school to eliminate regulations prohibiting
meetings and to protect student groups from interference by
government officials.
   A school official said the university permitted students to take
part in activities ``as long as they were healthy and good for the
students.'' But, Yan Huajiang, a school spokesman, declined to
define what type of activities those included.
   He said the university would take measures to stop ``unhealthy''
activities. He declined to comment on the poster.
   According to the poster, since the autumn semester, students
have been meeting in ``democratic salons'' to discuss political
topics.
   But recently school officials and authorities from the Beijing
city government have broken up the meetings, it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
