<FIRST>u i AM-Paraguay 1stLd-Writethru a0632 04-04 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0632,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rodriguez Pledges to Uphold Civil Liberties, Defends Feb. 3 Coup</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Following his...' with 3 grafs to UPDATE with
U.S. rejecting Stroessner request for visa. Pick up 5th pvs, ``I would...'
ADDS 3 grafs on Stroessner.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Andres Rodriguez said
Tuesday he will uphold human rights and civil liberties, including
freedom of expression.
   ``Dissent and criticism are no longer forbidden in Paraguay,''
said the 65-year-old provisional president and army commander who
toppled former President Alfredo Stroessner in a Feb. 3 coup.
   ``The crucial role of a serious and honest press should not only
be to secure democratic institutions but to project to the outside
world the truth, even if it contains imperfections,'' he said in a
speech to the Inter-American Press Association.
   In Brazil it was reported the United States has rejected a
request by Stroessner for a temporary entrance visa. Stroessner,
who ruled Paraguay for 34 years, was given political asylum by
Brazil and arrived there Feb. 5.
   Paraguayan Foreign Minister Luis Maria Argana said Stroessner
needs surgery for prostate cancer and the Paraguayan government
asked the U.S. State Department to grant him a temporary visa for
humanitarian reasons, but ``the answer was negative.'' Argana is in
Brasilia, the Brazilian capital, for a diplomatic conference.
   After speaking to the press association, Rodriguez mingled with
the nearly 200 editors and publishers at the luxurious Yacht and
Golf Club on the outskirts of the capital, Asuncion.
   ``I would have liked him to be more emphatic in defense of
freedom of the press, but it's good just to have a Paraguayan
leader talking about it in general terms,'' said Eduardo Uliberri,
director of Costa Rica's La Nacion.
   ``The general feeling in talking to the delegates is: so far, so
good,'' said Douglas A. Gripp, director of Los Angeles
Times-Washington Post news service.
   George Neavoll, editorial page editor for the Wichita (Kan.)
Eagle-Beacon, said: ``The speech was hopeful,'' but ``it's still a
period of wait-and-see.''
   Rodriguez defended the coup that ended Stroessner's regime,
which was marked by confrontations with the Roman Catholic Church,
economic setbacks, military shakeups, political repression and
international isolation in its last months.
   ``It was a legitimate reaction to an intolerable state of
affairs that was dangerously deteriorating the image of my
country,'' he said.
   Rodriguez was introduced by Aldo Zuccolillo, editor of the
newspaper ABC Color, which was closed by Stroessner and allowed to
reopen, along with Radio Nanduti and the political weekly El
Pueblo, after the coup.
   ``We are enjoying freedom but we will not let down our guard,''
Zuccolillo said. ``Freedom can become a permanent way of life in
this country.''
   Rodriguez is the ruling Colorado Party's candidate for president
in May 1 national elections, which he is widely expected to win.
   Argana told The Associated Press in Brasilia that Stroessner,
76, must go to a country with advanced medical facilities and that
he may go to Switzerland.
   Stroessner is living in a beachfront mansion in the Atlantic
resort town of Guaratuba, about 500 miles southwest of Rio de
Janeiro.
   Stroessner initially said he planned to live in Brazil but
recently expressed the desire to join his wife in Florida.
</TEXT>
