<FIRST>r a AM-People-Williams     04-04 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Williams,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hank Williams Jr. Banned From Arena</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRISTOL, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country music star Hank Williams Jr. was
banned from an arena after he cut a concert short and angry fans
burned T-shirts and other souvenirs.
   Williams sang for only 40 minutes Sunday night at Viking Hall to
a crowd of 5,000 that paid $17.50 each for tickets.
   Williams, 39, offered the audience no explanation when he
suddenly walked off stage, said Terrie Smith, director of the
city-owned hall. Fans screamed and booed for nearly an hour after
Williams jumped into a limousine for the airport.
   Members of the arena's board were in the audience and decided to
ban any future performances by Williams.
   Kathy Gangwisch, Williams' publicist, said the performer was
sick with a cold or the flu. ``He wasn't feeling up to par, but he
thought he could do the show and wanted to go on rather than face a
postponement,'' she said.
   Ms. Smith didn't buy that explanation. ``He was obnoxious, but
he was definitely not sick,'' she said.
   David Elkins, a representative of the Eastern Kentucky Disc
Jockey's Association, said some fans burned souvenirs in protest.
Elkins said he also saw Williams throw drumsticks and other objects
at his band and staff members.
   ``It really bothers me that all these young kids look up to this
man,'' he said.
   Williams, who lives in Paris, Tenn., is known for such hits as
``Family Tradition,'' ``All My Rowdy Friends are Coming Over
Tonight,'' and ``Born to Boogie.'' His current hit is ``A Tear in
My Beer.''
   Williams has invited anyone with a ticket stub to attend his
April 14 show in Knoxville, Ms. Gangwisch said. Ms. Smith said she
tried to no avail to get Williams' management to leave money for
refunds after the concert.
</TEXT>
