<FIRST>r i AM-Australia-Cyclone     04-04 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Australia-Cyclone,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cyclone Batters Australia, Kills At Least Two</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cyclone on Tuesday battered
Australia's soggy east coast where people were beginning to dig out
from floods caused by three days of torrential rains.
   At least two people were killed, 10 were injured and scores of
buildings were damaged as Cyclone Aivu lashed areas of Queensland
state with 100 mph winds. Authorities declared the Burdekin
fruit-growing region a disaster area.
   Police said one man perished when his trailer was swept into a
creek near Ayr and another man was killed when the cyclone
collapsed his house in Ayr. Most of the injured people were hit by
flying debris and at least 160 homes were destroyed or badly
damaged, according to police.
   They said power was cut in many areas and there was more
flooding.
   Floods that ravaged the east coast the previous three days were
blamed for the deaths of four people and four others are still
missing.
   The weather bureau said that during one 24-hour period more than
12 inches of rain fell and it was Sydney's wettest March in 26
years.
