<FIRST>u a AM-Shoney's-NAACP     04-04 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shoney's-NAACP,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Civil Rights Group Files Discrimination Suit Against Fast-Food Chain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A civil rights group Tuesday filed a
lawsuit accusing Shoney's Inc. fast-food chain of restricting black
employment and advancement.
   The class-action lawsuit was filed in federal court here by the
NAACP Legal Defense and Education Fund.
   ``This is a case of national importance because the employer is
a large and prominent corporation that employs a great number of
people,'' said Julius Chambers, director-counsel of the Washington,
D.C., organization.
   Shoney's operates about 1,550 restaurants in 30 states, mainly
in the Southeast, under the names Shoney's, Captain D's and Lee's
Famous Recipe Chicken.
   The complaint alleges that Nashville-based Shoney's set a policy
that limited the number of black employees in jobs with direct
contact with patrons and failed to promote or hire black workers
for managerial posts.
   Shoney's also was accused of firing blacks and whites who
complained about work conditions and dismissing blacks when their
numbers at a restaurant exceeded 30 percent.
   Shoney's spokesman Roy Vaughn said the allegations ``do not
reflect any policy or intent'' of the company.
   ``We intend to vigorously fight the suit and we expect to win,''
he said.
   The lawsuit seeks unspecified damages and an end to alleged
discriminatory practices.
   Thomas Warren, a lawyer working on the suit, said he believes it
is one of the first racial discrimation cases with both black and
white plaintiffs. Four of the nine former Shoney's employees or
applicants named as plaintiffs are white.
   The NAACP Legal Defense and Education Fund was founded by the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People in 1940
but is no longer affiliated with the NAACP. Since 1959 it has had a
separate board, staff and budget.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
