<FIRST>u a AM-Visitor-AIDS 1stLd-Writethru a0747 04-04 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Visitor-AIDS, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0747,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anger Over Detention Of Dutch Visitor Who Has AIDS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 6th graf, `Schiltgen, said ...' with previous
incidents and contagious disease restrictions for visa applicants.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHAKOPEE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Dutch visitor on his way to an AIDS
conference in San Francisco was held in a Minnesota prison Tuesday
because immigration authorities believe he has the disease.
   The detention of Hans Paul Verhoef prompted denunciations from
AIDS activists and a San Francisco congresswoman. But immigration
officials said they were just following the law.
   ``We are holding Mr. Verhoef as an excludable alien because he
has a dangerous and contagious disease,'' said Tom Schiltgen,
district director of the Immigration and Naturalization Service in
St. Paul.
   Verhoef, 31, of Rotterdam, was apprehended at the
Minneapolis-St. Paul Airport on Sunday by Customs officials who
discovered the AIDS drug AZT in his baggage.
   Verhoef, an AIDS prevention worker in his country, acknowledged
to immigration officials that he has acquired immune deficiency
syndrome.
   Schiltgen said tests would be conducted to verify Verhoef has
the disease before authorities proceed with the case. The tests
should be completed without a few days, he said.
   Joseph D. Cuddihy, INS senior immigration examiner in
Washington, said 10 to 15 people with AIDS have been turned away at
the border prior to the Verhoef case, and an unknown number have
been denied visas in their native country.
   For years, immigration laws have required people who want to
visit or move here to establish they have no dangerous, contagious
diseases. Congress added AIDS to that list of diseases in 1987.
   Verhoef can withdraw his application for admission to the U.S.
and return to the Netherlands or appeal his exclusion to the INS,
Schiltgen said. He said Verhoef tentatively had decided to appeal.
   Verhoef was transferred Tuesday from the Scott County Jail,
where he was held since Sunday, to a medical facility at Stillwater
State Prison outside St. Paul, Schiltgen said.
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., asked the U.S. attorney general to
approve a waiver that would free Verhoef to complete his trip to
San Francisco.
   Dave Runkel, a top aide to Attorney General Dick Thornburgh,
said late Tuesday that the request for a waiver had not yet reached
Thornburgh's desk.
   ``We do not believe the intent behind the immigration law was to
exclude tourists,'' said Pelosi.
   ``He didn't try to hide it,'' added Steve Morin, an aide to
Pelosi. ``We also question this on humanitarian grounds _ putting
someone in jail under these circumstances.''
   The detention also drew fire from AIDS activists in San
Francisco, where Verhoef was to be a delegate to the International
Caucus of the 7th National AIDS Forum and the 11th National Gay and
Gay Health Conference. They were to begin on Wednesday.
   ``What everyone is concerned about is that this is really a very
upsetting precedent because it impacts the freedom of people with
(the AIDS virus) to travel,'' said Steve Huber, a spokesman for the
AIDS conference.
   Bea Roman, executive director of the National Lesbian and Gay
Health Foundation, said the conference is an important educational
exchange for health care providers and educators worldwide in terms
of AIDS prevention.
   She said the exclusion of someone with the disease ``is
detrimental to international cooperation in the fight against
AIDS.''
   About 1,500 people are expected to attend the conference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
