<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 2142EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u p AM-DaleyProfile     04-04 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Daley Profile,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Daley Never Wandered Far From Early Political Arena</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Chicago Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   His nickname in high school was ``Mayor'' and his
traffic ticket on a trip home from college made front-page news.
Few men are to the manor born, but Richard M. Daley, almost
everyone said, was born to be mayor.
   On Tuesday, Daley realized that destiny when he was elected to
the office his father held for 21 years.
   Throughout a political career that had its beginnings nearly 30
years ago, the Daley name made many of Richard M.'s achievements
possible, diminished others, and left him forever open to the
charge that his vision extends only as far as his father's shadow.
   He lived at home until he was 30, and now, at age 46, still
lives only a few blocks from the bungalow where he grew up in the
working-class Bridgeport neighborhood. He looks, walks, talks, and
occasionally misspeaks in a way that makes him unmistakeably the
son of Richard J. Daley, the late six-term Chicago mayor and
big-city boss.
   ``He even began to look more like his father in recent weeks,''
said Eugene Kennedy, a Loyola University professor. ``He was
chunkier, more confident, he gave the same monosyllabic answers
with a lot of common sense in them.''
   The most frequent criticism of the younger Daley is that he has
the same politics as his father and will revive the Daley
``Machine.'' Kennedy, author of ``Himself,'' a biography of the
elder Daley, said he didn't think that was true.
   ``For one thing, a `Machine' like the old man's is a political
dinosaur that will never again roam the earth,'' Kennedy said, also
noting Daley's unsuccessful 1983 mayoral bid chastened him.
   The eldest son of seven children, Richard M. Daley cut his
political teeth working as an 18-year-old page for the Illinois
delegation to the 1960 Democratic National Convention.
   Daley graduated from law school in 1968. His father rewarded him
with a job as an assistant corporation counsel after he passed the
bar exam on his third try. The elder Daley also slated his son for
a seat in the Illinois Constitutional Convention.
   Then, in 1972, his father sent old Democratic machine warhorse
Ed Nihill packing and virtually handed Rich his seat in the
Illinois Senate.
   The younger Daley was criticized in his early years, called
little more ``his father's eyes and ears,'' and ``dirty little
Richie'' by one colleague for using his chairmanship of the
Judiciary Committee to routinely squash good-government legislation.
   But many of those same colleagues recalled how two events
changed him irrevocably. The first came on Dec. 20, 1976, when his
father died months into a sixth term. A year and a half later, his
third child, Kevin, was born with the crippling disease spina
bifida.
   ``After Dad died, Rich looked at himself for the first time
without Dad looking over his shoulder,'' recalled Daley's brother
Bill, his chief political strategist and the youngest of Richard
J.'s seven children.
   The strain of Kevin's illness may have an equally profound
impact on his life.
   Daley began taking a leadership role in such legislative issues
as nursing homes and abolishing taxes on some foods and medicine.
He showed a political acumen few thought him capable of, and forged
cautious alliances with the same reformers who often had opposed
his father.
   As a result, when he ran for the first of his three terms as
Cook County state's attorney in 1980, Democrats slated Alderman
Edward Burke to run against him. The younger Daley clobbered Burke,
then twice won re-election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890404-0186 </DOCNO>
