<HEAD>Israeli Leader Hints at Opposition to Bush's Newest Stance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Shamir's remarks. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL GEITNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said
Tuesday he would be willing to negotiate peace with ``anyone in the
world'' _ except the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Shamir began a 10-day U.S. visit Tuesday that will include a
meeting with President Bush on the Palestinian uprising.
   Speaking at the Conference of Presidents of Major American
Jewish Organizations, Shamir would not disclose specific proposals
he planned present to Bush.
   But the 73-year-old prime minister said he would be willing to
discuss ending the uprising in the occupied territories ``with
anyone in the world if I thought it would bring peace. I would do
it now, today, this minute.
   ``But sitting with the PLO will not bring peace,'' he said to
applause. ``It will guarantee disaster.''
   Shamir was to depart for Washington on Wednesday to meet with
Bush. He was expected to tell the president he opposes an
international peace conference to end the 16-month-old Palestinian
uprising in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Shamir also has rejected the U.S. ``land-for-peace'' formula.
   The prime minister said earlier Tuesday that elections in the
occupied territories are ``one of the options we're thinking
about.''
   Bush, speaking Monday after meeting in Washington with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak, called for a ``properly structured''
Middle East peace conference.
   ``Egypt and the United States share the goals of security for
Israel, end of the occupation and achievement of Palestinian
political rights,'' Bush said.
</TEXT>
