<FIRST>r a AM-HeirensClemency     04-04 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Heirens Clemency,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Convicted Killer Seeks Clemency after 43 Years in Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL A. DRISCOLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friends and supporters of William Heirens on
Tuesday pleaded for the release of the man sent to prison in 1946
for committing three sensational murders and scrawling on the wall,
``Catch me before I kill more.''
   Supporters told the Illinois Prisoner Review Board that Heirens,
who has been denied parole 28 times, is the very model of a
rehabilitated prisoner.
   But the brother and sister of one of his victims, 6-year-old
Suzanne Degnan, argued that Heirens, 60, would be a threat if freed
under executive clemency, and a prosecutor said Heirens is a
``secret killer.''
   ``I just fear for children,'' Betty Finn, sister of Suzanne,
said after the hearing. ``I don't want another family to go through
this again.''
   A lawyer for the parole board, Kent Steinkamp, said members will
send their clemency recommendation soon to Gov. James R. Thompson,
who will make the final determination.
   Heirens was a 17-year-old University of Chicago freshman when he
was sentenced to three consecutive life sentences. He pleaded
guilty to three murders and 25 burglaries.
   The dismemberment of the Degnan child followed the slayings of
two women, one stabbed, the other shot and stabbed. At one victim's
apartment, Heirens scrawled on a wall in lipstick, ``For heaven's
sake, catch me before I kill more. I cannot control myself.''
   Among the supporters urging Heirens' release was lawyer Arthur
O'Donnell, who said Heirens had gone from ``the depths of human
dispair'' to become the first Illinois prisoner to earn a college
degree behind bars.
   O'Donnell and other supporters described Heirens as a sensitive
man, always willing to help fellow prisoners. He argued that
Heirens should be released to show other inmates that there is hope
through rehabilitation.
   ``If we claim to be a civilized society, than perpetual
incarceration of anyone is antithetical to our society,'' said
O'Donnell.
   Assistant State's Attorney Joseph McNerney said Heirens's
supporters fail to see ``the nature of this man's problem.''
Outside prison, he said, Heiren would be a danger.
   ``He's a secret killer,'' McNerney said.
</TEXT>
