<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 2356EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BullfrogCounty     04-04 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bullfrog County,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nevada Senate Kills Bullfrog County Created to Tax Feds For Nuke
Dump</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nevada Senate on Tuesday killed
Bullfrog County, pop. 0.
   The county, formed in an attempt to prevent the federal
government from putting a nuclear waste dump there, was ruled
unconstitutional last year by the Nevada Supreme Court.
   It's ``not that I loved Bullfrog less, but that I loved Nevada
more,'' Sen. Thomas Hickey said in a eulogy that borrowed from
Shakespeare's ``Julius Caesar.'' ``As he was valiant, I honor him;
But as he was ambitious they slew him.''
   Hickey was a key sponsor of the bill that carved the
144-square-mile Bullfrog County out of Nye County in 1987. Bullfrog
County had no population, no roads and surrounded Yucca Mountain,
which the federal Department of Energy is studying as the possible
site for a high-level nuclear waste dump.
   Gov. Bob Miller and other state officials strongly oppose the
dump, and the desert county was formed solely to collect millions
of dollars from the government by imposing the highest property tax
rate allowed under the state constitution.
   But Nye County sued the state, contending it was entitled to any
money collected, and a Supreme Court justice ruled that Bullfrog
County was unconstitutional because, among other reasons, it lacked
a representative government.
</TEXT>
