<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 2359EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PoliceBombing     04-04 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Police Bombing,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Makeup Artist Convicted of Murdering Two Bomb Squad Officers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FERNANDO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A movie makeup artist was convicted
Tuesday of murdering two Los Angeles bomb-squad officers killed by
a pipe bomb they were trying to defuse in his garage.
   Donald Lee Morse, 39, also was found guilty of possessing a
destructive device.
   The jury, which deliberated for less than a day, also found
special circumstances that make possible a sentence of life in
prison without parole, said Deputy District Attorney Sterling
Norris. The prosecution did not seek the death penalty.
   Sentencing was scheduled for May 3.
   Detective Arleigh E. McCree, 46, head of the department bomb
squad, and Officer Ronald Ball, 43, were killed in 1986 by one of
two pipe bombs found at Morse's home.
   Police came upon the bombs while looking for a gun used by a man
in a ski mask four days earlier to wound an official of the Makeup
Artists and Hairstylists Union.
   Tests on a gun found at Morse's home determined it was not the
one used in the shooting. Morse never was charged in the case.
   McCree was a 21-year police veteran, twice a recipient of the
department's Medal of Valor and a world renowned bomb and terrorism
expert. He had been in charge of the department's bomb squad since
1979.
   The Marine Corps named him to a training team for Marines being
sent to Beirut after the October 1983 bombing of the Marine
barracks.
</TEXT>
