<FIRST>u w AM-US-Mideast 3rdLd-Writethru a0712 04-04 1043</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mideast, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0712,1070</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mubarak Says West Bank Uprising Cannot Be Halted</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 4 grafs at end with new material</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak said Tuesday
he sees no way to stop the violence on the West Bank and in Gaza
that has taken more than 400 lives since Palestinian Arabs began
their revolt against Israeli control nearly 16 months ago.
   After meeting with Secretary of State James A. Baker III for two
hours, Mubarak said that ``if anybody could stop it, we would be
very pleased,'' then asked, ``But how?''
   The Egyptian leader, nearing the end of two days of talks with
Bush administration officials, made no public demands on the United
States or Israel. He said he was simply ``trying to find out what's
the best way to achieve peace'' through negotiations.
   Baker stood aside, and in his only statement to reporters said
``it is important that we try and create a climate that can move us
toward those negotiations and try and improve the atmosphere on the
ground.''
   The next step in the search is a visit beginning Wednesday by
Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir. He is expected to outline to
President Bush and Baker a plan for holding elections among the 1.2
million Palestinians who live in the territories won from the Arabs
in the 1967 Six-Day War.
   The idea behind Shamir's proposal is to have Palestinians choose
leaders to negotiate with Israel.
   Mubarak, who has insisted that Israel deal instead with the
Palestine Liberation Organization, withheld judgment on Shamir's
proposal. He said the criterion should be whether an election would
help advance the peace process.
   A U.S. official, briefing reporters later at the White House,
said, ``We want to listen to what Prime Minister Shamir has to say
about how the peace process can be moved forward.''
   While Shamir disclosed his proposal last week in Israel, he has
withheld details until he sees Bush and Baker.
   The U.S. official, whose identity could not be used under White
House rules, called the situation on the West Bank untenable but
declined to say whether the Bush administration held the PLO
accountable.
   ``I am not going to get into the causes ... and who is in
control,'' he said.
   The Palestinian rebellion, which Shamir and other Israeli
officials say was inspired and is maintained by the PLO, began in
December 1987 and has had the effect of enhancing U.S. interest in
the situation on the West Bank and in Gaza. Since the rebellion
began, 418 Palestinian Arabs and 18 Israelis have died.
   Mubarak, in response to a question, told reporters ``neither you
nor anybody else would be able to stop the intefadeh (uprising in
Arabic). ... Let us be realistic and practical. We all hope that we
could reach peace and avoid losing lives and spending money for
killing and bloodshed. ...''
   Earlier, in an appeal for additional U.S. economic and military
aid, Mubarak told 15 senators that his nation had adopted economic
reforms and needs a continued high level of U.S. help.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell of Maine described the
90-minute private meeting as ``very beneficial and fruitful'' but
said commitments on the aid issue were neither sought nor given.
   Both Mitchell and Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas
said senators told the Egyptian president that the United States
must keep the large U.S. budget deficit in mind in dealing with all
requests for economic and military assistance.
   Mitchell said senators appeared favorably impressed with
Mubarak's description of Egypt's economic reform program, including
the reduction of subsidies on a number of consumer products and
revisions in the country's tax structure.
   ``The president argued that the pace he is pursuing is the one
most appropriate to their circumstances and the one most likely to
bring success,'' Mitchell said.
   The Egyptian leader is hoping that Congress will approve new
weapons sales once they are formally proposed by the Bush
administration and that $230 million in U.S. economic aid will be
released. The aid was withheld in March pending reforms in the way
Egypt manages its economy which that country must have in place by
June.
   Meanwhile, 200 American Jews said in a statement released by
Tikkum magazine in Oakland, Calif., that they challenged Shamir's
policies and urged him to begin negotiations with the PLO.
   ``Many American Jews, loyal supporters of Israel, do not support
the suppression of the Palestinian people and the continued
occupation of the West Bank and Gaza,'' the statement said. ``You
do not have a blank check from American Jewry to continue these
policies.''
   Tikkum is a bimonthly magazine that concentrates on political
and cultural issues of special interest to American Jews. The
signers included the comedian and writer Woody Allen, novelist
Philip Roth, playwright Arthur Miller and civil rights lawyer
Joseph Raugh.
   ``Begin negotiations with the PLO,'' the statement said. ``Not
only has the U.S. begun to talk to talk with them but recent polls
indicate that 58 percent of American Jews would support direct
negotiations with PLO leaders. ``If you are serious about seeking
peace, you must be prepared to talk directly with your enemies, and
you cannot expect to pick their representatives for them.''
   In a toast at a White House dinner honoring Mubarak, Bush said
called his two days of meetings with Mubarak ``productive, a time
for seeking common ground in approaching the peace process as well
as a good time to discuss the bilateral issues.''
   ``I firmly believe that peace will prevail if we continue to
work with a common purpose in the spirit of teamwork,'' he said.
``We must work to create a new atmosphere for Palestinians and
Israelis to put aside violence in favor of words. A dialogue for
peace for peace is the best way to establish Israeli security and
give the Palestinians their legitimate political rights.''
   Mubarak, in his toast, said Bush's presidency ushers ``a new era
of our freindship and cooperation,'' and called the president ``a
great friend of Egypt.''
   ``The American people have chosen you as the torch bearer at a
unique and critical juncture,'' he said. ``Together we have an
opportunity to make the middle east a much safer and more stable
place.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
