<DOCNO> AP890404-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 1314EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Palestinian-America Adv16   04-04 0858</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Palestinian-America, Adv 16,0881</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 16, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>``No Way You Can Forget Your Homeland.'' ^With BC-Palestinains, b0524,b0525</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhotos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON COHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jacob and John Rantisi have built a life in
America, but their hearts and minds often are in a faraway land,
where they knew the joy of being united with family and the pain of
seeing their world torn apart.
   Today, the Palestinian brothers are U.S. citizens, grateful for
freedom and success in their adopted country, but worried about and
longing for the simple, yet turbulent, homeland they left behind.
   ``It's impossible to forget your language, your home and your
people,'' said Jacob, 40, who with his younger brother John owns a
restaurant in this industrial city.
   ``I am willing to be a good citizen of the United States,'' he
said. ``(But) there is no way you can forget your homeland. When
you grow up in a place, you learn to love that place.''
   ``I remember my friends,'' said John, smoking a cigarette as he
and his brother sat in a booth in their restaurant. ``It's my home.
It's inside of me.''
   From a cramped single room they shared in the West Bank town of
Ramallah, the 11 children born to Sulieman and Rose Rantisi have
migrated to all corners of the world _ Canada, Saudia Arabia,
Jordan, Israel and the United States, Three are in Kenosha with
their mother. Sulieman died in 1974.
   Two brothers, Jaber and Audeh, remain in Ramallah. Their cousin,
Audeh, an Episcopal priest also lives there. A sister, Nadia, lives
in Jerusalem. The family keeps in contact with letters and phone
calls.
   The Rantisi brothers, who are Christians, grew up with the state
of Israel. Shortly after Israeli soldiers forced most Palestinians
out of Lod during Israel's war of independence in 1948, Jacob was
born in a cold cement room in Ramallah without doctors or nurses.
   In the following decades, Israel conquered the West Bank and the
family lived with the turmoil of tanks in the streets, fear of
bombings and worries about eviction.
   But the brothers, who built furniture in a small shop, also have
fond memories of sweet plum and almond trees, soft breezes and a
slower pace.
   ``It's a happy life without the complications like here,'' Jacob
said. ``Over here, there's too much to worry about _ money, bills.
...''
   In 1976, Jacob and his wife, Victoria, came to Illinois. His
in-laws lived there and husband and wife began working in factories.
   ``We thought we could have a better opportunity here,'' Jacob
said. ``(There) the economic situation was very bad.''
   There were other motivations. ``You're not free there,'' he
added. ``If there's a demonstration or a bomb, it makes everybody
fear they're going to be arrested. ... There is no peace.''
   John, 30, a bachelor, followed in 1979 and also worked in a
factory. They saved their money and though they had no restaurant
experience, they bought a small coffee shop in 1985.
   The brothers work 13-hour days, seven days a week, washing
dishes, cleaning and cooking in their Uptown Restaurant, which is
simply decorated with salmon-colored Formica tables and brown
Naugahyde booths.
   ``We didn't get rich here but we have a better standard of
living,'' said Jacob. He said he and his wife speak Arabic at home
and try to instill Palestinian culture in their three children.
   The brothers say they are tied by blood and spirit to the land
they still call Palestine and are troubled by the violence of the
intefadeh, the uprising against Israeli occupation in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip.
   ``When you see it on TV, especially when they beat a person, 10
years old, or 12 years old, or a lady ... you get upset, you get
angry,'' Jacob said. ``It's a very, very evil thing that they treat
human beings like that. ... I know it happens in different
countries ... but when you see this happen to your own country,
your own people ... I don't think God himself justified this.''
   ``The Palestinians are suffering in a way like the Jews suffered
from the Germans,'' he continued. ``(By) beating people and
shooting people, breaking their arms, breaking their noses ... it's
the same. Killing is killing. Suffering is suffering. You can't
justify what Hitler did and you can't justify what the Israelis are
doing against the Palestinians.''
   The brothers are hopeful a Palestinian state will emerge, though
they aren't certain how it would affect their lives.
   A settlement is needed soon, John said, ``before it's too late,
before people get more anger and more hatred.''
   But Jacob said if one comes, ``I don't see it's going to last
for too long. Neither one will be satisfied with their share.''
   Would they return?
   Jacob said he might try to open a business, but would have to
give it careful consideration. ``I live here 12 years,'' he said,
``it's not easy to leave.''
   John agreed. ``If I go back home one day,'' he said softly,
``I'm going to miss America.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday, April 16</NOTE>
