<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 1325EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-Abortion-AntiLaws Adv09   04-04 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Abortion-Anti Laws, Adv 09,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 9, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Louisiana, 14 Other States Have Anti-Abortion Laws on Books</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Abortion-Legislatures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first battles following any major
change in the U.S. Supreme Court's 1973 ruling legalizing abortion
probably would erupt in Louisiana and 14 other states that still
have anti-abortion laws on the books.
   The laws now are unenforceable because of the Roe vs. Wade
decision, but there is debate over whether they could take effect
if the high court ever overturned the 1973 ruling. The issue would
head immediately for the courts.
   Louisiana's law says that if the high court ever reverses the
1973 decision, the state's anti-abortion rules go back into force.
Idaho and Illinois have similar laws.
   ``Our law is broad and general and says the state can regulate
abortions totally within limits of the U.S. Supreme Court
decisions,'' said Jo Anne Lavert, a staff attorney for Attorney
General William Guste.
   However, Democratic state Rep. Woody Jenkins, who has written
most of Louisiana's anti-abortion laws since 1973, said he doubted
the laws could take effect again and predicted a new law would have
to be passed.
   Daniel Stier, an assistant attorney general in Wisconsin, which
has an anti-abortion law on the books from before the 1973 ruling,
said he was not sure what would happen.
   ``Until we get a decision, it's so speculative it would be a
waste of time to guess what the effect would be on Wisconsin law,''
he said. ``There are an infinite number of possibilities of what
might happen to the laws on our books.''
   Stier said he would advise district attorneys not to begin
prosecuting women for violating state law if the Supreme Court
reversed Roe vs. Wade.
   Walter Turner, an assistant state attorney general in Alabama,
said his office could not speak specifically about the state's 1852
anti-abortion law unless the Supreme Court overturned Roe vs. Wade.
But he said there had been previous cases in which old state laws
went back into effect after the Supreme Court reversed itself.
   The other states with anti-abortion laws pre-dating Roe vs. Wade
are Arkansas, Arizona, Connectituct, Delaware, Michigan,
Mississippi, New Hampshire, Oklahoma, South Dakota and West
Virginia. An attempt to repeal New Hampshire's law has passed the
House and is now before the Senate.
   Louisiana officials contend the anti-abortion law the state
enacted in reaction to Roe vs. Wade is the most stringent in the
nation.
   Before 1973, abortion was a criminal offense in Louisiana.
Anyone giving an abortion could get up to 10 years in prison at
hard labor.
   Since then, Louisiana has passed many anti-abortion laws that
have been found unconstitutional by the courts. Among the
provisions thrown out were rules forbidding abortions in the first
three months of pregnancy, requiring doctors to test the fetus to
see if it could live, mandating parental consent for minors and
requiring abortions to be performed only at hospitals by physicians.
   The only two provisions upheld prohibit public financing for
abortions and require that parents of minors be notified of plans
for an abortion.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 9</NOTE>
</DOC>
