<DOCNO> AP890404-0207 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 1325EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-Abortion-Havens Adv09   04-04 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Abortion-Havens, Adv 09,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 9, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Activists: New York Could Become Abortion Capitol Again</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Abortion-Legislatures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York was the nation's abortion capital
before the U.S. Supreme Court legalized abortions nationwide in
1973, and it likely would emerge again as a haven if the court ever
reversed the Roe vs. Wade decision.
   Women wanting to end their pregnancies would have more options
than they did 16 years ago, when 34 states outlawed abortions, but
New York still has very liberal rules on who may have an abortion.
   Some states allow the procedure only because of Roe vs. Wade and
would see renewed attempts to outlaw or restrict abortions. Fifteen
states still have anti-abortion laws on the books, although there
is debate whether they could take effect if Roe vs. Wade was
reversed.
   ``New York would retain the abortion laws it has now and women
from other states would come in here to get freely accessible
abortions, which would be a burden'' on health services, predicted
Janet Benshoof, director of reproductive freedom for the American
Civil Liberties Union.
   Under New York's law, abortions are permitted up to the 24th
week of pregnancy, as long as they are performed by a physician.
Abortions after 24 weeks are allowed if a woman's life is in danger.
   New York is one of just 12 states that still provide Medicaid
money for abortions for poor women, and it was the only one of the
16 states permitting abortions before 1973 that did not restrict
abortions to state residents.
   In neighboring Pennsylvania, by contrast, women under age 18 are
required to get their parents' consent for an abortion. The state
also requires women to be hospitalized for the procedure and to
report it to state authorities.
   Things are even more restrictive in some parts of the Midwest,
Benshoof said. She said she knows of women who have flown into New
York for abortions from Minnesota, where abortions are prohibited
after 20 weeks of pregnancy.
   ``All these reasons make abortion more delayed and more
expensive,'' she said. ``These women would want to come to New York
to avoid humiliation and unnecessary delay.''
   That was the practice during the brief period between the
legalization of abortion in New York in 1970 and the Roe vs. Wade
ruling. Young women stopped flying to England or Sweden and instead
came to New York.
   In 1972, a record 281,000 abortions were performed in the state.
By 1974, the first year after Roe vs. Wade, the number had fallen
to 162,000 and has been relatively constant ever since.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday April 9</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890404-0208 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 1320EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-WeeklyFarm Adv09   04-04 0957</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Farm, Adv 09,0977</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 9, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Consumer Food Prices Creep Up Moderately, Says USDA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barring another big U.S. drought or a major
disruption of international markets by sudden global losses in crop
or energy production, it looks like another year of moderate food
price increases for American consumers.
   The Agriculture Department is forecasing that retail food prices
may rise 3 percent to 5 percent in 1989, about in line with the
upward creep of recent years. That estimate averages 12 monthly
projections.
   But food ecomomist Ralph Parlett says the USDA forecast could be
revised later this month following a review of the price situation
for the first three months of this year.
   ``What we're looking at, primarily, is that we've gotten so much
stronger first-quarter prices, particularly in fruits and
vegetables, than we had anticipated,'' Parlett said. ``We sort of
missed ... with the cold weather in California, and some in Florida
too.''
   According to the department's Economic Research Service, if the
1989 forecast is revised upward by a full percentage point _ to a
range of 4 percent to 6 percent _ and if it proves to be accurate,
the gains in food prices would be the highest in eight years.
   In 1988, the average of monthly food prices rose an average of
4.1 percent, the same as in 1987. The annual increases previously
included: 8.6 percent in 1980, 7.9 percent in 1981, 4 percent in
1982, 2.1 percent in 1983, 3.8 percent in 1984, 2.3 percent in 1985
and 3.2 percent in 1986.
   Denis Dunham, another USDA analyst, notes in a new review that
food costs ``rose at a much higher rate in the second half of 1988
than in the first half due to the severe drought and other market
factors.''
   By December, he said, prices were 5.2 percent higher than in
December 1987, the biggest jump since 1980.
   The average 4.1 percent increase in last year's food prices was
exactly in step with the broader rise in living costs as measured
by the Labor Department's Bureau of Labor Statistics. In 1987, when
food prices also rose 4.1 percent, the overall index gained just
3.6 percent.
   Economists look at two major components: food sold in grocery
stores for use at home, and meals and snacks consumed away from
home. The two rose at almost identical average rates over the
entire year.
   But measured from December to December, food prices in grocery
stores went up much more rapidly, partly because last summer's
drought boosted prices for fresh vegetables, cereals and bakery
products, eggs, and fats and oils. By December, the food-at-home
index was up 5.6 percent from a year earlier.
   Food served in restaurants, which is affected less by the costs
of raw products, increased only 4.4 percent from December to
December.
   Dunham said the cost of the traditional market basket of food
items used to compare retail, marketing and farm values from year
to year rose 3.5 percent in 1988. The market basket includes only
grocery items produced on U.S. farms. It doesn't include imported
products or seafood.
   One of the features of the USDA market basket analysis is the
``farm value'' of various products. It is a translation of prices
received by farmers into an equivalent amount for a specific item
or quantity of food.
   For example, the average retail price of a pound of Choice-grade
beef, as measured on an all-cut basis, was $2.55 in 1988. The
producer's share, or farm value, was $1.47, or 58 percent of what
shoppers paid. But that doesn't mean live cattle sold for $1.47 per
pound because it takes 2.4 pounds of live animal to make one pound
of supermarket beef.
   Items that require lots of processing _ beef does not,
relatively speaking _ show much smaller farm values. A one pound
loaf of white bread, for example, sold for 61 cents last year. The
farmer's share for all ingredients was five cents, or 8 percent.
And that was up a penny from 1987.
   Overall, the farm value of market basket food in 1988
represented about 30 percent of the total, unchanged from 1987 and
the smallest farmer's share of the consumer food dollar since USDA
began compiling such figures more than 75 years ago.
   Department records show the farm value or share of the food
dollar averaged 46 percent in 1913. The prevous low mark was 32
percent in the early 1930s; the high was more than 50 percent in
World War II and for several years thereafter.
   Some economists, including USDA's Parlett, say that the trend to
a smaller share for the farmer also reflects a growing consumer
preference for a greater degree of processing in food. Hundreds of
preparations, microwave items and many others commonly found in
today's supermarkets were unheard of a few years ago.
   It adds up to huge spending on food.
   In 1988, according to USDA analysts, consumers spent an
estimated $394 billion in 1988 for foods produced on U.S. farms, up
$19 billion or about 5 percent from 1987. That includes both meals
at home and away from home.
   Some $97.5 billion, or about 25 percent of the total spent, was
returned to farmers, a weighted blend of the 30 percent share for
food at home and the much smaller 16 percent share of spending for
food eaten away from home. In 1987, the farm share was $92.8
billion.
   The remaining $297 billion, or the ``marketing bill'' to get
food from the farm to consumers, went to the food industry for
handling, processing and retailing food after it left the farm.
That was up $14 billion.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 9</NOTE>
</DOC>
