<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   04-04 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   
   ``Mystic Pizza'' (Virgin Vision. VHS-Beta, $89.95. Rated R)
   
   The three young women who serve up ``Mystic Pizza'' at a small
restaurant in the coastal Connecticut town of Mystic are real
charmers.
   One (Annabeth Gish) is naive and serious and headed to Yale
University; her sister (Julia Roberts) is sexy and independent and
terrified she has nothing to look forward to; and their feisty
friend (Lili Taylor) is determined to break out of her
working-class mold.
   ``Mystic Pizza'' is a slice of their lives, spiced with romance
that thrills, amuses and sometimes disappoints the women. But the
best scenes are in the pizza parlor presided over by a cook
(Conchata Ferrell) who refuses to divulge the secret of her sauce.
   Their town, populated by working-class people who make a living
from the fishing industry, and by the Connecticut upper class, is
beautifully photographed.
   The three women give excellent performances. Vincent Phillip
D'Onofrio is very good as the young man who wants to marry Taylor.
But the plot is too predictable, and the feel a little too sappy.
Still, ``Mystic Pizza'' would make a fine accompaniment to a
neighborhood pie with all the works and an evening at home.
   _ By Mary MacVean, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Big Business'' (Touchstone. VHS-Beta, $89.95. Rated PG)
   
   What happens when a dithering nurse switches twin infants by
mistake? A match more bizarre than Shakespeare's ``A Comedy of
Errors.''
   Bette Midler and Lily Tomlin play dual roles in this comedy hit
from the Disney factory.
   The Shelton sisters, Sadie and Rose, are born in a West Virginia
town whose key industry is a quilting business. They arrive at the
same time when the wife of a company employee gives birth to her
twins. Their names? Sadie and Rose, of course.
   Years later, Sadie (Midler) Shelton is the lizard sharp head of
a mulinational that wants to sell the West Virginia firm,
Hollowmade, for stripmining. Rose (Tomlin) Shelton is the _ as
Midler says _ ``wispy''twin who loves animals, the outdoors, feels
out of place in New York and doesn't want Hollowmade sold.
   Seque to West Virginia. Sadie (Midler) Ratcliff feels out of
place in the country and wants out. Sister Rose (Tomlin) wants to
fight the Sheltons to keep Hollowmade.
   The Ratcliffs come to New York. Through a mixup at the airport,
they are mistaken for the Sheltons and taken by limo to the Shelton
suite at the Plaza Hotel. The Sheltons arrive _ by subway. It's
only a matter of moments before the sisters collide.
   And that they do in the ladies room. Where else? Midler does a
wonderful mime with herself as she discovers her other ``half.''
   After confusing lovers, hotel workers and company execs, it all
works out in the end.
   ``Big Business'' is a small movie and, therefore, perfect for
the home screen. As a theatrical release, it is thin, and needed
more flesh to sustain it.
   _ By Dolores Barclay, AP Arts Editor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
