<DATELINE>SMYRNA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nissan Motor Manufacturing Corp. USA says
it will spend $490 million to expand its auto plant into one of the
biggest in the country and create 2,000 jobs.
   A new model to be made at the plant will be a four-door,
family-sized car pitched to the same market as the Nissan Stanza,
the company said Monday.
   The plant produces 240,000 Sentras and light trucks a year. The
production of the new car will boost the total output to 440,000
vehicles by 1992.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. has begun offering
interest-free, two-year loans on all of its cars and some light
trucks, in an escalation of the latest round of buyer incentives
from the automakers.
   The move Monday came after Ford Motor Co. dropped its interest
rate for 24-month loans to 2.9 percent last Wednesday. General
Motors Corp. followed that lead a day later.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three former defense contracting
executives heard themselves accused of ``bribing ... cheating ...
lying'' at the start of the first trial stemming from the federal
investigation into fraud in the Pentagon's purchasing system.
   The defendants' lawyers said Monday they had done nothing wrong.
   The three former Teledyne Electronics executives _ George Kaub,
Dale Schnittjer and Eugene Sullivan _ are charged with bribery,
conspiracy and making false statements.
</TEXT>
