<TEXT>
   Consumer confidence dropped in March as
Americans grew more concerned about rising interest rates, the
Conference Board says.
   The organization said Monday its consumer confidence index fell
to 117.7, down from 120.7 in February. The index has a base of 100.
   Despite the drop, the index remained at a relatively high level,
noted Fabian Linden, an economist with the business-supported
research group.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An insurance group says it will stop providing
advisory insurance rates, a step it said will increase costs to
insurance companies and state governments but should not affect
policyholders.
   The Insurance Services Office Inc. said Monday it dropped the
advisory rates in response to consumer groups' accusations that
they were akin to price-fixing.
   Instead, the group will provide its 1,400 participating
companies only with estimates of future loss payments.

</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon apologized for causing the nation's
biggest oil spill and promised to clean up every fouled beach in
Prince William Sound, but workers on those greasy-smelling beaches
said their efforts are futile.
   Police continued Monday searching for the captain of the tanker
Exxon Valdez, which crashed into Bligh Reef on March 24. The oil
slick has grown larger than Rhode Island.
   Meanwhile, Exxon Corp.'s president says he hopes the ``emotional
type of atmosphere'' generated by the spill does not prompt
Congress to reject the oil industry's request to drill in protected
wildlife areas.
   In an interview Monday, President Lee R. Raymond also sought to
dispel speculation that Exxon was profiting from the spill through
higher oil prices, or that the accident stemmed partly from
cost-reducing safety shortcuts.
</TEXT>
