<FIRST>r b PM-OilPrices     04-04 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Prices,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil futures declined in nervous trading
after near-normal activities resumed at the Valdez, Alaska, port,
which was partially blocked after a recent oil spill by an Exxon
Corp. tanker.
   Wholesale home heating oil also declined Monday, but unleaded
gasoline gained almost a penny a gallon on what analysts called
seasonal demands.
   Crude prices started out stronger but fell by midday after news
surfaced that the daily pipeline flow at Valdez had been increased
to 1.3 million barrels.
   ``Crude had been overbought from the Valdez crisis,'' said James
R. Steele, an energy analyst with Refco Inc. ``The opening of the
pipeline further relaxed the situation.''
   The pipeline usually carries 2 million barrels of crude a day.
But that was reduced to 800,000 barrels a day after the spill,
causing shortages at West Coast refineries and sending oil prices
higher.
   The Alaskan pipeline carries nearly one-quarter of the United
States' domestic supply of crude oil.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the May contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, slipped 24
cents to settle Monday at $19.95 a barrel. The contract had lost 62
cents on Friday.
   Among refined petroleum products, the May contract for heating
oil fell 0.62 cent to 52.75 cents a gallon. The April contract had
gained 0.71 cent on Friday, the day it expired.
   May unleaded gasoline settled at 67.85 cents a gallon, up 0.88
cent. The April contract, which also expired Friday, had ended the
week with a 2.12 cents gain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
