<DOCNO> AP890404-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 0052EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern Bjt   04-04 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, Bjt,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Creditors To Meet With Bidders</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group led by ex-baseball commissioner Peter
Ueberroth could present a reduced bid for strike-torn Eastern
Airlines to a committee representing Eastern creditors at a meeting
today.
   The Ueberroth group plans to lower its $464 million bid for
Miami-based Eastern, sources close to the sports figure and
businessman said Monday.
   The reduced offer would reflect developer Donald Trump's new
agreement with Texas Air Corp. to buy Eastern's prized Northeast
shuttle for $365 million, the sources said. Ueberroth's original
proposal _ which was withdrawn last week after he was informed it
had been topped by another suitor _ was for all of Eastern,
including the Boston-New York-Washington shuttle service.
   Separately, union and airline sources said Monday that the
15-member committee representing unsecured creditors of Eastern was
asking those interested in buying the airline to present their
offers at a meeting today.
   Union sources also said that the Air Line Pilots Association has
agreed to meet in the next few days with possible Eastern suitor
Jay Pritzker, head of the Hyatt Corp. hotel chain.
   The Ueberroth group on Thursday withdrew its $464 million offer
for Eastern after Texas Air said it had been ``materially'' outbid
by another suitor, identified by sources as Pritzker.
   However, Texas Air hasn't eliminated Ueberroth's bid from
consideration, sources close to the company have said.
   Pritzker offered about $500 million for the entire airline,
according to sources who spoke on condition of anonymity. The Hyatt
chairman is expected to meet soon with the Eastern pilots union,
possibly today, union sources said.
   Pritzker's offer is comprised of about $100 million in cash and
the rest in debt securities, according to sources. The Ueberroth
group, on the other hand, has said its $464 million offer included
about $200 million in cash.
   Takeover strategist Carl Icahn, the owner and chairman of Trans
World Airlines Inc., also has expressed interest in Eastern and has
garnered support from its unions. But he has not yet presented an
offer to the Texas Air board.
   The Ueberroth group offered to give Eastern employees a 30
percent stake in the airline in exchange for salary concessions.
The proposals by Pritzker and Icahn would involve similar
arrangements, according to sources.
   Ueberroth, Icahn and Pritzker were reported to be unavailable
for comment when contacted Monday.
   In addition to reviewing bids, the creditors committee also may
discuss strategy and organizational issues related to Eastern's
reorganization under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy laws,
according to people familiar with the proceedings who asked not to
be identified.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton Lifland, who is overseeing
Eastern's reorganization, has asked members of the creditors
committee not to discuss developments at today's meeting with the
press, the sources said. The meeting, possibly the first of a
weekly series, is expected to be held in the offices of lawyers
representing one of the creditors, they said.
   The creditors committee includes representatives of major
aircraft and engine manufacturers, banks acting as trustees for
Eastern bondholders, and the Eastern Machinists and pilots and
non-union employees.
   The panel has the right to review any reorganization plan
proposed by Eastern and can propose its own plan to the bankruptcy
judge. It represents unsecured creditors, who are the most likely
to lose money in the bankruptcy reorganization because they have no
collateral, or security, from Eastern in case of default.
   The Machinists union at Eastern struck the airline March 4,
drawing the support of pilots and flight attendants and bringing
operations to a virtual halt. Eastern was forced to seek
reorganization and bankruptcy protection from creditors five days
later as its cash reserves dwindled.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890404-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 0140EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AutoIncentives Bjt   04-04 0794</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Incentives, Bjt,0817</SECOND>
<HEAD>Free Financing For 2-Year Loans At Chrysler</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. has upped the ante in
what could be a high-stakes, match-me incentive game by offering
interest-free financing on two-year loans for all of its cars.
   The nation's No. 3 automaker made the move Monday, five days
after Ford Motor Co. challenged the other automakers with 2.9
percent financing for two-year terms. General Motors Corp. followed
Ford's lead a day later.
   Interest-free automobile financing was last offered in September
1986 by American Motors Corp., which Chrysler bought less than a
year later.
   Chairman Ben Bidwell of Chrysler Motors Corp., the corporation's
car-making arm, called the free financing deal ``the ultimate in
APR (annual percentage rate) programs.''
   ``It can't get any lower,'' he added. ``It can't get any
simpler.''
   In addition to the low financing for two-year terms, each of the
Big Three also expanded and boosted some of their cash rebates and
offered 5.9 percent financing for three-year loans and 6.9 percent
for four-year notes.
   Ford and GM will write a five-year loan for 9.9 percent, 1
percentage point lower than Chrysler's rate for a 60-month term.
Chrysler's program runs indefinitely. Ford's expires May 31 and
GM's runs out June 5.
   For a customer financing a $13,000 car with $1,000 down, meaning
a $12,000 loan, the monthly payments on a two-year loan would be
$500 under Chrysler's interest-free incentive, and $515.24 under
Ford and GM's 2.9 percent plans. A two-year loan at 11 percent, a
common open-market rate, would be $559.29 a month.
   For a more-common 48-month loan, a buyer of either a Chrylser,
GM or Ford car would pay $286.80 under the 6.9 percent loans
offered by the Big Three. With a market-rate loan of 11 percent, a
48-month loan would come to $316 monthly.
   Each of the companies acknowledged that the incentives would cut
into their profits, and Bidwell said the company's earnings during
the first six months of 1989 would be below last year's levels, and
then rebound in the second half.
   But automobile analyst David Healy of Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc. of New York disagreed.
   ``I think the gradual increase you've seen in sales incentives
over the last three or four months will have a significant
impact,'' he said. ``I think Chrysler's earnings are likely to be
flat. A few months ago, I was looking for a good-size increase.''
   The incentive war comes on the heels of unexpectedly low early
1989 sales and inventories that have been causing some worry, but
no panic, among automakers. Each of the Big Three automakers set
ambitious production schedules for the first few months of this
year, and there are no large-scale moves to curtail them yet.
   Car and light truck sales through the first 80 days of 1989 have
been running 5.4 percent behind the same period last year, the
second-best in the industry's history.
   Sales figures for the first quarter of the year are due out
today. The automakers are hoping that the new incentive programs
will give sales a boost during April, when they usually are strong
as Americans look forward to summer vacations and weekend driving
trips.
   Interest-free financing affects only two-year loans, which in
the past have made up about 12 percent of Chrysler Credit Corp.'s
business. Jerry Farrell, president of loan-making company, said he
expected that percentage to double with the new program.
   He also said the 6.9 percent interest rate for 48-month loans,
down from 8.9 percent in Chrysler's previous incentive program,
will attract buyers who may have been considering five-year notes.
   Chrysler, unlike Ford and GM, has not seen a growing number of
repossessions and loan defaults in the five-year loan category,
which makes up about 60 percent of the company's vehicle-loan
business.
   The interest-free loan deal was well received by dealers the
corporation talked with during the weekend, said Tom Pappert, vice
president for sales at Chrysler Motors.
   But the program is bound to face strong criticism from Ron
Tonkin, president of the National Automobile Dealers Association.
   Late last week, after Ford and GM announced their new incentive
programs, Tonkin called the incentive war a ``circus.'' He urged
automakers to get out of the match-me incentive games and ``lower
the prices once and for all and guarantee the public those are the
prices.''
   But Bob Lutz, president of Chrysler Motors, said that won't
work. Rebates frequently are used to bolster the credit-worthiness
of a potential buyer by increasing their down payment, he said.
   ``We would greatly prefer to operate the way we used to operate,
...'' Lutz said Monday, ``but the reality is that isn't the world
we live in anymore. Whether we'll ever get out of it is anybody's
guess.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
