<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 0223EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-UA-QintexLawsuit     04-04 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-UA-Qintex Lawsuit,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawsuit Filed To Stop United Artists Sale To Qintex</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM and PM-Foreign Invasion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York trust filed suit Monday in an
attempt to halt the sale of United Artists to an Australian company.
   The lawsuit, filed in Superior Court, came just three days after
Qintex Group proposed the purchase of the Los Angeles-based movie
studio for $1 billion, the biggest of a series of moves by foreign
firms to buy Hollywood companies.
   The Chappaqua Family Trust alleged that the price to be paid for
UA's assets is ``inadequate, unfair and fraudulently determined.''
   Investor Kirk Kerkorian, who owns 82 percent of the company's
stock, and the Tracinda Corp., Kerkorian's holding company, along
with Qintex Entertainment Inc. are named as defendants.
   Chappaqua Family Trust also alleges that UA executives were
derelict in their duty to stockholders because the sale, scheduled
for completion on Sept. 30, was ``designed specifically to enable
defendants Kerkorian and Tracinda to unfairly withdraw substantial
value from the company and to solidify and retain control over the
balance of the company's valuable assets.''
   Calls to Qintex offices in Los Angeles and to UA spokesmen after
business hours Monday were not answered.
   Under the deal announced Friday, Qintex agreed to acquire all
outstanding stock of UA's parent company,
Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer_United Artists, at $20 a share.
   Qintex, best known in the United States as one of the makers of
the CBS miniseries ``Lonesome Dove,'' would get the UA moviemaking
group and its film library.
   But Kerkorian would retain control of the MGM name and its TV
and movie studios, as well as 34 MGM movies, including
``Moonstruck'' and ``A Fish Called Wanda.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
