<DOCNO> AP890404-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 0228EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-C&amp;S-NCNB Bjt   04-04 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-C&amp;S-NCNB, Bjt,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>C&amp;S Board Rejects NCNB Buyout Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Citizens and Southern Corp. is relying on a
regulatory shield to fight an unwelcome $2.4 billion takeover
attempt by the NCNB Corp., a merger that, if completed, would
create the nation's sixth-largest bank.
   The board of the parent company of the Atlanta-based C&amp;S Bank
voted unanimously Monday to reject the NCNB Corp. offer, calling it
``inadequate,'' and saying C&amp;S' management can better serve the
bank's customers, shareholders and communities than can NCNB.
   The surprise bid for C&amp;S followed a push by NCNB into Texas last
year, in which it bought into the Republic Bank Corp. of Dallas.
The move by the Charlotte, N.C.-based corporation drove its stock
price up 50 percent, enabling NCNB to mount other takeover drives
with stock, not cash.
   ``We have managed this bank for service, growth, profitability
and long-term service to shareholders _ not for a quick sale,'' C&amp;S
Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Bennett A. Brown said in a
statement.
   ``The board of directors and the management have concluded that
this offer is clearly inadequate and not in the best interests of
C&amp;S shareholders, customers and employees,'' he said.
   In a statement Monday night, NCNB called its offer ``fair and
generous'' and said its legal advisers felt there was no regulatory
block to such an acquisition.
   ``We are determined to proceed, and request the C&amp;S board to
reconsider our offer and promptly authorize negotiations,'' the
release said.
   H. Rodgin Cohen, a New York lawyer specializing in bank
takeovers, said Monday there is ``some chance'' NCNB Corp. would
respect the wishes of the board.
   Cohen is acting as special counsel to C&amp;S. He said C&amp;S is the
stronger bank and that the Federal Reserve Board has frowned upon a
weaker bank taking over a stronger one.
   He also said the government is worried about banks that grow
radically faster than their peers. Along with the Texas
acquisition, acquiring C&amp;S would mean NCNB would expand its size
threefold in a year.
   Because of the structure of the C&amp;S board of directors, he said,
NCNB could not control it until two years after a takeover and
noted that the government had rejected mergers with similar
problems because of potential disruptions and discord between the
board and the majority stockholders.
   Ben E. Johnson III, a tax specialist with Alston &amp; Bird, the
Atlanta law firm representing C&amp;S, said the acquisition might be
blocked at the state level because by virtue of having more than 20
percent of its deposits in Texas, NCNB Corp. cannot be considered a
member of the Southeastern banking compact.
   Georgia banks cannot be sold to banks outside the compact.
   He said Georgia bank examiners might balk at the prospect of
NCNB moving Georgia capital from C&amp;S to Texas to ``finance a
speculative investment in a state outside the region.''
   NCNB, the Southeast's largest banking company, surprised C&amp;S and
financial observers Thursday with its $2.4 billion stock offer. C&amp;S
management was cool to the idea from the start.
   NCNB told C&amp;S it wanted to begin ``active merger discussions''
within five business days.
   Also Monday, the C&amp;S' board voted to adopt a new article in the
corporation's bylaws, under Georgia's Business Combination Act,
preventing any major shareholders from engaging in a business
combination for five years, unless certain conditions are met. The
move could make a takeover more difficult.
   A combined NCNB and C&amp;S would create a formidable bank with $76
billion in assets. NCNB officials characterized their buyout offer
as friendly and vowed to leave C&amp;S' managers _ and its name _ in
place in Georgia.
   Under NCNB's plan, C&amp;S shareholders would get 1.075 shares of
NCNB common stock for each of their C&amp;S shares.
   NCNB would have to issue about 66 million new shares to provide
C&amp;S stockholders with the $2.4 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
