<DOCNO> AP890404-0218 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 0245EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Northwest Bjt   04-04 0780</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest, Bjt,0807</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minnesota Will Fight Northwest Takeover Attempt, Officials Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY R. SANDOK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Rudy Perpich and other Minnesota
officials are pursuing a number of options aimed at thwarting a
takeover of Northwest Airlines, a move they see as a threat to the
state's economy.
   ``They're in for one hell of a fight,'' House Speaker Robert
Vanasek said Monday of two groups that have proposed buying
Northwest's parent company, NWA Inc., which is based in suburban
Eagan.
   Investor Marvin Davis has offered to buy NWA for $2.62 billion,
or $90 a share. Davis owns 3 percent of NWA's 29.1 million shares.
A second, unidentified group of investors that owns 4.9 percent of
the stock also is interested in buying the company, NWA says.
   NWA stock closed down 50 cents Monday at $84.37{ a share on the
New York Stock Exchange.
   Vanasek was among the legislative leaders and constitutional
officers from both political parties, union officials and others
who pledged at a news conference to back Perpich in what he has
described as an ``all-out war'' against a hostile takeover of the
nation's fourth-largest carrier and one of the state's largest
employers.
   NWA has indicated its board will review the Davis offer, which
he insists is friendly, but the company has said it intends to
remain independent.
   The airline has not asked for state assistance, state officials
have said. But unionized machinists, pilots, and flight attendants
have asked the state to help ensure that Northwest remains an
independent company and that Minneapolis-St. Paul International
Airport remains a Northwest hub, state Commerce Commissioner
Michael Hatch said.
   The Democratic governor said the following actions are being
taken:
   _U.S. Rep. James Oberstar, D-Minn., who chairs a House aviation
subcommittee, assured state officials that he will conduct a
hearing to investigate the financial background of any major
investor involved in a potential Northwest takeover. Such an
investigation, Perpich said, would be aimed at ensuring the
investor ``had the financial capability to operate Northwest
Airlines in the professional manner on which the economy of
Minnesota depends.''
   _Members of the Minnesota congressional delegation are being
asked to develop an anti-takeover strategy at the federal level.
   _The U.S. Justice and Transportation departments will be asked
to thoroughly review any proposed sale.
   _Legislation that would grant the Minnesota commerce
commissioner authority to approve a change of ownership of a
corporation that occupies a controlling market share of any segment
of the transportation industry is being researched for possible
introduction in the state Legislature.
   _The state attorney general's office is looking into the
possible anti-competitive effects of a takeover of Northwest and
legal remedies available to the state.
   _Legislative leaders are looking into possible legislative
proposals aimed at protecting state workers and state public
investment in the event of a buyout.
   Asked which items on the list might thwart a takeover, Perpich
said, ``We don't know, but we're going to explore every possible
avenue.''
   Industry analysts said it was unclear what, if anything, state
officials could do to block a takeover.
   ``It makes total sense for them to do what they can, but how
much of an impact can they have?'' asked Kurt Rivard of
Minneapolis-based Dain Bosworth Inc.
   If Davis upholds his promise of expanding the airline and
keeping its headquarters in Eagan, the state would be worse off by
blocking a takeover, said Louis Marckesano, an airline analyst for
Janney Montgomery Scott Inc. of Philadelphia.
   ``No management should be entrenched to the exclusion of a
sale,'' Marckesano said.
   The Legislature moved swiftly in June 1987 to block the
threatened hostile takeover of Minneapolis-based Dayton Hudson
Corp. by Dart Group Corp. by passing anti-takeover legislation. But
the law does not affect NWA, which is chartered in Delaware.
   The anti-takeover legislation played a role in the defense of
Dayton Hudson, but the October 1987 stock market crash _ which
slashed millions of dollars from the value of Dart's holdings _ is
largely credited with saving the company from takeover.
   Analysts have warned that a takeover of Northwest would almost
certainly result in the firing of some of the company's 35,000
employees.
   Northwest has about 17,000 employees in Minnesota. Perpich said
an additional 70,000 Minnesotans whose livelihood depends on the
airline operation also would be affected by a takeover.
   Monday's Wall Street Journal suggested that NWA could defend
itself from takeover bids by issuing a special dividend to
shareholders. NWA could easily raise money for a special dividend,
analysts told the newspaper, because it owns 73 percent of its
aircraft fleet, the second highest percentage of the eight major
U.S. airlines. NWA could sell the planes and lease them back.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
