<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 1040EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Drexel-Columbia     04-04 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drexel-Columbia,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Columbia Savings And Loan Investigated As Part Of Drexel Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Columbia Savings &amp; Loan Association
confirmed that federal investigators are examining whether it
engaged in illegal trading with the high-yield bond department at
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   The thrift has given ``cartons of documents'' to the U.S.
Attorney's office in New York and the Securities and Exchange
Commission, said Kenneth R. Heitz, Columbia's executive vice
president and general counsel.
   Some Columbia employees have been subpoenaed to appear before a
New York grand jury investigating criminal allegations against
Drexel, he said.
   However Drexel, which already has agreed to plead guilty to six
violations of securities fraud laws, said in a prepared statement
that it was confident no wrongdoing involving Columbia had occurred.
   ``Columbia Savings &amp; Loan Association has been one of the
largest customers of the Drexel Burnham Lambert high-yield bond
department, and we continue to have an important business
relationship with that group,'' the company said.
   ``Like virtually every important customer of Drexel's high-yield
bond group, Columbia has produced to the SEC and the U.S. attorney
its entire trading records with Drexel for the past five- to
seven-year period.''
   The Los Angeles Times, quoting unnamed sources, reported today
that at least one Drexel employee gave testimony several ome months
ago to the grand jury about Drexel's dealings with Columbia.
   Columbia has grown rapidly and earned large profits by using
deposits to invest heavily in the high-risk, high-yield junk bonds.
   Columbia's chief executive, Thomas Spiegel, has been described
as a close business associate of Michael Milken, head of Drexel's
Beverly Hills-based high-yield bond department until his indictment
last week.
   Milken, his brother, Lowell Milken, and former Drexel trader
Bruce L. Newberg were charged with racketeering and securities
fraud in a 98-count federal criminal indictment that had been
expected for months.
   Heitz declined to say who had been subpoenaed, but said Spiegel
was not among those called before the grand jury.
   Columbia said it conducted its own internal inquiry into trading
with Drexel.
   ``We have found nothing which indicates that any of the trading
activity between the two companies is anything other than normal
arm's length business transactions,'' the company said.
</TEXT>
