<FIRST>r f BC-DowVentures     04-04 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dow Ventures,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dow In Ventures With Chinese, Soviets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDLAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dow Chemical Co. said today it has entered
a joint venture to build a $50 million chemical plant in China and
joined a group of companies studying a venture to expand a Soviet
chemical plant.
   Dow said it entered a 50-50 joint venture with China's Zhejiang
Chemical Factory to build a $50 million chemical plant in Ningbo,
China.
   The new company, Zhejiang Pacific Chemical Corp., will produce
chemicals for China's growing polyurethane foam industry, reducing
its dependence on imports, Dow said.
   The company's Dow Canada subsidiary was awarded a $15 million
contract to aid in design, engineering, procurement of equipment
and training of operating personnel for the plant, which will
employ more than 200 people.
   The plant, in Zhejiang Province on China's east coast, is
expected to be operating in 1993, producing 20,000 metric tons a
year of polyether polyol, Dow said.
   Polyether polyol is used to make foam for furniture, seat
cushions, mattresses, automobile parts, laminated fabrics and
building and refrigerator insulation.
   The Chinese plant also will produce 5,000 metric tons a year of
propylene glycol for use in pharmaceutical products, solvents and
polyester resin.
   Dow also said it joined a consortium of Western firms, including
Dow Europe SA and Litwin Cos., launching a four-month feasibility
study of a joint venture with the Soviet petrochemical industry.
   The group is studying expansion of a petrochemical complex in
Shevchenko in the Soviet Union to add the manufacture of styrene
plastics and ethylene derivatives. If the project proceeds, total
capital is expected to amount to less than $1 billion, with Dow
Europe and Litwin Cos. providing less than 50 percent of that, Dow
spokeswoman Sarah Opperman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
