<FIRST>r f BC-BrothelBuyout     04-04 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Brothel Buyout,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Home State Sale Approved for Mustang Ranch Stock</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM GARDNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shares of stock in America's best-known
brothel are on sale in its home state.
   Seven weeks after the Securities and Exchange Commission
approved the initial offering of stock in the Mustang Ranch, the
Nevada Securities Division permitted the sale of a limited amount
of the issue on Monday, according to Judith Allan, education and
research coordinator for the agency.
   Allan said the division approved sales of $350,000 worth of the
$23.3 million offering after receiving a $300 filing fee and a
supplemental prospectus it had requested from the company making
the offer that detailed potential risks to investors.
   She said the remaining $23 million of the stock offer was
expected to be authorized once the state received an additional
$2,130 filing fee.
   The bid to take the Mustang Ranch public at $20 a share is about
80 percent sold out and the initial offering should close in about
a week, according to the president of the firm handling the sale.
   Eric Walloga, whose Tampa, Fla.-based American Wallstreet
Securities Inc. is overseeing the initial offering, said he
expected the issue to sell out once Nevada joins the nine other
states and the District of Columbia where the stock is being
offered.
   Since the offering was approved by the SEC in mid-February,
Walloga said the stock had been approved for sale in Florida,
Georgia, Illinois, New Jersey, Maryland, New York, Connecticut,
Colorado, Hawaii and the District of Columbia.
   He represents Mustang Ranch Inc., an investors' group composed
primarily of Reno businessmen and attorneys that wants to raise the
money to buy the brothel 10 miles east of Reno from Joe and Sally
Conforte.
   Once the initial offering is sold out, the brothel can
officially change hands and the stock will be traded over the
counter, Walloga said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
