<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 1141EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   04-04 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0275</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices for wheat were mostly lower but
corn and soybeans were higher today in early trading at the Chicago
Board of Trade.
   Analysts said wheat was being sold largely because of
profit-taking after Monday's closing rally and the lack of
confirmation of rumors concerning a big sale to China.
   ``The feeling is corn and soybeans were oversold yesterday,''
research director Jerry Gidel of LIT America Inc. said.
   Corn also was being supported by the sale overnight of 450,000
metric tons of the product to the Soviet Union, he added.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 4 cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.04{ a bushel; corn was 1\ cents
to 2\ cents higher, with May at $2.61\ a bushel; oats were 3\ cents
to 4\ cents higher, with May at $1.90{ a bushel; and soybeans were
2{ cents to 5{ cents higher, with May at $7.15{ a bushel.
   Futures prices for livestock and meat were mostly mixed in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   In early trading, cattle were .40 cent lower to .15 cent higher,
with the contract for delivery in April at 77.55 cents a pound;
feeder cattle were .63 cent lower to .15 cent higher, with April at
79.50 cents a pound; live hogs were .30 cent lower to .20 cent
higher, with April at 40.55 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies
were .10 cent to 1.10 cents lower, with May at 35.25 a pound.
   On Monday, livestock and meat prices were mostly lower.
</TEXT>
