<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 1229EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-SovietMBA     04-04 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Soviet MBA,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Portland State Helps Develop Soviet MBA Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Portland State University business courses
will be used by the Khabarovsk Institute of National Economy in a
new master's degree program that Soviet educators say reflects
their country's changing economic structure.
   The economic restructuring, or perestroika, brings greater
financial responsibility and the need ``to be a real businessman,''
said Pyotr M. Konevskih, rector of the institute in Khabarovsk,
about 30 miles north of the Chinese border and 350 miles northwest
of Japan. Khabarovsk is Portland's sister city in the Soviet Union.
   About 5,000 students attend classes at the institute.
   ``Our hope is that we'll be putting hundreds of students through
this program,'' said Earl Molander, program coordinator and
chairman of the management department in Portland State
University's School of Business Administration.
   About 50 students specializing in industrial management are
expected to start classes this fall to prepare them for the
program. The full program, expected to cost the Soviets $250,000,
will start in April 1990.
   ``It will be a great challenge, taking a business curriculum
designed for a market economy and Western culture and to use that
as a framework to educate a current generation in a centrally
engineered economy that is becoming more market-oriented,''
Molander said.
   Soviet educational and business systems differ greatly from
those in the United States, so the Portland State program will be
adjusted to the Soviets' economic system, while retaining basic
features like accounting, management, communication and marketing,
Molander said.
   Some concepts, however, don't translate easily, he said. The
term ``marketing'' had to be adopted straight from English into the
Russian vocabulary because there was no Russian equivalent,
Molander said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
