<SECOND>BC-India-Carbide,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bhopal Victims Want Union Carbide Declaration To Court Stopped</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers of the Bhopal gas leak victims
Tuesday cautioned the Supreme Court against accepting a declaration
by Union Carbide Corp. concerning compensation money to the
victims, news reports said.
   Union Carbide, in an affidavit, said it had complied with the
court's order to deposit a part of the $470 million compensation
for the victims of the Dec. 2-3, 1984, gas leak, United News of
India news agency said.
   More than 3,400 people were killed and at least 20,000 injured
when deadly methyl isocynate gas spewed from a pesticide plant run
by the Indian subsidiary of Union Carbide in the central Indian
city of Bhopal.
   Three lawyers, arguing on behalf of some victims, said that once
the court accepted the declaration, the U.S multinational would
refuse to submit to the jurisdiction of the Indian court, United
News of India said.
   The five-judge panel will hear arguments Thursday on the
objections by Shanti Bhushan, Soli Sorabji and Indira Jaising.
   The panel, headed by Chief Justice R.S. Pathak, on Feb. 14-15
ordered Union Carbide to pay $465 million as compensation following
a Feb. 14 settlement between the Indian government and Union
Carbide. The company had earlier give $5 million to the Red Cross.
   Union Carbide's attorney told the court that under the terms of
the settlement the compensation money had been deposited and the
``settlement orders stood complied with,'' United News of India
reported.
