<FIRST>r f AM-Tyson-HollyFarms     04-04 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tyson-Holly Farms,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tyson Officials Happy About Situation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGDALE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Now that Tyson Foods Inc. has tenders
for about 55 percent of the shares in Holly Farms Corp., the next
move in the battle for control of Holly Farms is up to ConAgra
Inc., an analyst says.
   Tyson, the nation's largest poultry producer, began its
attempted takeover of Holly Farms last fall. Holly, based in
Memphis, Tenn., responded by working out a stock-swap agreement
with ConAgra, based in Omaha, Neb.
   On April 14, shareholders of Holly Farms and ConAgra will be
asked to vote on the proposed merger.
   Tyson has extended its offer of $63.50 per share for Holly Farms
and said Sunday it had tenders for more than 10 million of Holly
Farms' 18.4 million outstanding shares. ConAgra has stuck by its
$59.25-per-share stock swap.
   ``The ball is in ConAgra's court now, and I believe that we will
see ConAgra either increase its bid or step out of the picture,''
Napoleon Overton, an analyst with Morgan Keegan in Memphis, said
Monday.
   ``The rules prohibit us from claiming victory, but this is very
encouraging,'' Jim Blair, Tyson's chief counsel, said of the status
of the tenders.
   ``The deal, as it is, looks like (shareholders) are going to
vote against the ConAgra merger. In order for ConAgra to win, it
needs a vote of over 12 million shares. But I'm not claiming a
victory.''
   A shareholder places a tender by calling his broker and
requesting it, but he can withdraw the tender any time, Overton
said. ``It's an indication, not a promise,'' he said.
   ``Someone can tender shares and still vote for the ConAgra
merger,'' Holly Farms spokesman Ted Bailey said. ``I've spoken to
shareholders that have done that.''
</TEXT>
