<FIRST>r f AM-ConrailCEO     04-04 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Conrail CEO,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conrail Names James A. Hagen as New President, Chairman, CEO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERICH SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conrail named CSX Corp. executive James A.
Hagen Tuesday as its new chairman, president and chief executive to
fill a vacancy left by the death of Richard D. Sanborn.
   Sanborn died on Feb. 12 after six weeks on the job from what was
described as an apparent heart attack. He was 52.
   Hagen, 57, is currently president and chief executive officer of
CSX Distribution Services Group in Baltimore, part of the rival
Richmond, Va.-based CSX. He officially joins Conrail on April 17.
   Hagen will officially join Conrail April 17. He will be
nominated to the railroad's board of directors at the company's
annual stockholders' meeting May 17. His appointments are to be
effective May 18.
   Hagen was Conrail's senior vice president of marketing and sales
from February 1977 to March 1985.
   Before his first stint with Conrail, Hagen had been president of
the United States Railway Association, the government agency
established to plan for the creation of Conrail out of six bankrupt
rail companies, including the Penn Central in April 1976.
   He will succeed Stanley E.G. Hillman, who was elected by
Conrail's board to the interim position of acting chairman,
president and CEO Feb. 15, after Sanborn's death. Hillman will
remain on Conrail's board after Hagen takes over.
   ``Mr. Hagen will bring a wealth of outstanding qualities to his
new position at Conrail, including his earned reputation as one of
the outstanding marketing executives in the reilroad industry, and
his substantial first-hand knowledge of Conrail as a company,''
said Hillman.
   Hagen was not in his office Tuesday to comment on the
announcement, his secretary said.
   In January, Sanborn said that studies were under way to see
whether Conrail should diversify into other transportation-related
businesses _ for example, hauling solid waste or operating sanitary
landfills to which the railroad would haul trash.
   Asked if Hagen intended to continue Sanborn's programs, a
Conrail spokesman referred to Hillman's comments as released by the
railroad. In that statement, Hillman said, ``Mr. Hagen is dedicated
to continuing specific programs initiated by Mr. Sanborn in
strategic planning, in making further improvements in customer
service, in new business exploration, and in safety, all of which
have been endorsed by Conrail's board of directors.''
   CSX said Glenn P. Michael, senior vice president for sales and
marketing of CSX Distribution, will take over the duties of the
departing Hagen.
</TEXT>
