<FIRST>r f AM-Britain-GoldFields     04-04 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Gold Fields,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Mining Group Promises Big Dividend If It Doesn't Deliver</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consolidated Gold Fields PLC on Tuesday unveiled a
novel defense against a hostile bid from Minorco SA, promisiBv to
pay its shareholders $2.2 billion in dividends if it doesn't meet
its own profit forecast.
   South African-based Minorco, whose offer values all of the
British mining group at about $5.4 billion, is trying to overturn a
U.S. court decision that threatens the bid. It would be Britain's
biggest takeover ever.
   A preliminary injunction arising from a U.S. antitrust suit
against Minorco blocks it from buying more than 30 percent of Gold
Fields' shares. The mining investment concern currently owns 29.6
percent of Gold Fields.
   Analysts generally expect Luxembourg-based Minorco to raise its
bid from its current cash and stock offer of $23.75 a share.
   Gold Fields shares rose 43 cents to finish at $22.92 on London's
Stock Exchange Tuesday. Minorco's shares fell 19 cents to $12.63.
   Gold Fields guaranteed shareholders more than 20 percent average
annual compound growth in earnings per share over the three years
ending in June 1992. If its target of $6.80 in cumulative earnings
per chare isn't met by the end of the 1992 fiscal year, then
shareholders will receive a special cash dividend of $10.20 per
share, it said.
   Gold Fields has about 213 million shares outstanding.
   ``No British company has ever committed itself so firmly to
value for its shareholders,'' said Chairman Rudolph Agnew. ``Gold
Fields has both the assets and the management to see off Minorco
for good and our performance pledge is designed to ensure both
value today"and value tomorrow for all our shareholders.''
   ``Quite a major scheme of (corporate) restructuring woUld be
necessary'' to pay the special dividend, a company spokesman said.
This could involve such moves as a stock offering of part of Gold
Fields' highly profitable ARC construction aggregates business or
of its U.S.-based Gold Fields Mining Corp., said the spokesman, who
wasn't identified, in accordance with British custom.
   The spokesman added there weren't any immediate plans for sales.
   The special dividend payment would require approval of a
resolution by 51 percent of the shareholders authorizing the
company to issue special preferred stock free to existing holders
on a one-for-one basis.
   ``It's a phenomenal growth rate for any company to admit to,''
said John Willis, an analyst at Yamaichi International (Europe)
Ltd. ``It's a very, very clever move'' by Gold Fields in its bid
defense.
   The move could help determine the outcome of the takeover
battle, Willis said. Institutional shareholders in Gold Fields,
many of whom are already flush with cash, might reject Minorco's
offer in favor of a guaranteed realization of their gains over the
next three years, Willis said.
   Minorco said Gold Fields' latest defense wasn't relevant to the
takeover bid and ``will have no impact on our thinking.''
</TEXT>
