<DOCNO> AP890404-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 1550EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-FarmTrade     04-04 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Trade,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Farm Leader Calls For Protective Farm Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress should write a 1990 farm bill on the
assumption that the European Economic Community will block any
chance of substantive progress for easing world agricultural trade
restrictions, a U.S. farm leader said Tuesday.
   Dean Kleckner, president of the American Farm Bureau Federation,
said the new legislation should continue the current Export
Enhancement Program, which subsidizes the export sale of certain
U.S. agricultural commodities, particularly those that must compete
with subsidized EEC farm products.
   The Bush administration wants to see the outcome of the current
Uruguay Round of talks under the General Agreement of Tariffs and
Trade before there is a new farm bill. The current law, passed in
1985, will expire next year.
   Some want the 1985 law extended a year or two so that any GATT
settlement can be considered as new legislation is drafted.
   ``I don't think we should write a farm bill based on what we
hope will happen in the GATT talks,'' Kleckner told a news
conference.
   The United States and the 12-nation EEC are hung up mainly on
long-term strategy and by what U.S. negotiators insist are
distortions caused by certain subsidies and restrictive policies.
   But EEC officials claim there has been progress in overhauling
the community's policies and that the United States should
compromise on some of its goals _ which at one time called for the
gradual elimination of trade-distorting farm subsidies and rules.
   Negotiations resume Wednesday in Geneva under GATT auspices.
Meanwhile, U.S. and EEC officials say they have agreed on
``progressive substantial reductions'' in agricultural subsidies, a
phrase Kleckner said he doesn't understand at this point.
   Asked about EEC claims of already making progress in scaling
back some of its agricultural programs, Kleckner said he couldn't
see those actions have amounted to much.
   ``In the total context of world trade, it really hasn't been
anything at all,'' he said. ``And it hasn't done anything
long-term.''
   Kleckner said the Europeans ``must make changes if we are to
move toward more rational world agricultural trade'' but that the
EEC ``refuses to entertain that notion.''
   Although Kleckner said he was not giving up yet on the Uruguay
Round of negotiations _ it has about two years still remaining _ he
said there is some danger of agricultural issues taking a back seat
to other trade matters.
   One of the reasons agriculture got attention when the current
round began in Punta del Este, Uruguay, on Sept. 20, 1986, was the
skyrocketing costs of government farm programs operated by many
countries, including the EEC and United States, Kleckner said. Food
costs also were rising in some countries.
   But farm program costs have come down, partly as a result of
higher commodity prices fueled by last year's North American
drought _ and lower support prices ordered by the United States
under the 1985 farm law.
   ``There's no question that last year's drought and the resulting
higher commodity prices around the world took the pressure out of
agricultural talks in this round,'' Kleckner said. ``But droughts
are temporary, they come and go. And so, the long-term problem is
still out there.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890404-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 1453EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Boeing-Wiring     04-04 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boeing-Wiring,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>36 More Incidents Of Crossed Wiring, Plumbing Found On Boeing Planes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crossed wiring or plumbing problems in fire
warning and extinguishing systems have been found on 94 Boeing
jetliners, the Federal Aviation Administration said today.
   The FAA said none of the problems directly affected the planes'
airworthiness, and all were corrected before the aircraft returned
to service.
   On Jan. 31, the FAA issued an airworthiness directive ordering
U.S. operators of Boeing jets to inspect for possible wiring or
plumbing problems in fire warning and suppression systems in
aircraft engines and cargo holds.
   The directive was prompted by the discovery of 32 such problems
in previous checks of Boeing planes.
   Only U.S. operators were required to make the checks, but many
foreign carriers followed suit voluntarily. The FAA said that of
the 63 problems found since the directive was issued, 36 were
reported since the last update on March 10. Six were found on U.S.
aircraft and 57 on foreign planes. Two problems were found on one
aircraft, FAA spokesman David Duff said.
   Duff said the names of the foreign carriers would not be
released because they reported voluntarily and ``because we feel
that would hinder the future flow of information.''
   However, Air Canada has said it found wiring problems on two of
its 767s, Australian Airlines reported wrong connections on fire
extinguisher bottles on four of its 737s and Japanese television
network NHK reported last month that problems were found on 19 747s
and 767s operated by Japan Air Lines and All Nippon Airways.
   At the time of the March 10 FAA update, Boeing Co. officials
said they had found an engineering solution to prevent wiring
problems and were awaiting FAA approval for it.
   Boeing Commercial Airplanes spokesman Craig Martin said today
the engineering changes were undergoing final review at Boeing
before submission to the FAA for its approval. He said the changes
involve the wiring and plumbing connectors, to ``physically
differentiate the connectors so it will be much more difficult to
connect them improperly.''
   The initial cross-connection problems were reported about a year
ago. Since then, Boeing ``has made a lot of progress looking at our
assembly procedures in the factory and the functional tests in the
factories,'' Martin said.
   Boeing also is examining its maintenance manuals to see if
instructions need to be clarified and whether there is a need to
test the extinguisher and warning system functions when maintenance
is carried out, he said.
   Martin said ``in the vast majority'' of the problems reported,
the fire suppression systems still worked. Both the cargo hold and
engine fire extinguisher systems have backups.
   The FAA said today that 19 of the 63 problems were found in the
engine fire warning and supression systems. Of those, 10 were found
on 737-300s and 737-400s, three on 767s, five on 757s and one on a
747.
   Forty-four problems were found in cargo compartment fire warning
and extinguishing systems, including 30 on 747s, one on a 757 and
13 on 767s.
   The 32 problems found before the Jan. 31 directive was issued
involved 12 U.S. and 20 foreign aircraft. Eight of those involved
engine systems, including four on 737-300s and 737-400s, three on
757s and one on a 747. The remaining 24 involved cargo hold
systems: seven on 757s and 17 on 767s.
   The FAA said that of the total 95 problems, 68 concerned wiring,
with 24 such problems in engines and 44 in cargo compartments. The
remaining 27 were fire extinguisher plumbing problems, with three
in engines and 24 in cargo compartments. All the plumbing problems
were on 767s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
