<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Corning     04-04 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Corning,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corning Reports $41.8 Million Quarterly Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORNING, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corning Glass Works reported Tuesday that
profits were $41.8 million for the first quarter of 1989, a
turnaround from a $46.8 million loss for the same period in 1988.
   Last year's first-quarter loss was a result of an accounting
change in the way the company figured its retirees' medical
benefits. The change resulted in a charge of $83.9 million against
earnings in the first quarter of 1988.
   Excluding accounting changes and special credits from both
years, Corning's 1989 first-quarter earnings would have risen 12
percent to $41.8 million, or 47 cents a share, compared with $36.8
million, or 41 cents a share.
   Sales for the first quarter, which ended March 26, of $534
million were up 18 from last year's first-quarter sales of $453
million, said Corning spokesman Stephen Albertalli.
   ``We continue to anticipate another record year,'' said Corning
Board Chairman James Houghton.
   Sales were up across the board, Albertalli said, and income from
jointly owned or partially owned companies rose 26 percent to a
record $17.7 million in the quarter.
</TEXT>
