<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 2149EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-IRSWoes     04-04 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IRS Woes,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Budget Could Squeeze IRS Further, Congressional Auditors Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Internal Revenue Service, already cutting
activities, is likely to face another squeeze next year because
President Bush's IRS budget includes no money to enforce a new
anti-drug law and the ``taxpayer bill of rights,'' government
auditors said Tuesday.
   ``We question whether the administration has properly reflected
what IRS will need to assure adequate funding of its ongoing
activities in fiscal year 1990,'' Jennie Stathis, an associate
director of the General Accounting Office, told a House Ways and
Means subcommittee.
   ``This budget is a real friend of the deadbeats,'' said Rep.
Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., a member of the oversight subcommittee. ``The
folks who don't meet their tax obligations are going to experience
a diminished threat'' with fewer IRS auditors and collectors,
Dorgan said.
   He noted that while the budget would require a reduction in the
number of tax auditors, it anticipates fewer auditors will produce
more revenue.
   There is nothing in the new budget to help the IRS deal with the
new drug law; the ``bill of rights,'' which is designed to help
taxpayers involved in disputes with the IRS, or a new tax to
finance catastrophic-illness protection for older Americans, said
Michael J. Murphy, acting commissioner of internal revenue.
   When the agency outlined its needs for the coming year, IRS
asked that its budget be increased by $1.3 billion, in part to
reflect increased responsibilities under the new laws. That
increase was scaled back by the White House Office of Management
and Budget, which, instead, approved a raise of $289 million, to
$5.5 billion.
   ``I feel the 1990 budget does step us forward in tax
administration'' despite some shortcomings, Murphy told the
subcommittee. But in the meantime, he added, ``We are dealing with
Treasury and look forward to working with OMB to resolve those
differences.''
   Ms. Stathis said that although the budget for the current year
is $360 million less than IRS needs, ``IRS is functioning so far
without any significant disruption to its basic operations. We are
uncertain, however, what lies in store for the rest of 1989.''
   In scaling back operations, the IRS vowed not to reduce
assistance to taxpayers or slow processing of returns. The agency
is reducing travel, training and purchases of computers and
supplies. A hiring freeze was imposed for most occupations.
   Robert M. Tobias, president of the National Treasury Employees
Union, which represents most IRS workers, said IRS enforcement has
suffered to the extent that in just six months the government has
lost $1 billion in revenues that it otherwise would have collected.
Another $1 billion will be lost by October unless the IRS is given
more money, he added.
   This year's squeeze was caused, GAO said, because of a mandated
4.1 percent increase in employee pay, higher postal rates and a
rise in premiums for workers' health insurance and pensions.
   GAO, an arm of Congress, said the IRS budget for next year is
suspect because it fails to include some costs, including the
anti-drug law and the taxpayer bill of rights, while anticipating
savings that are questionable. The latter was a reference to OMB
projections that the IRS can save a considerable amount of money by
having private contractors, rather than federal workers, do certain
jobs.
   The IRS, which has been under intense criticism because its
workers incorrectly answer taxpayers' telephoned questions about 30
percent of the time, was criticized by GAO for spending $57 million
this budget year trying to improve that record.
   ``Although the initiative is important ... IRS' decision to fund
it and other initiatives in 1989 added to the budgetary problems in
other parts of the agency,'' Ms. Stathis said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
