<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     04-04 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices headed higher in brisk trading
Tuesday, with crude rising above the $20-a-barrel level and
unleaded gasoline gaining more than a penny a gallon.
   Analysts attributed the rally to a variety of factors, including
expectations of a bullish weekly trade report on oil supplies due
to the Alaskan oil spill and bargaining hunting following Monday's
partial selloff.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the May contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, settled 47
cents higher Tuesday at $20.42 a barrel. The contract had lost 24
cents on Monday.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange Tuesday,
the May contract for unleaded gasoline jumped 1.61 cents to close
at 69.46 cents a gallon, after gaining 0.88 cent Monday.
   May wholesale home heating oil, which lost 0.62 cent at the
start of the week, settled at 53.64 cents, up 0.89 cent.
   Andrew Lebow, an energy analyst with E.D.F. Man International
Futures Inc., said traders were anticipating a dropoff in oil
supplies when the American Petroleum Institute releases its latest
weekly report.
   ``Most traders expect sharp draw-downs in crude inventory due to
the Alaskan situation,'' he said.
   Oil prices have risen sharply since a massive oil spill by an
Exxon Corp. tanker at the Valdez, Alaska, port. The Alaskan
pipeline there carries nearly one-quarter of the United States'
domestic supply of crude oil.
   Adding support to the market Tuesday, Lebow said, were reports
that the U.S. Coast Guard would continue to restrict tanker
activity at Valdez.
</TEXT>
