<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     04-04 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls While Gold Prices are Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar continued to decline Tuesday amid
more signs that the major industrial nations want to bring the U.S.
currency lower.
   Meanwhile, gold prices were narrowly mixed. Republic National
Bank of New York reported a bid of $385.90 for a troy ounce of gold
as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from $385.80 late Monday.
   The dollar fell largely because of central bank intervention,
which has squelched the currency's upward move for the time being,
said Dan Holland, a vice president at Discount Corp.
   The central banks, in response to requests from the big
industrial countries, sold dollars over several sessions last week
and again Monday and Tuesday to bring the dollar down.
   European dealers said the dollar fell Tuesday in response to
comments by French Economic Minister Pierre Beregovoy concerning
the Group of Seven's agreement that the dollar should not rise or
excessively decline.
   Officials from the seven countries _ the United States, Britain,
France, West Germany, Japan, Italy and Canada _ discussed the
foreign exchange markets during a meeting last weekend in
Washington.
   Traders in the United States were also following foreign
interest rate movements closely. Overseas interest rate hikes are
bearish for the dollar because they make other currencies more
attractive.
   Holland said the dollar might stabilize if Japan and West
Germany do not raise their interest rates.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7043 late Tuesday, more
expensive for buyers than Monday's late $1.6855. In later New York
trading, the pound rose to $1.7085 from $1.6912 late Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday's
prices, included: 1.86835 West German marks, down from 1.87625;
1.63075 Swiss francs, down from 1.64125; 6.3060 French francs, down
from 6.3300; 1,370.375 Italian lire, down from 1,376.625; and
1.18655 Canadian dollars, down from 1.18755.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with Monday's
late rates, included: 1.8670 West German marks, down from 1.8835;
1.6358 Swiss francs, down from 1.6488; 6.3100 French francs, down
from 6.3535; 2.1080 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1230; 1,372.75
Italian lire, down from 1,381.50; 1.1875 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1896.
   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar dropped to 131.05 Japanese yen from
132.26. In London late Tuesday the dollar traded lower at 130.95
yen, and in New York, it fell to 130.85 yen from 131.775 late
Monday.
   Gold dipped to $386.10 a troy ounce on the Commodity Exchange in
New York from late Monday's $386.20.
   Bullion was up more than $1 overseas. Gold traded late in
London, the major market, at a bid $386.75 a troy ounce, up from
$385.30 late Monday, while the Zurich late bid price was $386.50,
up from $385.25.
   Traders said that as anxiety about inflation was easing, the
dollar's weakness would not help gold much.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $387.25 bid, up from
$385.75.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $5.84 a troy ounce, up
from $5.80.
   On the Commodity Exchange, silver rose to $5.816 a troy ounce
from $5.788 late Monday.
</TEXT>
