<FIRST>r f AM-Pepperell-Farley     04-04 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pepperell-Farley,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farley Extends Tender Offer For West Point-Pepperell</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST POINT, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farley Inc. said Tuesday it hoped to
complete its $1.8 billion acquisition of West Point-Pepperell Inc.
later this week after extending its tender offer for another 21
hours.
   Pepperell shareholders had until 9 p.m. Tuesday to redeem their
stock at Farley's offer of $58 a share. The offer previously was
scheduled to expire at midnight Monday.
   Meanwhile, Farley officials were hoping their acquisition of the
Georgia textile giant would be completed by Thursday. That deadline
has twice been extended as Farley needed extra time to make
arrangements to complete the deal.
   ``It's a very big transaction,'' a Farley spokesman, who asked
not to be identified, said Tuesday. ``When you buy a car, it takes
some time. When you buy a house, it takes some time. When you buy a
West Point-Pepperell, it takes some time.''
   Josie Esquivel, an analyst for Shearson Lehman Hutton, said some
junk bond investors are concerned that Farley, the maker of Fruit
of the Loom underwear, was paying too much for Pepperell.
   But Wall Street investors indicated confidence that Farley will
complete the takeover. The textile company's stock rose 12{ cents
to $57.87{ per share in trading Tuesday on the New York Stock
Exchange.
   Farley officials would not comment on speculation Monday that it
was considering selling Fruit of the Loom, but the company has said
it is not having difficulty raising $1.8 billion for the deal.
   Farley has proposed financing the buyout with bank debt and junk
bonds.
   Pepperell, which manufactures Martex and Lady Pepperell sheet
and towels, Arrow shirts and Gold Toe socks, is the nation's
largest publicly held textile and apparel maker. It has about 29.8
million shares outstanding, including nearly 2.9 million shares
already owned by Farley.
</TEXT>
