<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     04-04 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coffee Futures Soar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIO FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices for coffee surged higher Tuesday on the lack of
bad news from the International Coffee Organization meetings in
London this week.
   On other futures markets, corn and soybeans were higher while
wheat prices fell, frozen pork bellies were off sharply while
livestock was mixed, and most energy products were higher.
   The volatile May coffee contract rose more than 320 points
during the session to over $1.31 a pound _ its highest level since
March 20 _ on the Coffee, Sugar and Cocoa Exchange in New York.
   ``There is now a perception of a compromise on quotas to replace
the accord that expires Sept. 30. The sentiment for months was that
there would be no ageement,'' said analyst Sandra Kaul of Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Also supporting prices were continued good demand,
behind-schedule shipments and forecasts for a reduced Brazilan
coffee harvest, she said.
   Coffee settled .50 cent to 3.25 cents higher, with the contract
for delivery in May at $1.3148 a pound.
   Futures prices for corn and soybeans were higher but wheat
prices were down at the close Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   The market's direction has been generally downward during past
several sessions.
   ``People walked in this morning and said it had been oversold,
and there was some European trade in the soymeal market,'' said
assistant vice president Cathy Leow of Thompson McKinnon Securities
Inc.
   Wheat was being sold largely because of profit-taking after
Monday's closing rally and the lack of confirmation of rumors
concerning a big sale to China, research director Jerry Gidel of
LIT America Inc. said.
   Wheat settled 1 cents to 7\ cents lower, with the contract for
delivery in May at $4.01\ a bushel; corn was 1} cents to 3 cents
higher, with May at $2.62 a bushel; oats were \ cent to 2 cents
higher, with May at $1.88 a bushel; and soybeans were 2} cents to 6
cents higher, with May at $7.14} a bushel.
   Futures prices for frozen pork bellies were off sharply while
livestock prices were mixed on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Pork bellies were depressed by record high storage supplies and
high retail prices, said Tom O'Hare of Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp;
Co.
   Supply concerns also kept prices uncertain for cattle and live
hogs, he said.
   Cattle settled .43 cent lower to .15 cent higher, with the
contract for delivery in April at 77.55 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were unchanged to .30 cent lower, with April at 79.50 a
pound; live hogs were .50 cent lower to .28 cent higher, with April
at 40.65 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .50 cent to 2
cents lower, with May at 34.77 a pound.
   Most energy prices rose on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Analysts attributed the rally to several factors, including
expectations of a bullish weekly trade report on tight oil supplies
due to the Alaskan oil spill and bargain-hunting following Monday's
partial selloff.
   Crude oil settled 22 cents to 47 cents higher, with the contract
for delivery in May at $20.42 a barrel; heating oil was .40 cent to
.89 cent higher, with May at 53.64 cents a gallon; and unleaded
gasoline was .33 cent lower to 1.61 cents higher, with May at 69.46
cents a gallon.
   Precious metals prices were generally steady on the Commodity
Exchange in New York.
   The market has become uncertain about the movement of the U.S.
dollar and the outcome of inflationary pressures, said John Jonat
of Deak International Inc.
   Gold settled unchanged to 20 cents lower, with the contract for
delivery in April at $386.10 a troy ounce; and silver was 2.2 cents
to 2.8 cents higher, with April at $5.81.6 a troy ounce.
