<FIRST>r f AM-BrokerHarassed     04-04 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Broker Harassed,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wealthy Art Collector Pleads Guilty to Harassing Her Broker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A socialite art collector who tormented her
stockbroker by telephoning him 1,208 times in one week has pleaded
guilty to aggravated harassment, been fined and ordered not to
contact the man for three years.
   Ethel Scull, 67, claimed she lost thousands of dollars in the
October 1987 stock market crash by following tips of broker Charles
Lewis, a Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. vice president. But
prosecutors said Lewis helped Mrs. Scull make $300,000 months
before the crash by putting her money into government bonds. They
said Mrs. Scull made the calls during a week in January 1988,
including one day when she telephoned him 485 times.
   She was arrested on harassment charges Feb. 1 and failed to keep
a court date Feb. 28. A warrant was issued for her arrest.
   After she surrendered and pleaded guilty Monday to aggravated
assault charges, Manhattan Criminal Court Judge Renee White fined
her $1,000 plus $60 in court costs and ordered her not to call,
write or go near Lewis for three years.
   Mrs. Scull, formerly married to taxi entrepreneur Robert Scull,
was awarded art works worth millions of dollars in her divorce
settlement in 1974. Her collection included pieces by Jasper Johns
and Andy Warhol.
</TEXT>
