<HEAD>Record 1,317 Wineries In U.S.; Kansas Newest Wine State</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS number of new wineries in other states; CORRECTS source
errors on totals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kansas, for the first time, is included in
the country's chief directory of wineries. A record 1,317 wineries
are in the new edition.
   The latest entry makes 44 states that now produce wine
commercially out of bonded premises, according to the 70-year-old
trade publication, Wines &amp; Vines.
   Kansas enters the list with Fields of Fair of Manhattan, Kan.,
recorded with the government late last year.
   The directory lists 669 wineries in California, which produces
90 percent of U.S. wine. The other leading wine-producing states
are New York, 92 wineries; Washington, 75; Oregon, 73; Ohio, 50;
Pennsylvania, 45; Virginia, 41; Missouri, 30; Texas 26; New Mexico,
18, and Michigan and New Jersey, 17 each.
   Of the 115 wineries listed for the first time this year,
California has 36; Washington 12; Ohio 11; Oregon and Virginia, 10
each; New York, nine; Pennsylvania and Texas, seven each; New
Mexico, three; New Jersey and Missouri, two; Rhode Island, Florida,
Arizona, Kansas, Minnesota and Maryland, one each.
