<DOCNO> AP890404-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 2139EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-McCaw-BritishTelecom     04-04 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-McCaw-British Telecom,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC To Permit British Telecom's Purchase Of McCaw Shares</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission on
Tuesday said it would not stand in the way of British
Telecommunications Inc.'s $1.5 billion investment in McCaw Cellular
Communications Inc., the nation's biggest cellular phone company.
   The FCC said the purchase of a 22.4 percent share of McCaw did
not involve a transfer of control of McCaw to British Telecom USA
and it also was in line with federal restrictions on foreign
involvement in U.S. broadcasting or common carrier companies.
   Gerald Brock, chief of the FCC's common carrier bureau, said the
1934 Communications Act limits foreign stakes in U.S.
communications companies to either 20 percent or 25 percent,
depending on whether the U.S. concern has direct or indirect
control of broadcast licenses.
   He said McCaw does not hold licenses directly, but rather
controls them through wholly owned subsidiaries. Thus he said the
25 percent limit applies.
   British Telecom will gain control of four of the 19 seats on
McCaw's board and acquire 22.4 percent of its stock.
   The deal is the largest yet for the fledgling cellular industry,
according to the Cellular Telecommunications Industry Association.
   The CTIA said McCaw was cash-strapped and had reported net
losses of $92.2 million in the quarter ended Dec. 31, 1988.
   The McCaw family and management holds a 41 percent equity in the
company, and board chairman Craig McCaw will maintain majority
control of electing directors, Brock said.
   McCaw owns subsidiaries which in turn hold interests in
cellular, paging and other areas of radio communications.
   British Telecom USA is the wholly owned subsidiary of British
Telecom, a publicly held corporation that is 49 percent owned by
the British government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
