<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf to CORRECT advances and declines. UPDATES with
closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices pulled back in moderate trading
Tuesday, relinguishing some of the market's recent gains.
   The market meandered in a narrow range in early trading before
turning lower in the afternoon, partly weighed down by weakness in
technology stocks.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 6.60 to 2,298.20.
   Declining issues outnumbered advancing ones by about 4 to 3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
838 down, 643 up and 491 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 160.68 million
shares, down from 164.66 million in the previous session.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 187.21 million shares.
   A decline in the dollar against other foreign currencies
depressed stocks.
   Hugh Johnson, senior vice president at First Albany Corp., said
stocks and bonds had benefited from the dollar's recent strength on
the theory that a higher dollar would bolster the confidence of
foreign investors and attract capital from overseas into U.S.
financial markets.
   Another negative influence on stocks was the announcement by
several companies involved in takeovers that they were taking
defensive measures.
   ``The market seems to be in somewhat of a holding pattern,''
said Jack Barbanel, a senior vice president at Gruntal &amp; Co. Inc.,
adding that Wall Street may remain subdued this week, awaiting
Friday's release of U.S. employment statistics.
   The Labor Department's employment report for March will furnish
a fresh indication of how much the economy is responding to the
Federal Reserve's efforts to slow growth and diffuse inflationary
pressures.
   Within the technology group, Tandem Computers said its earnings
for the quarter ended March 31 would fall short of expectations.
The estimate, which helped push Tandem's stock to 14~, off 2[ in
active trading, followed disappointing forecasts from other
computer manufacturers, including IBM, Digital and Unisys.
   Elsewhere in the technology sector, IBM was down 1] to 107[ and
Digital lost 1| to 96\.
   Smithkline Beckman led the active list for much of the session
and finished up \ at 65~. The stock was a strong performer Monday
also amid speculation that a rival bid may emerge for the drug
company following its disclosure that it is planning to merge some
of its major operations with Britain's Beecham.
   Lockheed shares fell 2 to 47} on news the company estimated a 40
percent drop in its first-quarter net income and foresees an
earnings decline in 1989.
   The company said it would issue 10.5 million new shares and buy
back the same number of shares in the creation of a $500 million
employee stock ownership plan. An investor group led by Harold
Simmons, which Monday said it had acquired a 5.3 percent stake in
Lockheed, said Lockheed's reorganization plans are discouraging the
group from increasing its stake for the time being.
   Tribune Co. skidded 3{ to 44{. The company has been a target a
takeover talk recently and Tuesday said it was selling $350 million
of convertible preferred stock to its ESOP and would use the
proceeds to repurchase up to 8 million common shares.
   NWA Inc. slid | to 83}. The parent of Northwest Airlines has
received a $90-a-share bid from investor Marvin Davis.
   Burlington Resources, which has been the subject of takeover
speculation, gained 1[ to 50[.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $6.483 billion, or 0.22
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
slipped 0.48 to 165.95.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index dropped 1.15 to 340.14, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index was down 1.08 at 295.31.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market fell
0.47 to 407.18. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 329.19, off 0.28.
