<FIRST>r f AM-Whirlpool     04-04 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Whirlpool,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whirlpool President Quits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BENTON HARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Albert E. Suter resigned Tuesday as
Whirlpool Corp.'s president and chief operating officer, a post he
held for seven months, to pursue other opportunities, the appliance
maker said.
   David R. Whitwam, the chairman and chief executive, said William
D. Marohn, 49, president of the company's Kenmore Appliance Group,
was named an executive vice president and given Suter's
responsibilities for North American appliance operations.
   ``As much as I value my relationship and experience with
Whirlpool, I now fully realize my career interests are to pursue
CEO or entrepreneurial opportunities,'' Suter said in a news
release from Whirlpool.
   A CEO post at Whirlpool would be unlikely, Suter said when
reached in Chicago, where he lives. ``I had never anticipated the
CEO post opening up,'' the 53-year-old Suter said. ``Mr. Whitwam
(at 47) is younger than I am.''
   He declined to comment on the brevity of his stay at Whirlpool.
``Dave Whitwam and I complemented each other very well,'' he said.
   Suter was previously vice chairman of Emerson Electric Co., a
major supplier of appliance components to Whirlpool and other
companies.
   He was named Whirlpool's president and chief operating officer
in September, assuming the title of president from Whitwam, who is
expected to seek the board's approval to regain the title of
president, Whirlpool spokeswoman Carol Sizer said.
   Marohn has been president of the Kenmore Appliance Group since
February 1988.
   Whirlpool reported earnings of $94.1 million on sales of $4.31
billion in 1988. It became the world's largest appliance concern
with a January agreement to purchase a majority of the appliance
division of NV Philips of the Netherlands.
</TEXT>
