<DOCNO> AP890404-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 2036EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern 3rdLd-Writethru   04-04 0864</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0893</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS new grafs 20-21 to UPDATE with Texas Air not paying
first-quarter dividends; picks up 21st graf pvs bg'ng, The sale ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal judge overseeing the Eastern
Airlines bankruptcy case ordered the U.S. trustee in the case late
Tuesday to show cause why he has postponed the appointment of a
bankruptcy examiner.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton Lifland ordered U.S. trustee Harold
Jones to explain at a hearing Wednesday why Jones postponed the
naming of an examiner Tuesday at the request of Eastern and a
committee representing its unsecured creditors.
   The order was highly unusual for a bankruptcy case, said Nancy
Lazar, Lifland's law clerk.
   Lifland, who is overseeing Eastern's Chapter 11 reorganization,
recently ordered appointment of an examiner with unusually broad
powers, including a mandate to mediate the bitter labor dispute at
the carrier in an effort to get it flying again.
   Jones, who is responsible for administration of the Eastern
bankruptcy case, declined to say in a telephone interview earlier
Tuesday why the company and creditors had asked for a deferral of
the examiner appointment.
   However, union sources speculated that Eastern and the committee
wished to postpone the appointment until U.S. District Judge Edward
B. Davis in Miami rules on Eastern's request that he declare a
walkout by its pilots an illegal strike and order them back to
work. Davis' decision is expected sometime this week.
   The pilots' walkout in support of a Machinists strike that began
March 4 has been crucial to the success of the strike and has
forced the airline to sharply curtail its flight schedules.
Eastern's flight attendants union also is honoring the strike.
   Jones had said the naming of an examiner to be appointed by
Lifland could be made Wednesday or later. He was unavailable for
comment late Tuesday after the judge issued his order.
   Miami-based Eastern filed for bankruptcy protection in the New
York court on March 9 due to a cash crisis created by the strike.
   Jones said ``substantial progress'' was made at a meeting
Tuesday between Eastern and the 15-member unsecured creditors
committee, which also includes representatives of Eastern's pilots
and Machinists unions and its non-union workers, but he declined to
elaborate.
   The creditors committee had requested potential buyers for
Eastern, including hotel executive Jay Pritzker and a group led by
ex-baseball commissioner Peter Ueberroth, to present their
proposals at its Tuesday meeting.
   Little was immediately known of developments at the closed-door
creditors committee meeting at a Manhattan law firm. Lifland had
asked members of the committee not to discuss developments at the
meeting with the news media, according to people familiar with the
proceedings who asked not to be identified.
   The Ueberroth group made a $464 million bid to acquire Eastern
but withdrew it last week after the airline's parent Texas Air
Corp. indicated it had received a higher offer.
   The group planned a revised, lower offer, that reflecting
developer Donald Trump's new agreement to buy Eastern's prized
Northeast shuttle for $365 million, sources close to Ueberroth said.
   Pritzker, former head of Braniff Airlines has offered around
$500 million for the whole airline, according to sources close to
the situation.
   America West Airlines, which has expressed is interested in
buying Boeing 757s and the shuttle's landing slots in New York and
Washington from Eastern, said it still considers itself a potential
buyer.
   The regional airline is not in discussions with Eastern but it
is watching developments closely, said Daphne Dicino, a spokeswoman
for Phoenix-based America West who was visiting New York. She said
America West believes it still could bid for the shuttle because
the sale to Trump hasn't yet been approved by the bankruptcy court.
   Trump said Friday he expected the deal to be closed within 60
days.
   The creditors panel has the right to review any reorganization
plan proposed by Eastern and can propose its own plan to the
bankruptcy judge.
   In a separate development, Houston-based Texas Air announced
that it would not pay dividends for the first quarter on its four
outstanding issues of preferred stock. The dividends would have
been payable on March 31, April 15 and April 30, depending on the
issue, the airline holding company said.
   Also Tuesday, Lifland approved Eastern's sale of three Boeing
727-100s to Federal Express Corp. for a total of about $10.8
million, Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said in Miami.
   The sale fulfills an accord signed last September in which
Eastern agreed to sell 10 of the planes to Federal Express. Matell
said the first seven were delivered between September and February.
   In Washington, Congressional Democrats pulled off the Senate
floor legislation that would require President Bush to appoint an
emergency board to recommend a solution to the walkout.
   The Democratic lawmakers attributed their reversal to a desire
to give potential buyers a chance to acquire Eastern and to allow
the bankruptcy court to find a way to end the walkout.
   Bush and congressional Republicans have opposed the measure,
saying the carrier's management and unions should work out their
dispute privately. Bush had threatened to veto the bill, which was
slated for Senate floor debate Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
