<DOCNO> AP890404-0265 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 2042EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Lockheed     04-04 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lockheed,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aerospace Company Says Restructuring Unrelated To Investor's Buy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CALABASAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lockheed Corp. said Tuesday a
reorganization that includes the creation of an employee stock plan
was unrelated to investor Harold Simmons' purchase of 5.3 percent
of the aerospace company's stock.
   The restructuring plan also includes the sale of Lockheed's
computer operations and acceleration of a previously announced
program to move aircraft manufacturing operations from Burbank and
sell about 225 acres of land there. That land includes the ``Skunk
Works,'' where the F-117 stealth fighter is made.
   The plan was approved at a board of directors meeting that was
scheduled before Simmons revealed Monday he had accumulated 5.3
percent of Lockheed's 59.5 million shares, said company spokesman
Robert Slayman.
   Lockheed makes the Trident II missile, the C-5B military
transport plane and works on NASA's space station project and the
``Star Wars'' missile defense, in addition to other military and
aerospace projects.
   ``There is no denying there are defensive characteristics to
these things, but that is not the primary purpose,'' Slayman said
of the employee-stock plan, or ESOP, and the other moves. ``The
primary purpose is to enhance our competitiveness. This gives
(employees) a bigger stake in the success of our company.''
   Simmons _ who also said he planned substantial investments in
Chrysler Corp., Paccar Inc. and Phelps Dodge Corp. _ said in a
letter to Lockheed management last Friday that he didn't intend to
try to buy the company.
   ``We have no plans, or desire, to disrupt management. We expect
to be a constructive, long-term shareholder,'' the Dallas investor
said in the letter, which he released to the press Monday.
   The ESOP would buy 10.5 million newly issued shares of Lockheed
stock for $500 million, and the company would offset the dilution
of its stock by buying an equal number of shares held by the
public. Establishment of the ESOP would result in employee
ownership of 17 percent of Lockheed common stock, the company said.
   Such plans are sometimes used to defend against hostile
takeovers because it places stock in friendly hands. For instance,
an ESOP was instrumental in Polaroid Corp.'s successful defense
against a buyout by California investor Roy E. Disney.
   Lockheed adopted a ``poison pill'' takeover defense in December
after Simmons disclosed he intended to buy up to $15 million worth
of the company's stock. That plan would entitle current
stockholders to buy additional, newly issued stock at a discount in
the event of a hostile takeover attempt, thus making a buyout more
expensive.
   On Monday, Simmons told the Wall Street Journal he intended to
invest at least $15 million each in shares of Chrysler, Phelps
Dodge and Paccar, a Bellevue, Wash., truck maker.
   Lockheed's restructuring plan includes:
   _The speedup of the previously announced move of Lockheed
Aeronautical Systems Co. from factories next to Burbank Airport to
Palmdale and Rye Canyon, Calif., and Marietta, Ga. The moves, part
of a consolidation effort, are to be finished in 1991 instead of
1992 or 1993, as executives previously stated.
   The move will free 225 acres in Burbank for sale, the company
said, revealing for the first time the acreage.
   _The four companies or divisions that make up Lockheed's
information systems group will be sold. The group, with 3,900
employees, accounted for $589 million of the company's $10.6
billion in 1988 sales. To be sold are CalComp of Anaheim, CADAM
Inc. of Burbank, Metier Inc. of Houston and DataPlan of Los Gatos.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
