<DOCNO> AP890404-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 2354EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-TribuneStock     04-04 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tribune Stock,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tribune Approves Stock Repurchase Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tribune Co. directors decided Tuesday to buy up
to 8 million shares of the company's stock, but the media
conglomerate would not say the move was designed to thwart a
potential takeover.
   The stock repurchase plan was authorized by the board of
directors one day after reports of the Robert M. Bass Group of Fort
Worth, Texas, acquiring 2 percent to 3 percent of Tribune Co. stock.
   Spokesmen for the Bass Group and Tribune Co. declined comment.
Tribune Co. would not say whether the plan was designed to stop a
possible takeover by Bass.
   Tribune Co. said it would issue $350 million worth of a new
series of convertible preferred stock to its employee stock
ownership plan. Money from the sale will be used to buy up to 8
million common shares on the open market.
   The company said it will make a loan to the employee stock plan
to finance the purchase of the convertible stock.
   ``Expansion of the (employee stock plan) increases ownership by
our employees and recognizes their significant economic stake in
Tribune Co.'s continued success,'' said Stanton R. Cook, chairman
and chief executive officer.
   More than two years ago the company said it would repurchase 10
million shares. It has acquired 8.6 million of them, it said.
   Tribune Co. holdings include the Chicago Tribune and the Daily
News of New York, as well as the Chicago Cubs baseball club, six TV
stations and a forest products unit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
